The Synthetic Causal Framework

An LLM-based Solution to the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference

Emil N. Meyer-Hansen1

Version: 2025-03-18-18-49

1 Abstract

When researchers want to test theories about causal relationships, an exogenous manipulation of the theorized cause, as commonly implemented in Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs), is often considered the scientific golden standard for making reliable causal inferences (Meldrum 2000). However, since RCTs require the cause to be manipulable, they cannot be implemented by researchers with non-manipulable theorized causes, leaving them with possibly endogenous theorized causes that may be subject to confounding, making causal inference unreliable (cf. Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49; Wooldridge 2019: 54-56). While causal frameworks and methods have been devised to provide reliable causal inference (e.g., Abadie et al. 2010; Dunning 2008; Rosenbaum and Rubin 1983), these generally rely on strict assumptions that are dubious, untestable, and unlike RCTs, are not ensured by design (cf. Rohrer 2018; Samii 2016; Wan et al. 2024). If these assumptions are violated, results are put at risk of confounding and bias (McElreath 2019; Pearl 2000; Rohrer 2018; Samii 2016; Stuart 2010; Wan et al. 2024), reducing the reliability of causal inferences derived from such research. A more reliable alternative to these frameworks would arguably remedy the inability to manipulate the theorized cause, enabling researchers to exploit the strengths of the exogenous manipulation underlying the logic of RCTs, which, ceteris paribus, ensures reliable causal inference by design (cf. Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49; Wooldridge 2019: 54-56). Since many instances of non-manipulable theorized causes are found in human subjects due to ethical and/or practical concerns (e.g., Buunk and van Vugt 2013: 17), the development of an alternative causal framework would prove especially useful for the social and behavioral sciences (see Wright 2015). This could exploit the fact that many social studies measure human behavior through expressions of natural language, creating a potential solution to make non-manipulable theorized cause manipulable with the use of Large Language Models (LLMs, cf. Shanahan 2024), which are specifically trained to mimic such expressions. This prospect is investigated in this paper, which introduces the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF), a novel solution for making non-manipulable theorized causes manipulable. Formalized as an extension of the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (cf. Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005), the SCF offers a synthetic solution to the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference (cf. Holland 1986), where simulated data and real-world data are synthesized using LLMs to produce synthetic units. To make the behavior of these units realistic and generalizable to human populations of interest, each unit has a unique life-history (cf. Bertaux 1981) generated by the LLM-model based on demographic characteristics, relevant for the topic being studied and representative of the population of interest. What would generally be considered a non-manipulable theorized cause could in such a framework then be manipulated among these LLM-driven synthetic units, with multiple simultaneous and independent manipulations being possible for each unit. By simultaneously and independently measuring the counterfactual outcome for each manipulation condition using parallel processing (cf. Ozdoganlar and Endres 2021[1999]), a procedure introduced here as parallel worlds-estimation, unbiased estimates of causal effects can then be derived using standard statistical models (cf. Westreich et al. 2015). By making a non-manipulable theorized cause manipulable, the SCF thus allows eliminating most forms of confounding by design (cf. Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49; Wooldridge 2019: 54-56), providing the framework with an a priori expectedly high internal validity (cf. Stock and Watson 2019: 478-481). A relevant concern is the external validity (cf. Stock and Watson 2019: 481; Gelman et al. 2021: 354-355) of the framework, that is, the generalizability of its results to human populations. To test its generalizability, and provide a proof-of-concept, the SCF is implemented in a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT), a similarly novel SCF-based extension of an RCT, in an effort to replicate the established human-based relationship between deservingness and welfare support (cf. Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019) among synthetic units. Using the relatively cost-efficient and high-performing GPT-4o-mini LLM by OpenAI (2024a), a nationally representative sample of 1,009 synthetic respondents, and Bayesian inference (cf. Brkner 2017, 2018), including Frequentist inference for robustness (cf. Bates et al. 2015), it is demonstrated that causal results derived from the SCF closely replicate results derived from human respondents. By merit of its high internal validity, and evidence in favor of a high external validity, this paper makes the tentative conclusion that, ceteris paribus, the Synthetic Causal Framework enables social and behavioral science researchers to draw valid and reliable causal inference when the theorized cause is non-manipulable. Practical implications of the SCF are discussed, including its substantially reduced costs compared to human studies, as well as its assumptions, limitations, future areas of application, and the need for further validations of the generalizability of SCF-based results to human populations.

Keywords: Synthetic Causal Framework, SCF, Synthetically Controlled Trial, SCT, Parallel-worlds estimation, Synthetic units, Simulated units, Causal inference, Causal framework, Causal methodology, Causal design, Experimental design, Potential Outcomes Framework, Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference, Natural Language Processing, NLP, Large Language Model, LLM, Generative Pretrained Transformer, GPT, Artifical intelligence, AI, Quantitative social science, Political methodology, Political science, Deservingness heuristic, Welfare support, Welfare attitudes, Evolutionary psychology, Conceptual replication

2 Introduction

In their effort to understand the physical world, researchers often produce theories about causal relationships between phenomena, that is, whether one phenomenon causes another phenomenon (Aronson et al. 2018: 54-61; Angrist and Pischke 2015; Angrist and Pischke 2009; Samii 2016; Sniderman and Grob 1996; Toshkov 2016: 35-37, 145-165). Consistent with various conceptualizations of the scientific method (Eysenck and Keane 2020: 667; Aronson et al. 2018: 45-46; Toshkov 2016: 4-6, 37-41; Farrell 2014: 10-23; Lakatos 1970; Nola and Sankey 2007; Popper 2002[1959]), proposed causal theories should be sought falsified by deriving testable hypotheses about the claims made by the theory. While no theory can ever be proven correct (Lakatos 1970; Miller 1974; Popper 2002[1959]; see also Dellsn 2024)2, a causal theory whose hypotheses pass repeated attempts at falsification can, for instrumental purposes, be scientifically treated as tentatively correct and added to the cumulative pile of human knowledge. That is, at least until the theory is eventually falsified and/or superseded by a better theory (Dellsn 2024; Lakatos 1970; Miller 1974; Popper 2002[1959]). While this view of the scientific method can be considered ideal, if not utopic (Feyerabend 1993; Kuhn 1970; Nosek et al. 2012; Nosek and Bar-Anan 2012; Uhlmann et al. 2019), in part due to its flawed implementations across disciplines (Anderson 2020: 11; Bishop 2006; Chopra et al. 2023; Christensen et al. 2019; Eysenck and Keane 2020: 34-36; Gigerenzer 2004; Lenz and Sahn 2021; Open Science Collaboration 2015; Ritchie 2021; Simmons et al. 2011), it helps emphasize that tests of causality need to be reliable, so that true hypotheses are not wrongly rejected and that false hypotheses do not wrongly fail to be rejected (Lakatos 1970; Neyman and Pearson 1933).

With causal inference involving the estimation of a theorized effect between a potential cause and outcome in a theoretically-outlined context (Angrist and Pischke 2015; Angrist and Pischke 2009; Samii 2016), for insights to be scientifically reliable, it is critical that the estimated effect is valid and can be generalized to the intended context. In line with the aforementioned views on the scientific method, this is because in the commonly applied Null-Hypothesis Significance Testing framework (NHST, for criticisms, see, e.g., Clayton 2021; Cohen 1994; Gigerenzer 2004, 2018), a nil hypothesis of no effect (Cohen 1994: 999-1000) in that particular context is either rejected or fails to be rejected based on this estimate.3 Accordingly, the estimate must not reflect a falsely identified causal relationship, which would constitute a false positive result (i.e., a Type I error, Neyman and Pearson 1933), nor must the result reflect a falsely unidentified causal relationship, and thus be a false negative (i.e., a Type II error, Neyman and Pearson 1933). Reliability is further threatened if the estimate fails to reflect the true direction (i.e., a Type S error, Gelman et al. 2021: 59; Gelman and Carlin 2014) or magnitude (i.e., a Type M error, Gelman et al. 2021: 59; Gelman and Carlin 2014) of the effect in the theoretically-outlined context.

These errors of estimation and generalization can occur due to confounding (Fisher 1935; Greenland et al. 1999; VanderWeele and Shpitser 2013), which occurs if a third phenomenon can impact both the theorized cause and outcome, or if the estimate is derived from a sample unrepresentative of the theoretically-outlined context (Aronow and Samii 2016; Deaton and Cartwright 2018; Samii 2016). These can be serious errors that produce invalid and unreliable scientific insights (Aronow and Samii 2016; Gelman and Carlin 2014; Samii 2016). These errors are to preferably be eliminated by design (cf. Rohrer 2018: 34; Stuart 2010: 3; Samii 2016), where (1) the theorized cause is manipulated in an exogenous manner (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49), with the exogeneity of the manipulation ensuring that the result cannot be confounded, since the theorized cause cannot be affected by them; and (2) the units from which the causal estimate is derived are representative of the context to which the theory supposedly applies (Stock and Watson 2019: 108; Thompson 2012). While a representative sample can generally be achieved with random sampling (Stock and Watson 2019: 108; Thompson 2012), an exogenous manipulation of the theorized cause is most often justified in a Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT, Coover and Angell 1907; Peirce and Jastrow 1885; Woodworth and Thorndike 1901). This is an experimental design, where researchers employ a random assignment mechanism (RAM) to manipulate the theorized cause, its randomness serving to ensure that the manipulation occurs exogenously of the influence of confounders (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49; Wooldridge 2019: 54-56). With the relatively high internal validity of results provided by an exogenous manipulation (Stock and Watson 2019: 478-481), coupled with a relatively high external validity provided by representative units (Stock and Watson 2019: 481; Gelman et al. 2021: 354-355), RCTs are generally considered the golden standard for making reliable causal inference (Meldrum 2000; Samii 2016; though for general criticisms see, e.g., Deaton and Cartwright 2018). A limitation of RCTs, however, is that randomization requires the theorized cause to be manipulable by the RAM. This means that for any instance where the theorized cause is non-manipulable in this way (e.g., Buunk and van Vugt 2013: 17), researchers cannot employ the design of RCTs to achieve reliable causal inference, leaving their results open to confounding and wrong scientific conclusions.

Methodologists recognize that reliable causal inference is paramount to the scientific endeavour (Aronson et al. 2018: 54-61; Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Samii 2016; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49), and for instances with non-manipulable theorized causes, they have formalized frameworks to help researchers identify premises for achieving reliable causal inference (e.g., Imbens and Rubin 2015; Pearl 1993, 1995), as well as methods whose reliability depend on those frameworks (Abadie et al. 2010, 2015; Abadie and LHour 2021; e.g., Angrist et al. 1996; Dunning 2008). However, these methods generally require making strict assumptions that are a priori dubious, untestable, and not ensured by design (e.g., Rohrer 2018; Samii 2016; Stuart 2010). For example, the methodology of matching requires making the dubious and untestable assumption of no unobserved confounders to achieve reliable causal inference (Ho et al. 2007: 206), that if violated makes causal inference unreliable by re-introducing the issues of confounding (e.g., Wan et al. 2024; see also Pearl 2000). Since researchers cannot assume a position of agnosticism regarding the viability of their assumptions due to the burden-of-proof being upon the researchers making a causal claim (cf. Russo 2019), concerns are justified regarding the ability of such methods in providing reliable causal inference. The current state of causal inference is thus one where researchers with non-manipulable theorized causes often have to rely on methods, whose ability to provide reliable causal inference is justifiably dubious.

The current shortcomings, however, may prove solvable given the accelerating advancements in Natural Language Processing (NLP, Pillai and Tedesco 2023). Here, Large Language Models (LLMs, Shanahan 2024) are proving increasingly capable of simulating human behavior as expressed through text. Such models, which include the popular ChatGPT by OpenAI (2022), have demonstrated human-comparable cognitive skills in the fields of logic, mathematics, and communication (OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; Yenduri et al. 2024). This potential has been recognized by researchers across disciplines (e.g., Bail 2024), and they have, for example, already seen success in simulating patients that help train medical doctors (Holderried et al. 2024; Pang et al. 2024). A theoretical foundation for simulating human behavior with LLMs is based on these models having been trained on huge datasets containing text-based expressions of real-life human behavior (OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; 2022; Ornstein et al. 2024), allowing them to expectedly infer how humans generally respond to different inputs. Researchers recognize that natural language is a rich media for capturing psychological and social behavior (Tadesse et al. 2018), and in their text-based format have been demonstrated to predict behavioral aspects, such as personality (Ramezani et al. 2022; Tadesse et al. 2018) and political affiliation (Khan and Khan 2024). Developing a causal framework grounded in LLMs is further advantageous when considering that LLMs can be easily controlled through prompts (OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; Ornstein et al. 2024), which could be used to create a simulated research environment (cf. Holderried et al. 2024) consisting of LLM-driven subjects, prompted with information that produces realistic behavior. In such an environment, subjects could be manipulated in many more ways compared to humans, possibly allowing the manipulation of a previously non-manipulable theorized causes. Should such a framework be feasible, this would enable numerous researchers to conduct studies using LLMs, with an internal validity comparable to RCTs (cf. Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49; Wooldridge 2019: 54-56). While the external validity of such a framework could reasonably be questioned since LLM-based results may not generalize to humans, this is an empirical question that, similar to the validation of existing frameworks and methods (e.g., Hainmueller et al. 2015; Sheagley and Clifford 2025), could be answered by comparing LLM-based results with human-based results on phenomena where the theorized cause is manipulable. Should this causal framework be found to provide both a high internal and external validity, this could allow researchers to more generally draw reliable causal inference for instances where the theorized cause would normally be non-manipulable. The prospect of developing such a causal framework is examined in this paper, with the aim formalized as the following research question:

RQ: Can an LLM-based causal framework be developed that provides reliable causal inference for instances where the theorized cause is otherwise non-manipulable?

To answer this research question, the paper reviews causal inference as conceptualized by the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (POF, Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005), the detrimental issues of confounding, and the limitations of existing methodologies in enabling reliable causal inference. Using the POF, a novel Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) is then proposed to solve these limitations by offering an alternative framework that offers reliable causal inference. This SCF is designed for researchers interested in assessing the potential effect of some theorized cause on an outcome in a human population but are unable to manipulate this theorized cause using the randomization of RCTs or similar exogenous manipulation procedures. The theoretical basis of the SCF builds on the established link between language and behavior (cf. Bandura 1999: 195; Holtgraves 2013; Lucy 1992; Pennebaker et al. 2003; Whorf 2011[1956]), with a critical assumption being that the theorized effect is meaningfully expressible through natural language, which would arguably be necessary for Large Language-models (LLMs, Shanahan 2024) to emulate it. The SCF specifically involves simulating units, whose characteristics are sampled in proportion to their prevalence in a human population of interest. Such characteristics are provided to an LLM together with a prompt instructing the model to generate unit life-histories (cf. Bertaux 1981). These life-histories are to be based on the assigned characteristics and the real-life data that the LLMs have been trained on, thus infusing simulated characteristics with real-world nuance. Units produced through this synthesis of simulated characteristics and learned real-world behavior are conceptualized as synthetic units, a term based on Hegelian dialectics (cf. Fichte 1970), introduced to distinguish these units from purely simulated units not infused with information from real-world data. Using prompts, a synthetic environment is created, where the LLM is instructed to behave as the synthetic units, basing its behavior on the generated life-histories. In this environment completely under the control of researchers, the theorized cause can then be manipulated by researchers, with the SCF specifically enabling each synthetic unit to be simultaneously and independently exposed to varying levels of manipulation. The simultaneity of the manipulations serve to eliminate time-based confounding (Mansournia et al. 2017), while the independent manipulations ensures that the LLM is unaware of previous and future exposures to treatment, which serve to eliminate spill-over (cf. Imbens and Rubin 2015: 12-13; Stuart 2010: 3), prior and post manipulation biases (cf. Linos and Twist 2018; Montgomery et al. 2018). With the counterfactual outcomes of each level of manipulation having been measured, intra-unit comparisons can be made to eliminate all unit- and time-invariant confounders (cf. Westreich et al. 2015), enabling the causal effect for each synthetic unit to be reliably identified. Based on these stipulations, the SCF is defined as a theoretical framework for drawing reliable causal inference when the theorized cause in non-manipulable in human populations, achieved through the use of LLM-generated synthetic units that enable independent and simultaneous intra-unit comparisons of counterfactual outcomes. While the SCF developed by this paper would a priori possess a high internal validity, based on criticisms of similar methods (e.g., Deaton and Cartwright 2018), there are concerns for the generalizability of synthetically-derived results to human subjects that require empirical validation.

To assess the generalizability of the SCF, and provide a proof-of-concept, the robustly established causal relationship between deservingness and welfare support in human populations (cf. Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019) is sought replicated using synthetic units. With the manipulation being a text-based vignette using natural language, the original RCT-based study (Aare and Petersen 2014) is replicated (n = 1,009) in the form of a novel Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT), an SCF-based extension of the RCT. Contrary to an RCT, instead of relying on randomization to manipulate subjects to one condition each, an SCT is capable of independently and simultaneously assigning all subjects to every manipulation condition. With adult respondents from the United States (US) being used in the original and replication studies, population estimates derived from IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021) are used in the SCT to jointly simulate common demographic characteristics proportional to their prevalence in the US. Employing the gpt-4o-mini LLM by OpenAI (2024a), life-histories are generated from these characteristics to produce synthetic respondents. With gpt-4o-mini controlling the behavior of each synthetic respondent, the SCT then conceptually replicates the survey environment and vignettes used in Aare and Petersen (2014). In this synthetic environment, each synthetic respondent is then independently and simultaneously exposed to vignettes detailing a lazy welfare recipient and an unlucky welfare recipient, measuring the synthetic respondents counterfactual levels of support for stricter requirements for the welfare eligibility of each recipient. The analysis then employs a multilevel Bayesian model (cf. Brkner 2017, 2018), with multilevel Frequentist models for robustness (cf. Bates et al. 2015), producing results that closely replicate the results from the human-based populations. Having demonstrated an implementation of the SCF, and produced evidence that causal results derived using the SCF generalize to human populations, its negligible implementations costs, assumptions, limitations, and potential improvements are discussed, followed by a conclusion about the future use of the SCF.

3 Theory

To develop a causal framework with the explicit goal of providing reliable causal inference when the theorized cause is non-manipulable, it is first necessary to understand what makes causal inference reliable. This requires defining a causal effect and the issues that inherently makes drawing causal inference with non-manipulable phenomena unreliable. The definition of a causal effect will draw on the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (POF, Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005), while the concepts of spuriousness and masking will be used to illustrate how the mere possibility of confounding produces unreliable causal inference. This is followed by a review of some of the fundamental issues inherent to existing alternative frameworks and methods for drawing causal inference with non-manipulable phenomena. From these insights, the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) is introduced to solve these issues and thereby enable reliable causal inference. The theory underlying the SCF is founded on behavioral and linguistic studies, simulations, and advances in natural language processing, which are used to outline fundamental assumptions and limitations of the SCF. This includes the novel conceptualizations of synthetic units and parallel worlds-estimation. The section concludes with a formalization of the SCF and a concern for the generalizability of SCF-based results to human populations, which serves as the basis for an implementation and test of the SCF in the remainder of this paper.

3.1 Causal Inference

Causal inference is a topic of broad relevance across the scientific disciplines. As of writing, more than 505,000 scientific articles are dedicated to the topic4, and recently in 2024, more than 10,278 projects were created to continue contributing to it.5 Research dedicated to causal inference span numerous fields in the social and behavioral sciences (Imbens and Rubin 2015; Wright 2015), such as economics (e.g., Angrist and Pischke 2015; Angrist and Pischke 2009; Gilchrist et al. 2024; Powell 2022), medicine (e.g., Bilgel and Galle 2015; Strbing et al. 2023), public management (e.g., Birdsall 2011), social psychology (e.g., Aronson et al. 2018: 54-61; Bettinsoli et al. 2015), political science (e.g., Abadie et al. 2010; Aronow and Samii 2016; Druckman 2015; Hartman 2021; Mutz and Pemantle 2012; Samii 2016; Slothuus 2016), and sociology (e.g., Aronow and Samii 2017). To provide theoretical conceptualizations of causal inference, several frameworks have been developed (e.g., Greenland et al. 1999; Imbens and Rubin 2015; Mazaheri et al. 2024; Pearl 1988, 1993, 1995; Rubin 2005), and these have in turn produced methods that rely on the stipulations made by these framework to identify conditions that enable researchers to draw reliable causal inferences (e.g., Abadie et al. 2010, 2015; Abadie and LHour 2021; Arkhangelsky et al. 2021; Dunning 2008; Pang et al. 2022; Rosenbaum and Rubin 1983; Strbing et al. 2023). As such, causal inference is an important and thriving scientific topic, and the usefulness of contributions to this literature span numerous disciplines.

The general utility of causal inference as a field is founded in theorists often proposing causal relationships to explain physical phenomena6. Using standard notation and set theory (Burgess 2022[1948]; Cantor 1874), a causal relationship can be conceptualized to involve at least two physically distinct phenomena (e.g., \(X\) and \(Y\), with \(X \ne Y\))7, where one phenomenon (\(X\)) temporally precedes the second phenomenon (\(X \prec Y\)), with the former exacting an effect upon the latter (\(X \rightarrow Y\)).8 Such relationships are unique to causal inference, since the theoretical claim is not merely that one phenomenon correlates with, or predicts, another phenomenon, but that the phenomenon causes the other, which is especially vital for researchers interested in ultimate causes (e.g., Boyer and Petersen 2018) and the causal mechanisms underlying phenomena (e.g., Bullock et al. 2010). This distinction can be further illustrated by emphasizing that the goal of causal inference is the valid and reliable identification of a theorized causal effect (e.g., \(D\)). The concern for validity and reliability means that an estimated effect (e.g., \(\hat{D}\)) should ideally be equivalent to the true effect (i.e., \(\hat{D} = D\)). This distinct focus can be contrasted with predictive (Cranmer and Desmarais 2017; James et al. 2021), correlational (Pearson 1895a), and imputational inference (Kalton and Kasprzyk 1982; King et al. 2001; Rubin 1988). While these are similarly concerned with relationships between phenomena, such relationships are not necessarily causal, and their goal is to predict a phenomenon (e.g., \(Y\)) using other phenomena (e.g., \(X\)), with the central concern being to make predictions (i.e., \(\tilde{Y}\)) that ideally are perfectly accurate (i.e., \(\tilde{Y} = Y\)). Since these approaches serve different purposes, they can have different concerns for what constitutes valid and reliable inference. For example, while the inclusion of causes in a model may yield good predictive inference (Schlkopf et al. 2021), the inclusion of non-causes in a model cannot yield good causal inference, or as alternatively stated by Nancy Cartwright (1994): No causes in, no causes out. To illustrate the concerns specific to causal inference, a more formal conceptualization of an effect is useful, which can be provided by the Potential Outcomes Framework.

3.1.1 Potential Outcomes Framework

One popular conceptualization of a causal effect, helpful in establishing reliable causal inference, is provided by the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (POF, Holland 1986; Imbens 2015: 374-377; Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005), which defines a causal effect as a difference in potential outcomes (Imbens and Rubin 2015: 6; Angrist and Pischke 2015: 6-8; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 13-15; Wooldridge 2019: 100-102). Consistent with the modern conceptualization by Guido W. Imbens and Donald B. Rubin (2015), with the use of set theory (Burgess 2022[1948]; Cantor 1874), potential outcomes can be understood as the set of all possible outcomes, irrespective of whether or not any of these outcomes are realized. To help distinguish realized from potential outcomes, one can draw a parallel to the particle/wave duality in physics (Thomson and Reid 1927; Zeilinger 1999; see also Monroe et al. 1996): The set of potential outcomes can be understood as a superposition of possible, yet contradicting outcomes that collapses when any one outcome is realized. As such, only one realized potential outcome is ever observed, while all other potential outcomes become counterfactual outcomes. This concept of a causal effect helps emphasize that comparisons between potential outcomes are what defines a causal effect, and once having observed a realized outcome, causal inference involves comparing this realized outcome with at least one other counterfactual outcome (Imbens and Rubin 2015: 4; Wooldridge 2019: 10-14, 53-56). If the theorized cause truly affects the outcome, different variations of the theorized cause would expectedly produce different potential outcomes, which in turn imply different counterfactual outcomes. This can be synthesized with the above criteria for a causal effect so that any physically distinct and temporally preceding phenomena, which can be held attributable to a difference in potential outcomes, can be considered a cause of that outcome.9

A strength of the POF is the ability to formalize this difference in potential outcomes mathematically. This is shown here using discrete mathematics (Gallier 2011), with the underlying assumption being that the phenomena of interest can be meaningfully reduced to mathematical constructs (Mazur 2006; for discussion, see, e.g., Eronen and Romeijn 2020). For the purposes of illustration, no measurement error (Bandalos 2018) will be assumed, and consistent with the POF (Angrist et al. 1996; Imbens and Rubin 2015: 9-12), the illustration will invoke the Stable Unit Treatment Value Assumption (SUTVA, Cox 1958; Gelman et al. 2021: 353-354; Rosenbaum and Rubin 1983; Rubin 1974; Stuart 2010: 3), which states that the potential outcomes for any unit do not vary with the treatments assigned to other units, and, for each unit, there are no different forms or versions of each treatment level, which lead to different potential outcomes. (Imbens and Rubin 2015: 10). This means that units characterized by a certain manifestation or level of the theorized cause do not affect units with different manifestations in any relevant way, which would hinder the identification of an effect due to spill-over (Imbens and Rubin 2015: 12-13; Stuart 2010: 3; e.g., Aronow and Samii 2017). Again using set theory (Burgess 2022[1948]; Cantor 1874), first suppose that the outcome (i.e., \(Y\)) is a real-valued vector (\(Y \subseteq \mathbb{R}\)) of an arbitrary length (\(|Y|\)), so that \(Y = \{Y_1, Y_2, Y_3, ..., Y_{|Y|}\}\), with any arbitrary index-value being denoted by \(y\). Second, suppose a distinct and temporally-precedent theorized cause (i.e., \(X\), with \(X \prec Y\), \(X \ne Y\)), which is similarly a real-valued vector (\(X \subseteq \mathbb{R}\)), its length (\(|X|\)) being arbitrary, so that \(X = \{X_1, ..., X_{|X|}\}\), with \(x\) indicating an arbitrary index-value. Suppose then a \(N_C \cdot K_C\) matrix of all precedent and distinct causes of the outcome (denoted \(C\)), which in the event that \(X\) truly is a cause of \(Y\), does not contain \(X\) (i.e., \(X \not \subseteq C\)). Note that \(C\) is not indexed for ease of illustration, and that all causes in \(C\) precede and are distinct from \(X\). The potential outcome, \(Y(\cdot)\), can then be expressed conditionally on \(C\) and, as theorized, possibly conditional on \(X\) as: \(Y(X, C)\). A causal effect of \(X\) would then entail a difference between two potential outcomes that vary solely with respect to \(X\), that is, \(Y(X_x, C)\) and \(Y(X_{x'}, C)\), with \(C\) held constant and \(x'\) being an index-value of \(X\) that is not \(x\). By keeping \(C\) constant and only varying \(X\), any difference in potential outcomes will be solely attributable to \(X\), allowing its theorized effect to be reliably assessed. In the instance that the difference varies across \(X\), the causal effect is heterogenous by being conditional on the particular potential outcomes being compared (i.e., \(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}}\)).10 This formalization of causal inference based on (Imbens and Rubin 2015) results in equation 1.1 provided below.

\(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}} = Y(X_x, C) \: - \: Y(X_{x'}, C)\) 1.1

NOTE: Mathematical equation. \(D\) = Difference in potential outcomes. \(Y(\cdot)\) = Potential outcome. \(X\) = Theorized cause, with \(x\) being the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause, while \(x'\) is the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause that is not \(x\). \(C\) = All causes that impact \(Y(\cdot)\), excluding \(X\) in the event that \(X\) impacts the potential outcomes.

While this formalization helps conceptualize a causal effect, equation 1.1 is arguably too simplistic for most practical purposes. This is evident when adding notation to reflect that causal inference typically involves computing causal effects from a number (\(n\)) of measured units (i.e., \(n \in \mathbb{N}\), indexed by \(i\)), which consistent with SUTVA are here assumed to be independent of each other. Since the theorized cause, potential outcomes, and causal effects can vary across units, 1.1 can be modified using Imbens and Rubin (2015) to that of 1.2.

\(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}, i} = Y_i(X_{x, i}, C_i) \: - \: Y_i(X_{x', i}, C_i)\) 1.2

NOTE: Mathematical equation. \(D\) = Difference in potential outcomes. \(Y(\cdot)\) = Potential outcome. \(X\) = Theorized cause, with \(x\) being the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause, while \(x'\) is the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause that is not \(x\). \(C\) = All causes that impact \(Y(\cdot)\), excluding \(X\) in the event that \(X\) impacts the potential outcomes. \(i\) is the index-value of an arbitrary unit.

As shown in equation 1.2, the computation of a causal effect requires a comparison of the same unit across at least two contradicting potential outcomes. This may seem plausible by manipulating the same individual with respect to \(X\) at two different points in time (e.g., a repeated manipulations design, Shaughnessy et al. 2015: 219-242; Sullivan 2008). However, consistent with equation 1.1 and 1.2, this would require the assumption that time (\(T\)) is not a cause of \(Y\) (\(T \not \subseteq C\)), since any phenomena contained in \(C\) must be constant when comparing potential outcomes to avoid conflating the effect of \(X\) with the effect of \(T\). This can be exemplified by formalizing time as \(T\), a real-valued time vector (\(T \subseteq \mathbb{R}\)) of arbitrary length (\(|T|\)), so that \(T = \{T_1, ..., T_{|T|}\}\), indexed by \(t\). In the event that \(T\) impacts the potential outcomes, \(T\) is here not contained in \(C\), is physically distinct from and occurs simultaneously with \(X\), and the requirement for equivalence in this term can then be made explicit, as demonstrated in equation 1.3.

\(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}, t, i} = Y_i(X_{x, i}, T_{t, i}, C_i) \: - \: Y_i(X_{x', i}, T_{t, i}, C_i)\) 1.3

NOTE: Mathematical equation. \(D\) = Difference in potential outcomes. \(Y(\cdot)\) = Potential outcome. \(X\) = Theorized cause, with \(x\) being the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause, while \(x'\) is the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause that is not \(x\). \(T\) = Time, with \(t\) being the index-value of an arbitrary point in time. \(C\) = All causes that impact \(Y(\cdot)\), excluding \(X\) in the event that \(X\) impacts the potential outcomes, as well as \(T\) in the event that \(T\) impacts the potential outcomes. \(i\) is the index-value of an arbitrary unit.

Equation 1.3 implies that differences between potential outcomes (\(D\)) needs to be computed by varying the theorized cause (\(X\)) for the same individual (\(i\)), at the same point in time (\(T\)), with all other causes (\(C\)) held constant. A repeated measures design logically violates this equality by varying time across the potential outcomes, and any differences in potential outcomes caused by time will be able to confound results, producing estimates that conflate the effect of \(X\) on the potential outcomes with the effect of \(T\). This issue is further emphasized by considering that a repreated measures design must assume that multiple manipulations are independent of each other, which is easily violated if the unit is impacted by the manipulation in a way that affects future manipulations, which would cause spill-over and violate the fundamental SUTVA assumption. Examples of such violations include expectancy (cf. McDermott 1895: 34) and learning effects (cf. Shaughnessy et al. 2015: 222-224), which interacts with the effect of the manipulation. This independent and simultaneous comparison of individuals at counterfactual states has been recognized as impossible, being denoted the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference (Holland 1986; Stuart 2010: 3).

Much of the literature on causal inference has been dedicated to solving the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference (e.g., Holland 1986: 947). These typically involve shifting the focus from individual causal effects (i.e., \(D_i\)) to average causal effects (i.e., \(\bar{D}\), Angrist and Pischke 2015: 8-10; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 3-4, 13-22, 54-57; Stock and Watson 2019: 475-476), also referred to as expected causal effects (i.e., \(\mathbb{E}(D)\)). Consistent with SUTVA, assuming that the manifestation of the theorized cause cannot vary within each group condition (Imbens and Rubin 2015: 9-12), this focus on averages enable one to drop the individual unit subscript \(i\), since estimates are now computed based on the potential outcomes of groups of individuals. This is demonstrated by modifying equation 1.2, producing equation 1.4, where the \(T\) introduced for equation 1.3 will (again) be considered simultaneous with, and a subset of, \(C\) if it impacts the potential outcomes.

\(\mathbb{E}(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}}) = \mathbb{E}(Y(X_x, C)) \: - \: \mathbb{E}(Y(X_{x'}, C))\) 1.4

NOTE: Mathematical equation. \(\mathbb{E}(\cdot)\) = Expectation. \(D\) = Difference in potential outcomes. \(Y(\cdot)\) = Potential outcome. \(X\) = Theorized cause, with \(x\) being the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause, while \(x'\) is the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause that is not \(x\). \(C\) = All causes that impact \(Y(\cdot)\), excluding \(X\) in the event that \(X\) impacts the potential outcomes.

Equation 1.4 reveals that contradicting unit comparisons of potential outcomes are no longer a strict requirement for reliable causal inference. Instead, this only requires group comparisons where all confounders are held constant. Time is less of an obtrusive confounder here, since it is theoretically possible to simultaneously compare two groups at contradicting levels of the theorized cause, though the time of making these comparisons may still matter if the effect is heterogenous across time. Such a group comparison is theoretically achieved through an exogenous group assignment, which is typically implemented in a Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT, Coover and Angell 1907; Peirce and Jastrow 1885; Woodworth and Thorndike 1901) using a Random Assignment Mechanism (RAM). The randomness of this RAM serves to ensure that there are no expected group differences prior to the manipulation of \(X\), enabling a constant \(C\) across the group potential outcomes (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49; Holland 1986: 948; McDermott 1895: 33; Wooldridge 2019: 54-56). For example, while units may not be assigned to the manipulation at the same point in time (\(T\)), at the group level, the time of manipulation are expectedly equivalent, since units are assigned to a group independent of the time of their participation, producing estimated group differences unconfounded by time.

Further notation can be introduced to illustrate the RAM, which involves assuming varying group manipulation conditions (\(G\)) of an arbitrary length (\(|G|\)), so that \(G = \{G_1, G_2, G_3, ..., G_{|G|}\}\), where \(g_x\) indexes the arbitrary manipulation condition (e.g., a treatment or control condition), with the \(x\)-subscript indicating the manifestation of \(X\) that the manipulation is theorized to induce. This helps conceptualize an exogenous manipulation as practically equivalent to an exogenous group assignment, where a different exposure condition in each group serves to manipulate the units in different ways. Here, the exogeneity of the RAM can be formalized as a group assignment probability (\(Pr\)) that is independent of confounders (i.e., \(Pr(G = g_x) = Pr(G = g_x \ | \ C)\)). The distinction between the manipulated value of the theorized cause and the manipulation level intended by the assigned group condition serves to indicate that they are not necessarily equivalent and that the estimated effect may be conditional on both. For example, suppose that the theorized cause (\(X\)) truly is a cause of the outcome (\(Y\)) and that we employ an RCT, where for this particular study the use of the RAM ensures perfect group balance (i.e., constant \(C\)) across two different group manipulation conditions (e.g., \(g_x\) and \(g_{x'}\)). However, suppose then that the actual level of the theorized cause achieved by the group manipulation conditions results in the same level (i.e., \(x\)) across groups. While \(X\) does cause \(Y\) in this example, the group manipulation conditions fail to manipulate \(X\) resulting in an estimated causal effect of zero, which is exactly what happens if an RCT was to be conducted on a theorized cause that cannot be manipulated. Besides highlighting the issue that this paper serves to solve, this consideration helps distinguish between the manipulation level theoretically induced by a group manipulation condition (\(g_x\)) and the actual level of manipulation (\(x\)) that occurs, which is why an inadequate exogenous manipulation can fail to identify a causal effect and thus be one cause of a false negative result. This is reflected in the distinct notions of a causal effect versus a treatment effect, with the latter being an often used term to indicate that an effect can be conditional on the treatment used in the manipulation conditions. While this paper will generally assume that the intended and actual manipulation levels are equivalent, allowing a reliable identification of a causal effect, the ability to account for the distinction is useful and further warranted by the notion that interactions between the theorized cause and the manipulation condition can occur that results in varying identified effects. Such interactions can occur because the manipulation condition changes the effect of the theorized cause on the outcome (Linos and Twist 2018). For example, if the unit has already been exposed to that manipulation condition prior to the study (i.e., pretreatment effects, cf. Sniderman 2011; e.g., Slothuus 2016), with an identified effect in this instance constituting a special case of a treatment effect denoted the marginal effect of additional treatment (Slothuus 2016: 303; Gaines and Kuklinski 2011: 450). The fact that the potential outcomes, and thus the identified causal effect, can be conditional on both the theorized cause, confounders, and the manipulation condition is incorporated into equation 1.5:

\(\mathbb{E}(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}, \underset{g_x, g_{x'}}{\Delta}}) = \mathbb{E}(Y(X_{x}, C) \: | \: G = g_x) \: - \: \mathbb{E}(Y(X_{x'}, C) \: | \: G = g_{x'})\) 1.5

NOTE: Mathematical equation. \(\mathbb{E}(\cdot)\) = Expectation. \(D\) = Difference in potential outcomes. \(Y(\cdot)\) = Potential outcome. \(X\) = Theorized cause, with \(x\) being the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause, while \(x'\) is the index-value of an arbitrary manifestation of the theorized cause that is not \(x\). \(C\) = All causes that impact \(Y(\cdot)\), excluding \(X\) in the event that \(X\) impacts the potential outcomes. \(G\) = Group, \(g_x\) is an arbitrary group condition, subscriptet by the manifestation of the theorized cause it serves to induce.

As illustrated in equation 1.5, consistent with (Stuart 2010: 2), a causal effect can be defined as the expected difference in potential outcomes across counterfactual group manipulation conditions. This helps further the understanding that the exogenous manipulation conditions here serves to produce two groups, which a priori have the same potential outcomes, since the RAM makes independent group assignments, but by merit of being differently manipulated across the manipulation conditions, they will expectedly differ with respect to the theorized cause, resulting in two counterfactual group outcomes being observed, one for each group. For this illustration, reliable causal inference reduces to simply computing the difference in group means (Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 3; Stock and Watson 2019: 121-123). In line with this, it should be noted that the principle of no group differences except with respect to \(X\) in equation 1.5, realistically only applies to groups of infinite size, or to estimates derived from an infinite sequence of RCTs. This is because for any study with finite group size, the RAM used to implement the exogenous manipulation does not guarantee no group difference with respect to \(C\) (i.e., no confounding), only the expectation of no group differences (Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 6; Imai et al. 2008: 488). This principle of no expected confounding is also referred to as unbiasedness (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 12; Hartman 2021: 386; cf. Wooldridge 2019: 717-718). Stated similarly, group balance will only be guaranteed asymptotically (Wooldridge 2019: 721-724), meaning that for any comparison of groups of finite size, or estimates from a finite sequence of RCTs, \(C\) may be inequivalent across group potential outcomes (Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 6; Imai et al. 2008: 488), allowing confounders to influence the results of any particular study, though confounding is reduced the larger the groups and the greater the amount of RCTs that causal estimates are averaged over, with the specific bias for any study being unknowable unless one knows the correct functional form of the confounders (Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 4; Rubin 1974).

Taken together, the POF provides useful insights on how to conceptualize causal effects and the premises for making reliable causal inferences. This primarily emphasizes equivalency with respect to confounders when comparing potential outcomes that differ with respect to the theorized cause. While the POF helps illustrate concerns for confounding and the elimination of confounders through exogenous manipulation, it is necessary to further emphasize the issues of confounding and their inescapability when the theorized cause is non-manipulable.

3.1.2 Confounding

Confounding is a serious concern to reliable causal inference (Fisher 1935; Greenland et al. 1999; VanderWeele and Shpitser 2013). Defined as a variable that (1) temporally precedes treatment and is both (2) associated with the treatment and (3) associated with the outcome (Elwert 2013: 262), a confounder can make a causal interpretation of results entirely invalid, leading to the production of wrong scientific insights, which if used for policy recommendations can mean a waste of resources and the implementation of policies that could potentially harm individuals. Confounding can make causal inference unreliable through numerous avenues. Some of the most important confounders considered here include reverse-causality, spuriousness, and masking. To provide an overview of these type of relationships, directed acyclic graphs (DAGs, Pearl 1988, 1993, 1995) of (1) no causal relationship, (2) a causal relationship, (3) a reverse-causal relationship, (4) a spurious (non-causal) relationship, and (5) a masked causal relationship are provided in figure 3.1.

Reverse-causality refers to instances where the theorized cause of some outcome is actually itself caused by that outcome (e.g., \(X \leftarrow Y\), Shadish et al. 2002). Causal inference may be made unreliable by this type of confounding whenever the theorized cause does not precede the outcome (\(X \nprec Y\)), but instead succeeds the outcome (\(X \succ Y\)). This violates the criterion of temporal precedence (Hume 2011: 72-73) outlined above (i.e., \(X \prec Y\)). Temporal precedence can be guaranteed by employing an exogenous manipulation of the theorized cause, for example, using the RAM of RCTs, since an exogenous theorized cause by definition cannot be caused by other phenomena, such as the theorized outcome, it can only itself cause other phenomena. When the theorized cause is non-manipulable, researchers often employ alternative strategies, such as relying on longitudinal data (Wooldridge 2019: 7-10, 334-335), that is, they measure the theorized cause and outcome at one point in time (e.g., \(T = t_1\), with \(X_{t_1}\) and \(Y_{t_1}\)), followed by measuring the outcome again at a later point in time (e.g., \(T = t_2\), with \(Y_{t_2}\)). They can then substract the measures of the outcome across this time period (\(\Delta Y = Y_{t_2} - Y_{t_1}\)) and model a relationship between the theorized cause measured at the first time point (\(X_{t_1}\)) with the difference in the outcome (\(\Delta Y\)), ensuring that the outcome being studied temporally succeeds the theorized cause. However, longitudinal studies can be considerably expensive, and they can often enhance other types of biases (e.g., attrition bias, Hausman and Wise 1979; Rohrer 2018: 36), so researchers may alternatively use a cross-sectional design (Wooldridge 2019: 5-7). Here, they can try to ensure temporal precedence by measuring the theorized cause prior to measuring the outcome, and as a response to the reliability of this solution, it is here necessary to emphasize that the time of measuring a phenomenon does not equal its time of origin. This means that just because the theorized cause is measured prior to the outcome, this does not mean that the theorized cause originated at a time prior to the outcome, and temporal precedence thus remains violable.11 As such, while a longitudinal study helps ensure temporal precedence, which is necessary for reliable causal inference, it is not a sufficient condition (de Leeuw 1985: 372; with claims to the contrary being a post hoc ergo proper hoc logical fallacy, Manninen 2019a), and as will be made evident below, an exogenous manipulation generally offers a more reliable approach in terms of reliability.

Figure 3.1: Examples of Relationships

NOTE: Directed Acyclic Graphs (Pearl 1988, 1993; DAGs, Pearl 1995). \(x\) = Theorized cause, \(y\) = outcome, \(s\) = spurious confounder, \(m\) = masking confounder. Non-exhaustive list of relationship types.

Two other types of confounders considered here are (1) spuriousness, which refers to an instance when there is no relationship between the theorized cause and outcome, but where a third variable (e.g., \(s\)) impacts both of them, creating a spurious relationship that researchers may wrongly attribute to the theorized cause (Gumbel 1933; McElreath 2019: 123-144; Stock and Watson 2019: 584-586); and (2) masking, that involves a situation with a relationship between the theorized cause and outcome, but where a third variable (e.g., \(m\)) impacts both of them in a way that masks their relationship, leading to the researcher wrongly concluding no effect of the theorized cause12 (McElreath 2019: 144-153). These related confounders are both reliably solved with an exogenous manipulation, since an exogenous theorized cause by definition cannot be affected by a third variable, preventing any spurious or masking effects to occur. Stated in the terminology of the aforementioned DAGs, this is because an exogenous manipulation closes any and all back-doors, that is, any relationships between the theorized cause and confounders (i.e., the back-door criterion, Elwert 2013: 259-260; McElreath 2019: 184-189; Rohrer 2018: 30-31). However, when the theorized cause is non-manipulable, researchers may alternatively attempt to identify all possible confounders to avoid the issues of falling victim to spuriousness or masking, for example, by drawing encompassing DAGs. However, what constitutes the true DAG of a causal relationship is inherently unknowable (Elwert 2013: 270), and it is the researchers responsibility to justify having accounted for all possible confounders (Elwert 2013: 248). Failing to account for any confounder can produce spurious or masked relationships, while accounting for any non-confounder can induce other types of biases (e.g., collider bias or overcontrol bias, Elwert 2013: 250; Elwert and Winship 2014; McElreath 2019: 176-183; Rohrer 2018: 34-38). With non-manipulable theorized causes, researchers can reasonably suspect that their results may be confounded and attempt to estimate how much a confounding effect would be necessary to make an identified relationship spurious (e.g., Cinelli and Hazlett 2020). But a shortcoming of such procedures is that researchers may erroneously conclude that because the confounding effect would have to be too large for a known confounder to produce, then the identified relationship must be causal. There are several issues with this argument. Specifically it applies numerous logical fallacies (Arp et al. 2019), including an appeal to ignorance (Bebbington 2011; McCraw 2019), or alternatively an appeal to personal incredulity (Manninen 2019b), if not both, since researchers inability to know or imagine such a relevant confounder does not mean that this confounder does not exist. Further, assuming that the large confounding effect would have to originate from a single confounder commits the oversimplification fallacy (Burkett 2019), since the large confounding effect could be caused jointly through the aggregation of smaller effects by numerous confounders. Ultimately, unless researchers know the functional form of the confounder, which they rarely do, they cannot know the magnitude by which it may confound results (Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 4).

In line with these insights, the issues of reverse-causality, spuriousness, and masking would seem most reliably solved through an exogenous manipulation of the theorized cause. This implies that any phenomenon that is merely observed or manipulated in an non-exogenous manner may be endogenous and affected by confounders (Mutz and Pemantle 2012: 3), such as reverse-causation, spuriousness, and masking. Accordingly, researchers interested in drawing causal inference from non-manipulable phenomena face numerous issues of confounding that a priori justify serious concerns regarding the reliability of causal inference drawn from possibly endogenous phenomena. While numerous methodologies exist to mitigate these concerns, as will be made clear in the subsequent section, unless they enable an exogenous manipulation of the theorized cause, these justified concerns generally make them unable to provide reliable causal inference.

3.1.3 Issues with Existing Solutions

The issues of drawing reliable causal inference with non-manipulable theorized causes are widespread and affect numerous phenomena of substantial scientific interest. Non-manipulable phenomena include gender, personality, and other deeply rooted traits and values [] (Buunk and van Vugt 2013: 17) that all have been the focus of numerous studies (Block and Block 2006; Graham and Haidt 2012; Mac Giolla and Kajonius 2019; e.g., Mondak 2010). These are generally considered non-manipulable (e.g., Holland 1986: 946) either for ethical reasons or due to being biologically rigid and thus practically impossible to manipulate (e.g., personality traits, Buss 2009; Larsen et al. 2021; Mitchell 2018). For the aforementioned reasons, any causal relationship involving non-manipulable phenomena, RCTs cannot be employed for reliable causal inference, and observational designs that fail to account for the possibility of confounding thus risks making false positive or false negative conclusions regarding the hypothesized causal relationships. A solution to this issue could involve changing the scope of the research from causal inference to correlational or predictive inference, since this avoids the issue of making false causal conclusions. However, researchers may find it difficult to change scope if their central interest is specifically that of a causal relationship. This is evidenced by researchers often making inappropriate causal interpretations (for such criticisms, see, e.g., Chiu et al. 2023; Keele 2015; Lee 2012; Rohrer 2024; Samii 2016) despite the lack of manipulability of the phenomena essentially restricting them to correlational/predictive/imputational inference. While they often justify a causal interpretation through theory (e.g., Xu and Peterson 2017), given the multitude of ways for confounding outlined above, a theoretical argument alone seldom provides any reliable guarantees for the absence of confounding, a consideration that is further expanded upon below.

A strategy for researchers to justify a causal interpretation when being unable to exogenously manipulate the theorized cause is through theory and argumentation. While this arguably helps justify a causal interpretation (Elwert 2013: 247), such arguments often make implicit, if not explicit, use of logical fallacies (Arp et al. 2019). Examples of fallacious logic that researchers can employ to justify a causal interpretation include shifting the burden of proof (Russo 2019) of the causal claim to the skeptic (e.g., If you are so skeptical of my claim that \(x\) causes \(y\), prove to me that \(x\) does not cause \(y\).). This is a logical fallacy because the burden of proof (onus probandi) ultimately falls upon the one making the causal claim (i.e., the researcher) and not the one skeptical of the claim (Cargile 1988; Hume 2010[1748]; Russo 2019; Sagan 1979). Another fallacy can involve a researcher justifying a causal interpretation because (whether guided by theory or intuition) they cannot imagine any confounders, or have accounted for the select number of confounders of which they are aware (e.g., I have controlled for \(z\) so therefore \(x\) must cause \(y\).). This would be the fallacy of an appeal to ignorance (Bebbington 2011; McCraw 2019), or alternatively an appeal to personal incredulity (Manninen 2019b), if not both, since the ignorance of (or inability to imagine) confounders does not equate with there being no confounders. The probably least sound argument explicitly involves simply requiring researchers to be able to imagine a causal relationship (Morgan and Winship 2007: 279; as cited by Bollen and Pearl 2013: 313), which obviously fails to lift the burden of proof and is highly susceptible to confirmation bias by the causal claimant (Johnson 2019). Another, perhaps more commonly known, logical fallacy that researchers can employ is to suggest that a correlation between phenomena implies causation. This would be a cum hoc ergo propter hoc logical fallacy (Manninen 2019c), since the co-occurrence of phenomena, no matter how consistent, does not necessitate that one phenomenon be the cause of the other13. This is why researchers generally recognize that correlation does not imply causation (Pearson 2015[1900]) and that causation does not imply correlation (Kennaway 2015).14

Researchers can also employ methodological designs to help justify a causal interpretation of results. Among the more justifiable approaches is the natural experiment (Dunning 2008; Stock and Watson 2019: 490), which attempts to exploit a manipulation of the theorized cause to help identify a causal effect. The natural experiment, however, differs from an RCT, since this manipulation is not controlled by the researchers, but instead is under the control of naturally occurring phenomena. In line with the logic underlying the RAM in RCTs, it remains key that this natural manipulation occurs exogenously of all possible confounders, which in this context is referred to the manipulation being as-if-random (Stock and Watson 2019: 497-498). Should the naturally-occurring manipulation fail this criteria, it will be endogenous, resulting in possible confounding and unreliable causal inference. Numerous researchers have employed natural experiments to test theorized causal relationships with theorized causes not manipulable by researchers (e.g., Erikson and Stoker 2011; Jones and Olken 2005; Kokkonen and Sundell 2020). Here, the as-if-random manipulation is often sought justified through theory and knowledge about the manipulation mechanism. While some manipulation mechanisms are undoubtedly more credibly exogenous than others (e.g., a lottery, Erikson and Stoker 2011), many are open to the aforementioned logical fallacies (e.g., I think of no confounders, ergo no confounders.). The ability of natural experiments to provide reliable causal inference therefore rests on the exogeneity of the manipulation mechanism, which unlike the RAM of RCTs are not generally as testable in relation to their randomness (Mutz and Pemantle 2012). Another limitation is the identification of natural experiments, which can be difficult and subject to luck. As such, while natural experiments, in principle, could enable reliable causal inference through an as-if-random manipulation of a phenomena non-manipulable by researchers, they are difficult to identify, and distinguishing between truly exogenous and endogenous manipulation mechanisms are difficult if not impossible, making them generally unable to deliver truly reliable causal inference.

Designs related to the natural experiment (i.e., quasi-experiments) include relying on regression discontinuity designs and instrumental variables. The regression discontinuity design (RDD, Skovron and Titiunik 2015; Thistlethwaite and Campbell 1960) involves identifying a causal effect by studying a theorized cause across a time period. During this period some change is induced in the theorized cause, which is expected to cause a change in the outcome (Stock and Watson 2019: 495-496; Angrist and Pischke 2015: 147-177; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 251-267; Gelman et al. 2021: 432-452). To justify a causal interpretation, it is necessary that the change is induced exogenously in an as-if-random manner (Stock and Watson 2019: 496). As such, the procedure is highly similar to a natural experiment, though with the added requirement that the theorized cause is observed across time. While this helps researchers understand variations in the outcome prior to the induced variation in the theorized cause, which undoubtedly can help separate random noise from a possible effect of the theorized cause (e.g., regression to the mean effects, cf. Gelman et al. 2021: 87-90; McElreath 2019: 92), this design again relies on strong assumptions of an exogenous manipulation that similarly makes natural experiments generally unreliable for causal inference. By contrast, Instrumental variables (IVs, Stock and Watson 2019: 427-472, 494; Angrist and Pischke 2015: 98-146; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 113-218, 259-267; Gelman et al. 2021: 421-454; Imbens and Rubin 2015: 513-584) are phenomena that are manipulable, either by researchers or by naturally-occurring phenomena, which are expected to impact the theorized cause. The idea is to isolate variation in the theorized cause exogenously induced by the IV and identify a relationship between this variation in the theorized cause and the outcome (Angrist and Krueger 1991; e.g., Hariri 2012; Stock and Trebbi 2003; Wright 1928). While for naturally-occurring IVs, whose exogeneity rely on the same issues of as-if-randomness that generally make natural experiments unreliable, IVs exogenously manipulated by researchers can arguably provide a better justification for a causal interpretation of results. While this may sound promising, the reliability of IVs rests on numerous assumptions (Gelman et al. 2021: 422-423), and a central criticism considered here targets the exclusion restriction assumption, which states that the IV cannot impact the outcome except solely through the theorized cause (Angrist and Pischke 2009: 116-117, 153-154; Angrist and Pischke 2015: 101-107, 130-131; Samii 2016: 948; Gelman et al. 2021: 423). This is a strong assumption that is impossible to test, since this would require investigating every possible phenomena with a temporal occurrence between the theorized cause and the outcome. Consistent with the above, the reliability of this strategy for causal inference cannot rely on researchers ability to adequately account for every possible confounder nor for every possible way that an IV could impact an outcome other than through the theorized cause. Accordingly, neither RDDs nor IVs are taken to generally provide reliable causal inference.

A third set of methods that researchers can employ for causal inference involves the construction of counterfactual comparison groups. Such designs include difference-in-differences, synthetic control, matching, and functional adjustment. Through different means these all attempt to correct for imbalances between units varying with respect to the theorized cause, which if inadequately accounted for can introduce confounding through selection bias (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 8-11; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 23-24; Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 9; Heckman 1979; Rohrer 2018: 36-38). The perhaps most sophisticated of these is the difference-in-differences (DiD) design (Stock and Watson 2019: 492-494; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 227-243; Angrist and Pischke 2015: 178-208). This involves observing at least two groups across time, where one group experiences a (naturally) occurring change in the theorized cause. To assess the counterfactual scenario of the outcome had this group not experienced this change during the observed time period, the difference in the outcome of the non-changed group for the same time period is used as an estimate of the counterfactual difference, producing a difference-in-differences estimate (e.g., Allers and Hoeben 2010; Bechtel and Hainmueller 2011; Card and Krueger 1994). For this method to be reliable, the changed and the non-changed group must be balanced in terms of all possible confounders prior to the chance in the theorized cause, an assumption that has also been referred to as parallel trends (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 184-187). This is commonly ascertained by assessing balance between the groups prior to the change. If data contains numerous measurements of the groups pre- and post-manipulation, this method can be combined with RDD to produce the possibly more reliable differences-in-discontinuity design (Grembi et al. 2012). However, it is clear that the assessment of parallel trends requires assuming a version of no unmeasured confounders to avoid results being plagued by omitted variable bias (OVB, Angrist and Pischke 2015: 69-93, 132-174, 212-213; Ho et al. 2007: 206), which again is dubious since researchers may not know of all possible confounders. Given these and other issues (e.g., Baker et al. 2022; Bertrand et al. 2004; Ferman 2023; Kahn-Lang and Lang 2020; Ryan et al. 2015), in accordance with the above, this method can similarly be found too unreliable for causal inference.

The synthetic control method similarly requires data across time, with the same underlying logic of a group experiencing a change in the theorized cause (Abadie et al. 2010, 2015; Abadie and LHour 2021). Here, multiple groups not experiencing this change are used to construct a counterfactual estimate of the outcome of the changed group had it not experienced the change. This involves a re-weighing of data similar to matching (see below), and for a causal estimate to be reliable, the counterfactual comparison group cannot differ from the treated group with respect to unobserved confounders. As such, it can be subjected to the same criticisms of plausibly failing to account for omitted variables as the DiD, making it similarly unreliable for causal inference.

By comparison, matching (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 50-56; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 69-91; Ho et al. 2007; Imbens 2015; Imbens and Rubin 2015: 337-358; Stuart 2010; e.g., Kam and Palmer 2008) does not require longitudinal data, but it similarly involves constructing a counterfactual outcome using units that did not experience a change in the theorized cause. While it does not rely on parallel trends like the DiD, it does make the same innate assumption of no unobserved confounders (Samii 2016: 948; Stuart 2010: 5; Rohrer 2018: 32-33; Ho et al. 2007: 200, 206-207), and in the event of failing to account for any confounder, this can re-introduce confounding through selection bias (Imai et al. 2008: 489; Pearl 2000; Wan et al. 2024). These and other issues (Imai et al. 2008; King and Nielsen 2019) means that it can generally be considered to fail in providing reliable causal inference, in particular for any scenario where researchers cannot reliable demonstrate no possible confounders.

Lastly, functional or parametric adjustment (cf. Stuart 2010: 2; Imai et al. 2008: 489), commonly known as controlling, involves the inclusion of covariates in a statistical model in an attempt to account for confounding phenomena. This is closely related to matching, and while it can reduce imbalances between two groups varying with respect to the theorized cause, as well as reduce variation in the outcome to help identify an effect of the theorized cause, the reliability of this procedure relies on numerous assumptions. This includes the assumption of correct functional form (Ho et al. 2007: 218), which means that the relationship between the confounder and the theorized cause and outcome must have been modeled correctly. For example, a linear adjustment is only appropriate if the impact of the confounder truly is linear, which can be difficult to ascertain. Another assumption shared with matching (Ho et al. 2007: 202) is that the phenomena being adjusted for must temporally precede the theorized cause, since the adjustment of any phenomena that occurs after the theorized cause risks inducing post-treatment bias (Montgomery et al. 2018). A more critical assumption is again the assumption of no unmeasured confounders. Since both matching and functional adjustment amounts to nothing more than selection on observables (Imbens 2015: 373), their ability to provide reliable causal inference relies on the correct adjustment for all confounders (Imai et al. 2008; Stuart 2010: 3), including confounders of which the researchers doing the adjustment may not be aware. For these reasons, functional adjustment also generally fails to provide reliable causal inference (cf. Aronow and Samii 2016; Imai et al. 2008; Samii 2016). With all these designs relying on the assumption of no unobserved confounders, it is worth stressing that in their attempt to increase balance, either by choosing groups similar to the group experiencing a change in the theorized cause, re-weighing groups, matching units, or making functional adjustments, that this runs the risk of increasing other imbalances. That is, by decreasing some imbalances, they can introduce new imbalances through selection bias, specifically by conditioning on observables (Ho et al. 2007: 202; Rohrer 2018; Wan et al. 2024).

Given the above review of existing methodologies for causal inference with non-manipulable phenomena, while it may seem strict to deem these methods unreliable in terms of causal inference, the take-away is that viewing these methods as being able to provide reliable causal inference generally increases the risk of making false causal conclusions in an manner that can be considered to be unjustified. Instead of putting researchers in a position where they have to measure all possible confounders, since this is the burden of proof of causal inference, an alternative and reliable approach would, instead of relying on numerous dubious and untestable assumptions, involve a design that at least guarantees, or at least by expectation, simply by its design, that results cannot be systematically confounded (cf. Rohrer 2018: 34; Stuart 2010: 3; Samii 2016). Researchers must listen to the multiple criticisms targeting attempts at causal inference with non-manipulable phenomena (e.g., Baumrind 1983; Berk 1994; Cartwright 1994; Cliff 1983; de Leeuw 1985; Elwert 2013; Freedman 2004; Guttman 1977; Imai et al. 2008; Rohrer 2018; Samii 2016; Wan et al. 2024), recognize that there simply can be no causation without manipulation15 (Holland 1986: 959), and understand that, similar to that of the RAM in RCTs, reliable causal framework generally necessitates an exogenous manipulation.

3.2 Synthetic Causal Framework

The previous sections have established that (1) a causal effect is the difference in potential outcomes, (2) that confounding is an ever present threat when the theorized cause is non-manipulable, and (3) that existing solutions generally fail to provide reliable causal inference, at least by comparison to RCTs. The consequence of the latter is that substantial parts of scientific disciplines interested in non-manipulable theorized causes are barred from making reliable tests of causal hypotheses, making a solution to this problem relevant for scientific progress. These insights will be used to lay the foundation of a framework aimed at solving the issue of non-manipulability and provide a methodology that can provide causal inference as reliable as RCTs.

The novel framework devised here to enable researchers to draw reliable causal inference when the theorized cause is non-manipulable will be denoted the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF), which will be outlined and formalized in this section. The development of this framework will draw on the established logic and notation by the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (POF, Holland 1986; Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005), with the aim of maximizing reliability through a high internal and external validity by design (cf. Stuart 2010: 3; Rohrer 2018: 34; Samii 2016). Following the POF, an a priori high internal validity will be achieved by making the non-manipulable theorized cause exogenously manipulable, allowing causal inference to be at least as internally valid as RCTs (cf. Angrist and Pischke 2009; Imai et al. 2008: 488; McDermott 2011; Stock and Watson 2019: 478-481). As similarly proven by theory on statistical inference, random sampling (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 14-16, 34-37; Thompson 2012) will be employed by the framework to provide a high external validity (cf. Gelman et al. 2021: 354-355; Stock and Watson 2019: 481; Imai et al. 2008: 488; McDermott 2011).

The first step in developing the SCF involves defining its scope. Given that the theorized cause is often non-manipulable in the social and behavioral sciences (Buunk and van Vugt 2013: 17), due to the manipulation of humans sometimes being unfeasible (e.g., due to ethical, practical, or cost concerns), the SCF will be developed with the intended aim of application within these disciplines, specifically for research topics where human individuals are the unit of interest, and where the theorized cause would otherwise not be manipulable. This means that the concern for external validity in relation to the SCF involves inference to human populations. The successful development of the framework will thus require an ability to rely on random sampling from an arbitrary human population, at least on a theoretical basis, and the manipulation of an arbitrary theorized cause, with results derived from an analysis of this manipulation being generalizable to the intended human population. This limitation in scope is unlikely to substantially reduce the usefulness of the framework, since the social and behavioral sciences encompass numerous disciplines and subdisciplines (Wright 2015). This is not to say that the SCF cannot necessarily be applied to other areas of research, but the scope helps clarify its intended area of application, as well the area-specific assumptions and limitations that the development and application of the SCF needs to consider and be evaluated against.

3.2.1 Large Language Models

With the intended application of the SCF being that of human-based studies, considerations can be made about random sampling and how to achieve an exogenous manipulation of an otherwise non-manipulable theorized cause. Given that numerous social scientific studies are conducted using online surveys (Batinic et al. 2002; Gideon 2012), where human respondents provide text-based responses, the solution that will underlie the SCF involves simulating human behavior using Natural Language Processing (Pillai and Tedesco 2023). In this field, Large Language Models (LLMs, Shanahan 2024) are developed with the specific aim of imitating human language and intelligence (Ornstein et al. 2024; e.g., Kjell et al. 2022). There have been numerous advances in this field, with LLMs being increasingly complex and trained on larger sets of data of text-based human language (OpenAI 2024b; 2024c; e.g., OpenAI 2022). The most advanced models include the Generative Pretrained Transformers (GPT) by OpenAI, such as the popular ChatGPT (OpenAI 2022). These GPT-models have proven capable of closely mimicking not just human language (Jansen et al. 2023; e.g., Colette et al. 2024; OpenAI 2022), but also human cognition, performing comparably in terms of logic, mathematics, and communication (e.g., OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c). For example, GPT-4o (OpenAI 2024b) can process text, audio, and image input, making it easy for researchers to use it in various ways, while o1 (OpenAI 2024c) can engage in complex reasoning that has enabled it to outperform physics PhDs. The prospect of simulating human behavior using such models has been recognized by researchers (e.g., Bail 2024).
