For example, LLMs have previously seen success in simulating patients to help train medical doctors (e.g., Holderried et al. 2024; Pang et al. 2024). A reliance on LLMs, however, restricts the application of the SCF to language-based mostly-online virtual environments, since the use of these models generally require a stimuli expressible through natural language in the form of a prompt, and efficient use of these models generally involve making online requests to the LLM using an application programming interface (API, De 2023), which require a stable internet connection. However, since text-as-data approaches are becoming more popular (e.g., Alrababah and Blaydes 2021; Barber and Rivero 2014; Chadefaux 2014; Daigneault et al. 2018; Hollibaugh 2019; Van Atteveldt et al. 2017), this limitation to a text-based virtual environment is nonetheless unlikely to substantially reduce the SCFs general applicability to researchers. At the same time, while their performance can be considered impressive, such models still have limitations (e.g., Edyko et al. 2023; Koga and Du 2024; Lecler et al. 2023; Obaid et al. 2023; Park and Choi 2024; Saka et al. 2024; Shea and Ma 2023; Zhang et al. 2024), and one might question whether models trained on natural language can be expected to sufficiently capture the nuances of human behavior.

To build a case for LLMs being capable of emulating human behavior, or at least behavior as it is expressed in natural language, and why such research would even be meaningful in the first place, it should be emphasized that the recognized functionalist view in psychology makes no innate distinction between the mental states of humans and mechanical operations of computers (Farrell 2014: 88, 398-403; for a general introduction and criticisms, see, e.g., Farrell 2014: 340-359; Hempel 1959; Rosenberg 2016: 195-210; for an example, see, e.g., Elster 1983). In this view (Farrell 2014: 111), it would be considered entirely meaningful to investigate human behavior through simulated modelling, since what is essential for understanding such behavior is not the substance of the unit being investigated but the function of their behavior. For example, the question of whether an LLM needs to possess consciousness (Eysenck and Keane 2020: 767-800) to emulate human behavior is entirely dependent on whether the distinct functions of consciousness are relevant for the specific behavior being studied. That is, if the functions of consciousness for the studied behavior can be adequately modeled and emulated, research using these models are just as meaningful and valid. Viewed alternatively using behaviorism (Farrell 2014: 362-389), intrapsychic differences between an LLM and humans, such as the presence of consciousness, would be entirely irrelevant, and any scientific inquiry will yield meaningful insights as long as their behavior are indistinguishable.

As to whether LLMs trained on natural language could be expected to sufficiently capture the nuances of human behavior, social psychologists and linguistics have long argued that language, thoughts, and behavior, while distinct phenomena, are closely linked (Holtgraves 2013; Lucy 1992; Thibodeau and Boroditsky 2011; Whorf 2011[1956]; e.g., Carpenter and Drabick 2011; Chen 2013; Fausey and Boroditsky 2010; Gao et al. 2015). Natural language is a medium for communicating information (Lyons 1991), and the types of data transferable in this manner are numerous. For example, information about the characteristics of objects (e.g., their color and shape), groups (e.g., their shared identity and goals), and individuals (e.g., their values and beliefs) can be communicated through natural language. Communication does not necessitate the transfer of information between individuals, since individuals sometimes engage in subvocal talking (i.e., thinking, Farrell 2014: 377-378), which can also occur vocally (i.e., by talking to oneself), and these types of communication are similarly communicable through natural language, showcasing just how nuanced human behavior can be captured through language. This is mostly achieved by language providing a formalized syntax, grammar, and vocabulary for expressing past and present thoughts, relations, experiences, feelings, values, and intended behavior in a structured, consistent, and predictable manner (Anderson 2020: 375-448; Eysenck and Keane 2020: 461-568; Lyons 1991). At the same time, language is undergoing constant adaptation to human requirements for communication (e.g., the term Synthetic Causal Framework was invented to denote the concepts introduced in this paper), making it relatively reliable in terms of capturing the nuances of old and new behavior. Especially relevant is the consideration that language can be used to communicate ones intended behavior, which can be considered an imperfect proxy for actual behavior (Ajzen and Fishbein 1977; Back et al. 2009; Zanna et al. 1980), since stated behavior is not necessarily equivalent to actual behavior.

The ability of language to capture the nuances of human behavior is further supported by personality psychology (Larsen et al. 2021), where trait-based approaches have relied on the lexical hypothesis (Galton 1884) to derive distinct personality traits that capture large parts of human behavior. This lexical hypothesis states that as language has evolved, the most relevant characteristics to distinguish individuals from each other have been incorporated into our language as distinct words. This ties into the use of language as being revelatory of the intraphychic state of individuals, with communication patterns and choice of words being predictive of the psychological states and social behavior of an individual (Chung et al. 2007; Pennebaker et al. 2003). But language not only expresses behavior in a nuanced manner, it also shapes thought patterns on which actions are based. (Bandura 1999: 195). This means it also affects behavior by structuring our thoughts (Farrell 2014: 261), with some arguing that language even structures our perceptions of reality (i.e., the hypothesis of linguistic relativity, Lucy 1992; Whorf 2011[1956]; e.g., Boroditsky 2001; Fausey and Boroditsky 2011). That language shapes our thoughts and behavior is, for example, evidenced by framing (Tversky and Kahneman 1981) and priming (Bargh and Chartrand 2000), which often consists of a text-based information, communicated through natural language, that affects behavior by structuring our thoughts, either by presenting fragmented information or making some information salient (Weingarten et al. 2016). Such research demonstrates that human preferences and behavior are not fixed nor entirely determined on our genetic predisposition and the entirety of our lived experiences, but, consistent with the view of human reason as being bounded (Elster 1989/1990; March 1994; Simon 1955), instead vary in relation to the salience of information communicated through natural language. Accordingly, it could be expected that an LLM, despite lacking genes, consciousness, and lived experiences, if provided with enough relevant information about a particular context, could emulate human preferences and behavior, at least as they are expressed using natural language. Given these considerations, language would seem to capture many relevant nuances of human behavior, making human behavior somewhat predictable from natural language, and since LLMs have been trained on natural language (Ornstein et al. 2024), they can arguably be expected to, albeit imperfectly, predict human behavior.

3.2.2 Simulated Data

The choice of the SCF to mimic human behavior using LLMs to make non-manipulable theorized causes manipulable invites concerns regarding the appropriateness of essentially simulating data for research. Simulated data is often used by researchers in statistics to investigate the properties of estimators, since simulations allow them to control every underlying aspect of the data (e.g., Green and Yang 2009; Hanmer and Kalkan 2013; Homburg and Dobartz 1992; Hu and Bentler 1999; Jackson 2003; MacCallum 1990; Sheng and Sheng 2012). While concerns regarding the inference of simulated results to real world applications could plausibly be justified, such inferences underlie numerous approaches to research, and are, as mentioned, consistent with functionalist and behaviorist psychology (Farrell 2014: 88, 111, 362-389, 398-403). For example, the statistical method of bootstrapping (Efron 1979, 2003; Efron and Tibshirani 1994) is used to make inferences to the real-world, and this involves simulating counterfactual samples of real-world data to obtain a sampling distribution of the estimates, their usefulness for inference generally outcompeting analytical approaches in terms of robustness (Angrist and Pischke 2009: 293-308; King and Roberts 2014). For the non-parametric bootstrap (Efron and Tibshirani 1994; e.g., Barber and Thompson 2000), this is done by permuting data (i.e., re-sample data with replacement), assuming that the unit characteristics in the data are proportional to their prevalence in the population, while the parametric bootstrap (Efron and Tibshirani 1994; e.g., Studer 2021) involves assuming a specific probability distribution for the estimates and computing sampling distributions using Monte Carlo simulation (Robert and Casella 2013; Rubinstein and Kroese 2016). This is similarly done in Bayesian statistics (Bayes and Price 1763; Gelman et al. 2014; Kruschke 2014; Laplace 2009[1814]; McElreath 2019) with the use of Markov-Chain Monte Carlo methods (Brooks et al. 2011; Duane et al. 1987; Gelman and Rubin 1992; Metropolis et al. 1953), which like the parametric bootstrap, involves parametric simulations. These methods have from a statistical-theoretical standpoint numerous advantages, and they are generally considered valid when making inferences to the real-world (e.g., Gelman et al. 2021; Imai and Tingley 2012: 223-224; King et al. 2000: 352; Pawitan 2001: 122). Besides relying on simulations for statistical inference, they are also used when encountering real-world limitations of the phenomena being studied. For example, in the field of social dilemmas (van Lange et al. 2013), simulations underlie agent-based modeling, which are models used to estimate the actions of individuals in relation to social dilemmas across a number of trials too large to feasibly be conducted with human participants (van Lange et al. 2013: 31; Macy and Willer 2002), and this is again entirely consistent with a functionalist view of social research (Farrell 2014: 88, 398-403). This means that the reliance on simulated data is not necessarily inappropriate for research, and it can be emphasized that as with any computer simulation, it becomes important to collect actual data, contrast the results against the simulation results, and then address the question of why there are deviations between the modeled and actual results. (van Lange et al. 2013: 31) As such, similar to the bootstrap, Bayesian statistics, and agent-based modeling, the employment of simulations in the SCF do not automatically make results invalid nor meaningless. Instead, it poses an empirical question regarding the quality of the simulated data and the ability to infer results to human populations, something that the SCF must be validated against.

In terms of data quality, consistent with the mantra of garbage-in-garbage-out (GIGO, Yoder-Wise 2023), the ability of the SCF to provide reliable causal inferences hinges in part on its external validity, since its fundamental aim is to generalize results to human populations. To take advantage of the aforementioned fact that LLM have been trained on a plethora of data containing natural language expressions of human thoughts, values, and behavior (cf. OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; 2022; Ornstein et al. 2024), which would expectedly allow it to closely emulate human behavior as expressed through natural language, the SCF will simulate human units by using an LLM to behave as each unit. This means that the SCF produces results based on LLM-driven inferences of human behavior. Given that the external validity of this behavior is critical, the SCF will involve several procedures that serve to make the LLM-based behavior as realistic as possible. The first step involves supplying the LLM with a prompt detailing relevant characteristics of each human unit. Since LLMs are inherently text-processing neural networks that generate a probability-based output based on the input (cf. OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; 2022; Ornstein et al. 2024), supplying the model with the characteristics of each simulated unit will likely enable it to more accurately infer the types of language-based behavior of an individual with those specific characteristics (cf. Chung et al. 2007; Pennebaker et al. 2003). While the relevancy of characteristics will likely differ between research topics, human characteristics that are generally considered relevant include those related to their sex, age, income, education, and geography (Memon et al. 2024). Researchers applying the SCF are encouraged to consider characteristics beyond those mentioned here, since consistent with concerns of latent measurement precision (cf. Bakker and Lelkes 2018; Cred et al. 2012), the greater the amount of simulated characteristics, the more precise the LLM can plausibly be expected to realistically and generalizably infer human behavior when controlling simulated units. At the same time, researchers should note that, just like humans (cf. Anderson 2020: 171-244; Eysenck and Keane 2020: 239-392), LLMs have a finite limit of how much information they can process and retain (cf. OpenAI 2025a), so the most relevant characteristics in relation to the research topic should likely take precedence. As such, by explicitly specifying these characteristics and supplying them to the LLM, it is expected that its ability to realistically emulate humans will expectedly increase.

The second consideration is that, like with any human data (Aronow and Samii 2016; Deaton and Cartwright 2018), the external validity of the simulations are closely related to how representative the simulated units are of the population of interest. If data on the entire population of interest is available, external validity is generally not a concern (Imai et al. 2008), but since the simulation of every human in a population would likely be unfeasible for a practical implementation of the SCF, the framework will be developed with a reliance on samples of simulated human units in mind, making external validity a concern. Generalizing from any sample to a population, it is an ideal that the unit characteristics in the sample are proportional to their prevalence in the population, since sample-population imbalances can produce errors (e.g., Type M and S) if effects vary across characteristics (Gelman et al. 2021: 59; Gelman and Carlin 2014; Imai et al. 2008). A sample with characteristics representative of the population is typically achieved through random sampling (Stock and Watson 2019: 108; Thompson 2012), where each unit has the same probability of being included in the sample. However, since the SCF will rely on LLM-based simulated units, a random sample from a population cannot be achieved in the conventional manner, for example, by distributing an online survey. Instead, the SCF will involve a simulated random sample, which will specifically be done by considering representativeness solely with respect to the aforementioned relevant characteristics. To apply random sampling to the simulation of these characteristics, it is necessary to obtain the prevalence of these characteristics in the population of interest. This may be unfeasible for some applications, but census data often contain such micro-level data, or at the very least, estimates of them (e.g., the IPUMS for the US Population, Ruggles et al. 2024). To then mimic random sampling, it is ideal if the simulated random sampling relies on the joint probability of characteristics (i.e., the probability of a characteristic conditional on all other characteristics), since different combinations of characteristics may not have equal probability of occurring in the population. For example, suppose that the population of interest is the voter population of the United States and that the characteristics to simulate are race (e.g., Caucasian and Afro-American) and party affiliation (e.g., Democrat and Republican). Here, it is known that Afro-Americans, compared to Caucasians, have greater probability of being affiliated with the Democratic Party than the Republican Party (Wallace et al. 2009), so it would be incorrect for the simulation to assume that the probability of being a Republican and a Caucasian is the same as the probability of being Republican and Afro-American (i.e., \(Pr(Republican \ | \ Caucasian) \ne Pr(Republican \ | \ Afro-American)\)). Accordingly, a simulated random sampling that simulates characteristics with independent probability would fail to account for this interdependence of characteristics, which is why the SCF will simulate random sampling using joint probability. This procedure for simulated random sampling can be implemented by transforming the census data into a stratification matrix (cf. Gelman and Little 1997), which is characterized by containing the proportion of each combination of the characteristics in the population, which in Frequentist statistics is equivalent to the joint probability. Analogous to the aforementioned bootstrapping (cf. Efron 1979, 2003; Efron and Tibshirani 1994), joint probability random sampling is implemented by randomly sampling with replacement from the stratification matrix, with the sampling probability being the (estimated) population proportion of each combination of characteristics. As evidenced by the equivalent logic of the bootstrap (cf. Efron 1979, 2003; Efron and Tibshirani 1994), this (asymptotically) guarantees a sample representative of the population with respect to the characteristics. A limitation of this procedure is the reliance on census data, which can contain measurement error and may not be current, easily available, nor contain measures of all relevant characteristics. For these instances, it may be necessary to simulate characteristics with outdated population estimates and/or without accounting for interdependencies. Nevertheless, the use of a joint-probability-based random sampling helps ensure that the characteristics supplied as the basis of the LLM-driven simulated units are sampled in proportion to their prevalence in the population of interest, increasing the external validity of the SCF.

3.2.3 Life-Histories

To further improve the ability of the SCF to provide results that generalize to human populations, the literature on life-histories (Bertaux 1981; Rosenthal 2018; Schtze 1997, 2008) is consulted. To understand why the concepts of life-histories can be used within the SCF to make the behavior of the simulated units more realistic, a brief review is presented here. A life-history can be considered a narrative gestalt that must be envisioned as an ordered sequence of personal experiences (Schtze 2008: 168; cited in Wygnaska 2019: 116, emphasis in original), whose orderliness implies the inner identity development of the biography incumbent (Schtze 2008: 168; cited in Wygnaska 2019: 116). This means that a life-history is a structured autobiographical narrative, and the fact that it expresses a persons psychological construction of self-identity based in intuition (Schtze 2008: 164; Wygnaska 2019: 115) is supported by evidence of people forming spontaneous narratives of self-lived experiences (Riemann 2014: 27; e.g., Alea 2008; Bellana et al. 2022). In sociology, this concept is the foundation for the life history method, a style of interview, where the interviewer lets the interviewee tell their life history (Riemann 2014: 23; Wygnaska 2019: 113). The method has seen extensive use (for review, see, e.g., Goodson 2001; for critcisms, see, e.g., Hamel 2013), including case studies of people having undergone traumatic episodes (Gaulejac 1997; e.g., Riemann 2014; Wygnaska 2019). Being the storyteller of their own life, the emphasis of this method is on the interviewees subjective experiences, and they have generally free constrains on how to order and frame their life and what experiences to talk about. A life-history can include information about the origin of the interviewees parents, their childhood, family dynamics, ethnicity, moral and cultural values, education, employment, social interactions, and experiences as an adult (e.g., Riemann 2014; Williams and Khan 2020; Wygnaska 2019). The main advantage of this method is the possibility for the narrator to recreate in his/her story, the significant biographical processes that shaped his/her life in subsequent phases of biography, experienced situations, and the social framework in which his/her biographical processes took place. (Kamierska and Schtze 2013: 131; cited in Wygnaska 2019: 115). This means that the interview does not have to extensively cover all aspects of their life, letting the interviewee choose to highlight what they perceive as the most defining events of their life. Based on the life-history, the researchers then attempts to explain motivations, attitudes, and values that shape human behavior and the flow of human affairs (Stanfield 1987) by basing the analysis on how the interviewee constructs meaning around the events of their life (Schtze 2008: 131; Wygnaska 2019: 116). Since this narration may cover traumatic events and socially undesirable behavior of the interviewee, trust between interviewee and interviewer are critical for the quality of the information divulged in this manner (Riemann 2014: 23; Wygnaska 2019: 115), and if this is achieved, even socially undesirable behavior can be divulged.

This concept of life-histories can be used by the SCF to further characterize simulated units. Compared to manually specifying every relevant characteristic, by letting the LLM serve a the autobiographical narrator of the simulated unit, the relevant characteristics assigned to each unit (e.g., gender, age, income), based on the aforementioned joint probability sampling procedure, can be used to the LLM to further flesh out the unit through the generation of a life-history containing more characteristics and information about the unit. Stated differently, prompting the LLM to generate a life-history allows the generation of greater nuances about the individual, their identity, and behavior. Similar to the rationale for supplying the LLM with explicitly assigned relevant characteristics, basing the life-history on the assigned characteristics serves to ensure that the contents of the life-history are probabilistically determined conditional on the assigned characteristics. Compared to merely supplying the assigned characteristics to the LLM as a list, this also serves to embed the assigned characteristics in a realistic manner within the narrative structure of the life-history, allowing them to contribute to the creation of a more ecologically valid (cf. Schmuckler 2001) autobiographical identity of each simulated unit. This, of course, requires that the LLM generates a life-history that includes and is consistent with the assigned characteristics. While these are relevant concerns, they are partly empirical and can be evaluated by the researcher by comparing the assigned characteristics with the generated life-history. As such, prompting the LLM to generate life-histories based on the assigned characteristics are likely to provide more information on the type of individual that the LLM is to emulate, thus increasing the realism and external validity of the LLM-based behavior to human populations. Similar to the specification of relevant characteristics to simulate for the simulate units, note again practical limitations on the length of life-histories, which need to be short enough for the LLM to process and retain it when controlling the behavior of the synthetic units.

3.2.4 Synthetic Units

The synthesis of simulated characteristics and the LLM-generated life-history is expected to produce units that when controlled by the LLM produces substantially more realistic and generalizable behavior than simulated units lacking life-histories. This is because the LLM, by merit of being trained on real-world data (OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; Ornstein et al. 2024), expectedly infuses the researcher-assigned characteristics with real-life characteristics, making the product not strictly simulated nor strictly real. As such, units produced by the synthesis of simulated characteristics and LLM-determined life-histories will, borrowing Hegelian dialectical terminology (Fichte 1970; Hegel 2014; though see Kaufmann 1959: 154), be denoted as synthetic units to clarify a conceptual distinction from simulated units. The concept of synthetic units borrows from the existing concept of synthetic data (e.g., Abadie et al. 2010; Agarwal et al. 2023; Emam et al. 2020; Strbing et al. 2023). Such data similarly involves a synthesis between real-world and simulated data, and it has been used to circumvent privacy laws, where data containing personal information is used to generate realistic but simulated data that can be shared without violating such laws (Abowd et al. 2004; Emam et al. 2020). On a similar note, synthetic data is also used to train deep learning models aimed at real-world application (Nikolenko 2021; Kennedy et al. 2024; e.g., Zivenko et al. 2025). Consistent with the SCFs reliance on LLM to generate synthetic units, previous studies have generated synthetic data using statistical models (Christensen et al. 2019: 187; e.g., Kinney et al. 2011), and the synthetic units produced by an LLM with the SCF can thus be considered to constitute a special case of synthetic data that is entirely valid for the basis of research. This also means that a key step of applying the SCF is thus the transformation of simulated units into synthetic units by generating life-histories based on relevant characteristics that are sampled in proportion to the population.

With synthetic units having been produced, it is then possible to conduct a study using these units in place of human respondents. This has the caveat that synthetic respondents can be manipulated in many more ways compared to human units, since there are fewer practical, ethical, and cost concerns. This means that a previously non-manipulable theorized cause could in principle be manipulated with the SCF, though a key assumption here is that the manipulation is meaningfully expressible through natural language and can be processed as input by the model (e.g., text, images, etc.). For example, if the purpose of the study is to evaluate the effects of a new pharmaceutical drug on human welfare, the LLM-driven synthetic respondents conceptualized by the SCF will likely yield invalid results because the LLM necessitates that the phenomena under investigation can be meaningfully captured in existing language-based expressions. The effects of a new drug fails to meet this criteria, because the effects of pharmaceutics mostly involve biochemical processes that may not be distinctly expressed in natural language. Accordingly, the use of the SCF in medical research is likely invalid and should only be considered with utmost precaution due to the direct ramifications of such research on human health. With these considerations in mind, the specific procedure used in the SCF to achieve an exogenous manipulation can then be outlined.

3.2.5 Exogenous Manipulation

For the SCF to provide an internal validity compareble to RCTs, the manipulation of the theorized cause in synthetic units must be exogenous to reliably avoid confounding (cf. Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49; Wooldridge 2019: 54-56). In line with the aforementioned considerations on this, Guido W. Imbens and Donald B. Rubin (2015: 31) have outlined theoretical restrictions on what constitutes an exogenous assignment mechanism, which involve it being individualistic, probabilistic, and unconfounded. These restrictions apply to the aforementioned RAM of RCTs, where each unit is individually assigned to a group manipulation condition (e.g., treatment or control), with equal probability (e.g., 50%), and independently of all other factors. This means that the RAM exogenously assigns any individual to any one manipulation condition. However, recall from the Potential Outcomes Framework and equations 1.4-1.5, how this procedure can be viewed as the result of the inability to assign the same unit to multiple manipulation conditions due to a lack of independence and simultaneity (equations 1.2-1.3), and that the RAM as a result only prevents confounding in an unbiased and asymptotic manner (Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 6). By instead relying on synthetic units, the SCF offers a synthetic solution to the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference (cf. Holland 1986), since each unit can be independently and simultaneously assigned to every manipulation condition. This is because each synthetic respondent can in principle be exposed to one level of a manipulation theorized to impact the potential outcome, \(Y_i(X_{x, i})\), while independently and simultaneously being exposed to another level of manipulation, \(Y_i(X_{x', i})\). The independence of assignment occurs because the LLM determining the behavior of the synthetic units in each manipulation condition is unaware of previous, cuncurrent, and future manipulations of each unit, making the potential outcomes independent and thus avoiding pre- and post-manipulation biases (cf. Linos and Twist 2018; McElreath 2019: 170-176; Montgomery et al. 2018). The simultaneity of assignment occurs because multiple requests to the LLM can be made at the same time, which eliminates time as a confounder, because it would not vary between the manipulation conditions (equation 1.3). The results of this is that a counterfactual outcome, one for each manipulation condition, can be measured in an unbiased manner. Causal effects are then computed as the difference of each synthetic unit in one manipulation condition to the same unit in another manipulation condition (equation 1.2), meaning that all unit- and time-invariant factors are subtracted away, producing a causal effect arguably more reliable than one produced by an RCT. Under these conditions, not just average causal effects, but individual causal effects can be estimated without confounding (cf. Westreich et al. 2015). As such, in the SCF, all synthetic respondents are assigned to every manipulation condition using a simultaneous and independent exogenous assignment mechanism (SIXAM). The SIXAM of the SCF meets the aforementioned criteria by being individualistic (cf. Imbens and Rubin 2015: 34), since the probability of being assigned to a manipulation condition is independent of the manipulation condition of other units; it is probabilistic (cf. Imbens and Rubin 2015: 38), since it meets the requirement of every unit having the possibility of being assigned to any manipulation condition (with that probability being 1); and it is unconfounded (cf. Imbens and Rubin 2015: 38), since the assigned manipulation condition does not depend on the potential outcomes. As such, the SIXAM of the SCF differs from the RAM of RCTs, and causal effects are derived within the SCF through an independent and simultaneous generation of counterfactual outcomes that are compared across synthetic respondents (see equation 1.2), enabling unbiased estimates of causal effects through the elimination of confounders by design.

The simultaneity of the simultaneous and independent generation of counterfactual outcomes outlined above serves to eliminate time confounding results when employing equation 1.2, for reasons previously outlined in relation to equation 1.3. While this paper mostly serves to outline the theoretical framework of the SCF (though for a proof-of-concept, see below), with specific implementations of the SCF likely varying across research topics, a theoretical basis on how to implement a simultaneous generation is provided here for clarity. The ability to simultaneously generate counterfactual outcomes for the same synthetic unit is made possible by the reliance on LLMs, with multiple LLMs being available for use at the same time. Hence, a synthetic unit can be operated by one LLM under one manipulation condition, while the same synthetic unit is operated by a different yet identical LLM under another manipulation condition. This is perhaps most easily achieved by relying on an API for the LLM (e.g., OpenAIs API, 2025a). By specifying the different manipulation conditions for the synthetic unit, a parallel process (cf. Gottlieb and Almasi 1989; Ozdoganlar and Endres 2021[1999]) can be used to simultaneously call the API, one time for each manipulation condition, allowing the LLM to expectedly generate an outcome for each manipulation condition with no time difference nor dependency on the generation of other outcomes under different manipulation conditions. To conceptually denote this parallel processing-procedure in relation to the SCF, this simultaneous and independent exogenous manipulation and generation of counterfactual outcomes will, with inspiration from Sara Steegen, Francis Tuerlinckx, Andrew Gelman, and Wolf Vanpaemel (2016), be denoted as parallel worlds-estimation. This helps emphasize the notion that the employment of equation 1.2 to compute causal effects makes a simultaneity assumption to ensure its equivalency with equation 1.3. This simultaneity assumption states that the point in time for measuring the counterfactual outcomes for any unit do not vary with the manipulation assigned to each unit. Note that this assumption mostly matters for the computation of unconfounded individual causal effects, since the average causal effect, just like for RCTs (Ho et al. 2007: 207-208), is unconfounded if the points in time for measuring the counterfactual outcomes do not vary across the manipulation groups. As such, the SCF solves the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference (cf. Holland 1986) by implementing a simultaneous and independent exogenous manipulation and generation of multiple counterfactual outcomes for each synthetic respondent, which are used to reliably isolate a causal effect through intra-unit comparisons of counterfactual outcomes. This identification strategy outlined for the SCF can account for the aforementioned fact that the mere assignment to any manipulation does not ensure the intended level of manipulation, and that the potential outcome could in fact depend on an interaction between the theorized cause and the manipulation levels (e.g., if the LLM infers a prior manipulation of the synthetic unit which interacts with an effect on the inferred outcome). This is achieved by modifying equation 1.2 using equation 1.5, resulting in the following:

\(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}, \underset{g_x, g_{x'}}{\Delta}, i} = (Y_i(X_{x, i}, C_i) \: | \: G = g_x) \: - \: (Y_i(X_{x', i}, C_i) \: | \: G = g_{x'})\) 1.6

As already stated, equation 1.6 involves the computation of individual treatment effect using intra-unit comparisons of counterfactual outcomes that have been generated using the parallel worlds-estimation procedure, which employs the aforementioned SIXAM. Unlike equation 1.2, equation 1.6 accounts for an interacting effect between the manipulation condition and the theorized cause by explicitly denoting the effect (i.e., \(D\)) as possibly conditional on the realized (i.e., \(x\) and \(x'\)) and intended levels of manipulations (i.e., \(g_x\) and \(g_{x'}\)). Aggregated to the group level, the identification strategy is equivalent to equation 1.5 and can be re-formalized for clarity as the following equation.

\(\mathbb{E}(D_{\underset{x, x'}{\Delta}, \underset{g_x, g_{x'}}{\Delta}}) = \mathbb{E}(Y(X_{x}, C) \: | \: G = g_x) \: - \: \mathbb{E}(Y(X_{x'}, C) \: | \: G = g_{x'})\) 1.7 (1.5)

To statistically estimate the causal effect, equations 1.6 and 1.7 specify it as the difference in potential outcomes across counterfactual manipulation conditions. This is easily estimable using the simple but powerful difference-in-means estimator, which is unbiased and requires few assumptions (Deaton and Cartwright 2018: 3; Gelman et al. 2021: 350-351). For designs with more than two manipulation conditions, the identification strategy of the SCF can easily be generalized to an arbitrary number of manipulation conditions, though the estimation of a causal effect with more than 2 groups would likely necessitate introducing more assumptions about the functional form of the relationship between the theorized cause and outcome (e.g., non-linearity). Note also that since the estimation involves intra-unit comparisons, the identification strategy of the SCF as outlined here guarantees perfect balance between groups in terms of unit-invariant confounders (though time-invariant confounders will also be balance if the aforementioned simultaneity assumption holds), which is different from the mere unbiased and asymptotic properties of balance in RCTs. This procedure is similar to and equally efficient as blocking (Gelman et al. 2021: 347-353), which involves a stratified randomization based on measured confounders that guarantees balance on those confounders (Imai et al. 2008: 489; Duflo et al. 2007: 3925). Perhaps most importantly in terms of efficiency, by merit of making such intra-unit comparisons, the SCF obtains perfect balance on both measured and unmeasured confounders.

Inferring a causal estimate derived from the sample to the population using this procedure outlined for SCF can then be done using standard statistical inference, for example, with parametric or non-parametric statistical models. However, for inferential statistics to be reliable, they need to account for each synthetic unit having been measured multiple times. This is because of the fact that data derived from the same unit can be autocorrelated (Stock and Watson 2019: 375; Gelman et al. 2021: 459), which produces downward-biased estimates of inferential uncertainty. Autocorrelation can be mitigated by accounting for the clustered structure of the data, with a common approach being multilevel models (Gelman and Hill 2007). These can be easily implemented using standard statistical software packages16, meaning the causal inference can be easily derived from data generated by the SCF using standard statistical inference.

3.2.6 Formalization

With the theory underlying the framework outlined above, the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) is here defined as a theoretical framework for drawing reliable causal inference when the theorized cause in non-manipulable in human populations, achieved through the use of LLM-generated synthetic units that enable independent and simultaneous intra-unit comparisons of counterfactual outcomes. As outlined here, the SCF can primarily be considered a theoretical contribution to the literature on causal inference, with its scope of application being that of the social and behavioral sciences (cf. Wright 2015), specifically studies that rely on human populations, where the theorized cause is non-manipulable. Its central assumption is that the theorized cause and outcome must be meaningfully expressible through natural language, and researchers applying the SCF must be able to justify why this assumption holds for their particular research topic. Since it is typically unclear what specific data an LLM have been trained on, researchers should also justify why they use a specific LLM and why they expect the theorized cause and outcome to have been expressed in data that this LLM could have been trained on. These are prerequisites for establishing why the LLM can be expected to infer human behavior in relation to an effect of the theorized cause on the outcome.

This formalization of the SCF can be considered an an extension of the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (cf. Holland 1986; Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005), with its fundamental definition of a causal effect being the difference in potential outcomes varying solely with respect to the theorized cause. The causal identification strategy of the SCF involves making simultaneous and independent intra-unit comparisons of the counterfactual outcomes, with the equation used for estimating this at the individual level being equation 1.6, a modified form of the aforementioned equation 1.2. At the group level, the equation used for estimating the expected causal effect is equation 1.7, which is equivalent to the aforementioned equation 1.5. By using the parallel worlds-estimation procedure, the SCF applies a simultaneous and independent exogenous assignment mechanism (SIXAM) to assign each synthetic unit to every manipulation condition, with a counterfactual outcome being measured for each, allowing intra-unit comparisons of the counterfactual outcomes to eliminate all unit- and time-invariant confounders. Should the parallel worlds-estimation procedure fail or be unavailable to researchers (e.g., parallel processing requires a computational core for each manipulation condition), to reliably estimate individual causal effects, researchers may alternatively rely on the simultaneity assumption. However, researchers invoking this assumption should note that if it is violated, time may confound causal estimates at the individual level, but similar to RCTs, not at the group level. While these considerations together ensure a high internal validity of the SCF, its external validity is less certain. Such concerns are mitigated by procedures embedded within the SCF, foremost through the generation of synthetic units from characteristics simulated for their relevance to the research topic. This simulation involves census data, where a joint probability random sampling procedure is used to ensure that the characteristics simulated are proportional to their prevalence in the population of interest. These characteristics are then used to generate further characteristics as part of a life-history (cf. Bertaux 1981), that while being expectedly less important than the simulated characteristics, nonetheless serve to add human-like nuance to the synthetic units, so that the LLM-driven behavior of each synthetic unit becomes more realistic and generalizable to humans. To provide an ease of overview of the formalization of the SCF and the workflow involved in its use, a flowchart is provided in figure 3.2.

Figure 3.2: The Synthetic Causal Framework

\(\ \)

NOTE: Flowchart. \({}^{[1]}\!\)Joint probability sampling is used to simulate relevant unit characteristics in proportion to their prevalence in the population. \({}^{[2]}\!\)Simulated unit characteristics and instructions to generate a life-history are provided in a prompt to the LLM. SIXAM = Simultaneous and independent exogenous assignment mechanism. \({}^{[3]}\!\)Parallel processing is used to simultaneously, independently, and exogenously assign each synthetic unit to both manipulation conditions. With the LLM controlling the behavior of the synthetic units based on the generated life-histories, a counterfactual outcome for each manipulation condition is measured. Note that the dashed circle indicates the area of the design where the parallel worlds-estimation is implemented. \({}^{[4]}\!\)Data is transposed into a long-format to account for the multiple outcome measurements of each synthetic unit.

Having outlined the SCF in this manner, there are several considerations worthy of a brief discussion. It should be noted that the reliance on generating synthetic data for causal inference is not new (e.g., Mazaheri et al. 2024). For instance, the previously mentioned synthetic control methodology (Abadie et al. 2010, 2015; Abadie and LHour 2021) serves to enable causal inference through the generation of counterfactual outcomes. This method is often used in case studies of countries and the effects of policy implementations, with the counterfactual outcome being constructed from the outcomes of other units (e.g., countries that did not implement the policy, Bilgel and Galle 2015; Birdsall 2011; Gilchrist et al. 2024; Powell 2022). While this method does provide justification for a causal interpretation and is relatively easily implemented in conventional software (e.g., Abadie et al. 2011), it does possess the same previously mentioned issues of adjusting for observables, since the synthetic conterfactual outcome is constructed from measured characteristics across groups in the data, leaving results possibly confounding by the failure to match on unobservables. Another limitation of that approach is the necessity for researchers to possess time-series data, reducing it applicability by researchers (though applicability is expanding, e.g., Abadie and LHour 2021; Arkhangelsky et al. 2021; Pang et al. 2022). While both methods essentially involve the inference of counterfactual outcomes, unlike the synthetic control method, the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) proposed here does not solely match on observables and does not require time-series data, making it more broadly applicable.

On a related note, the internal and external validity of the SCFs reliance on LLMs may be criticized on the theoretical grounds that the generation of counterfactual outcomes essentially involves the LLM making stochastic predictions conditional on the life-history of each synthetic respondent. Implicit in such criticism is the premise that such behavior is fundamentally different from how humans behave. However, for this criticism to hold, the generation of outcomes in humans must substantively differ from synthetic respondents. That is, humans must not be stochastic nor condition their responses on their life-history. But researchers consistently assume that, and find evidence consistent with, human behavior being stochastic and conditional on their life-history (e.g., their gender, age, education, income, political affiliations, Memon et al. 2024), where every aspect of ones identity or experiences do not matter equally, nor are they equally salient across different moments. Analogous to an LLM making a stochastic prediction of counterfactual outcomes conditional on a life-history, human respondents similarly make a guess about the outcome (e.g., their preference for a political leader) based on salient components of their life-history, which may change at a later time, for example, due to the acquirement of new experiences and information. Similarly in terms of stochasticity, when making statistical inference from data consisting of human self-report data, a common assumption is that of random measurement error (Gelman et al. 2021: 49-50; Levy and Mislevy 2020; Stock and Watson 2019), where any human response is characterized by some idiosyncratic and stochastic error component, and the concepts of inter and intra-rater reliability specifically serve to account for the stochasticity of human rating (Saal et al. 1980). Accordingly, an LLM predicting a preference based on the life-history and characteristics of the synthetic respondent is not inherently different a human respondent forming a preference based on their characteristics, life-history and context of the situation.

While these considerations arguably does lend some credence to the external validity of the SCF, it should be noted that LLMs currently do possess numerous limitations (e.g., Edyko et al. 2023; Koga and Du 2024; Lecler et al. 2023; Obaid et al. 2023; Park and Choi 2024; Saka et al. 2024; Shea and Ma 2023; Zhang et al. 2024). While future models may solve some of these issues (e.g., OpenAI 2024c), a central concern for this paper is whether results produced by current LLMs allow researchers to implement the SCF and expect results to generalize to human populations. To test the external validity of the SCF, and provide a proof-of-concept for how researchers can implement it, the remainder of this paper is therefore dedicated to validating the SCF against human data and assess whether its results are generalizable.

4 Methodology

To justify the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) empirically, as well as help researchers implement it, a conceptual replication study (cf. Isager et al. 2023: 2; Nosek et al. 2012: 619) is undertaken that simultaneously serves as a demonstrative proof-of-concept. This section first details that the external validity of the SCF will be validated through a large-scale replication (n = 1,009) of the established relationship between deservingness and welfare support (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019). This involves a theoretical justification of this relationship, with the exact causal estimate to replicate being determined by conducting a meta-analysis (Eysenck 1995; Glass 1976; Sharpe and Poets 2020) on studies previously investigating it within the United States. The study then follows the illustrated workflow of the SCF (see figure 4.1) by implementing a joint-probability random sampling procedure to simulate random sampling from the adult population of the United States, making results expectedly more representative of that population. This is followed by specifying prompts for generating life-histories (cf. Bertaux 1981) and detailing code for making requests to the gpt-4o-mini LLM (OpenAI 2024a) using OpenAIs API (2025a), which serve to transform the simulated respondents into synthetic respondents, making their expected behavior more nuanced and realistic. The novel concept of a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) is then introduced, where the parallel worlds-estimation procedure is implemented for a simultaneous and independent exogenous manipulation of deservingness. Group balance and the simultaneity assumption are then assessed, followed by specifying the Multilevel Bayesian Generalized Robust Linear Model (cf. Brkner 2017, 2018) that is used in the analysis for identifying the causal effect of deservingness on welfare attitudes.

Figure 4.1: SCF-based Replication Design

\(\ \)

NOTE: Synthetic Causal Framework-flowchart. n = Sample size. \({}^{[1]}\!\)Based on population estimates from IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021), joint probability sampling is used to simulate relevant unit characteristics in proportion to their prevalence in the population. These unit characteristics are US state of residence, area type of residence, number of children in household, sex, age, marital status, ethonoracial group, level of education, employment status, annual household gross income in 2022 US dollars, preferred political party, and political ideology. \({}^{[2]}\!\)Simulated unit characteristics and instructions to generate a life-history are provided in a prompt to the API of the GPT-4o mini LLM (OpenAI 2024a). SIXAM = Simultaneous and independent exogenous assignment mechanism. \({}^{[3]}\!\)Parallel processing is used to simultaneously, independently, and exogenously assign each synthetic unit to manipulation conditions, where they are exposed to a lazy (Manipulation A) and an unlucky welfare recipient (Manipulation B). With the LLM controlling the behavior of the synthetic units based on the generated life-histories, a counterfactual outcome for each manipulation condition is measured, which is the support for restricting the welfare eligibility for the corresponding welfare recipient. Note that the dashed circle indicates the area of the design where the parallel worlds-estimation is implemented. \({}^{[4]}\!\)Data is transposed into a long-format to account for the two outcome measurements of each synthetic unit, doubling the sample size.

Following recent recommendations for reproducible and transparent research (e.g., Alister et al. 2021; Lenz and Sahn 2021; Open Science Collaboration 2015; Peng 2011; Ritchie 2021), this study subscribes to the open science standard (Christensen et al. 2019; Nosek et al. 2012, 2015). This means that the study is (1) an open project, whose development can be followed by the public; (2) that it uses open data, with raw data being made freely available; and (3) that it relies on open software by using the free and open-source R programming language (R Core Team 2024) and RStudio integrated development environment (IDE, Posit Team 2024), which is especially suited for data science (Welbers et al. 2017: 245) and reproducible research (Krotov and Tennyson 2018: 171), with code being provided as R syntax in the markdown (Gruber 2014) version of this file. This is all made available using the Open Science Framework (OSF), with materials provided on the project hub: DOI: 10.17605/OSF.IO/5P3M2 (Note that data and code are not made available in this preview version). Similarly, for transparency and reproducibility, software specifications, used R packages, descriptive statistics of the data, and details not covered in the main paper are provided in the appendix.

4.1 Deservingness Heuristic

To assess the external validity of the SCF, that is, the generalizability of results derived from synthetic respondents to human populations, this study seeks to replicate the established relationship between deservingness and welfare attitudes (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019). To understand the concepts involved in this relationship, and its usefulness for validating the SCF, a brief review of existing theory and results is provided.

The relationship between deservingness and welfare attitudes is founded in evolutionary psychology (Buss 2019), where substantial parts of human behavior are considered the product of evolution by natural selection (Darwin 1998; Futuyma and Kirkpatrick 2023). In this view, the three essential components of evolution - genetic variation, inheritance and differential reproductive success (Buss 2019: 7) - has lead to the human genome adapting physically, psychologically, and socially to the conditions of the environment (Buss 2009, 2019; Dawkins 1976; Elster 2007). With evolution by natural selection operating mostly at a slow pace, the human genome is generally considered adapted to an environment characteristic of a hunter-gatherer society (Buss 2019; e.g., Boyer and Petersen 2018; Van Prooijen and van Vugt 2018), meaning that it is mostly not adapted specifically for the modern society. In the long run, evolution produces adaptations useful for a particular environment, but these adaptations are not necessarily optimal and can prove disadvantageous across different environments (Boyer and Petersen 2018; Buss 2019; Li et al. 2018; Sperber and Hirschfeld 2004). While some of these adaptations have lead to predispositions for different types of behavior that vary across individuals (e.g., Claessens et al. 2020; Hibbing et al. 2019; Oxley et al. 2008; though see Bakker et al. 2020; Osmundsen et al. 2022), others are posited to produce mostly invariant predispositions in the form of cognitive modules in the brain (Kurzban and Aktipis 2007; Sperber and Hirschfeld 2004) that operate subconsciously, automatically, and mandatory (Cosmides et al. 2003: 173). Being specialized for making cost-efficient computational operations that affect our behavior by serving as decision heuristics (Kurzban and Aktipis 2007; Sperber and Hirschfeld 2004; e.g., Boyer and Petersen 2018; Pietraszewski et al. 2015), such modules are closely related to System I intuition-based thinking (Kahneman 2024; e.g., Haidt 2013; Haidt and Joseph 2004). It should be noted that while cognitive heuristics are generally theorized as being universal and thus invariant across populations, they are not necessarily utilized to the same extent across individuals (e.g., Aare et al. 2017), and like other predispositions (Hibbing et al. 2019: 26), they do not determine behavior in a monocausal manner, since biological and social phenomena likely interact (e.g., Hinsz et al. 2013). With cognitive modules functioning involving processes spanning different brain regions (Kurzban and Aktipis 2007; Sperber and Hirschfeld 2004), they are physical constructs, and similar to how other cognitive modules can become defunct due to a neurological disorder (e.g., people with prosopagnosia cannot recognize faces, Buss 2019: 253), some individuals may not possess nor be affected by a cognitive heuristic.

Since humans are social creatures and depend on cooperation with others to improve their reproductive success, this has lead to the development of social groups (Buss 2019), and cognitive modules on how to assess ingroup and outgroup members likely evolved to solve issues with whom to cooperate and how to redistribute goods (Fong et al. 2006). One such cognitive module has been denoted the deservingess heuristic (Aare and Petersen 2014; Petersen et al. 2011, 2012; Petersen 2012), and researchers state that it influences everyday judgments about interpersonal help giving and constitutes a key psychological basis for judgments about political help giving; that is, social welfare (Aare and Petersen 2014: 686). Consistent with related research (Feather 1999; Gilens 2000; Larsen 2006; Skitka and Tetlock 1993; van Oorschot 2000; Weiner 1995), this means that the deservingness heuristic assesses whether members are deserving or underserving of being redistributed goods (Aare and Petersen 2014: 686). An individual being assessed as low in deservingness can, for example, occur because they enjoy the benefits of the goods while being unwilling to invest effort to improve their circumstances (Aare and Petersen 2014: 687). By comparison, an individual may be assessed as high in deservingness because they are making an effort and trying but failing due to forces beyond their control (Aare and Petersen 2014: 687), which indicate that the perceived effort of a person is central in assessing their deservingness. The deservingness heuristic, similar to other heuristics, likely operates in an automatic and subconscious manner (Petersen et al. 2011) by regulating emotions (cf. Al-Shawaf et al. 2015), producing a behavioral response (e.g., a political attitude) by evoking a positive emotion for individuals deemed high in deservingness and a negative emotion for individuals low in deservingness (Petersen et al. 2012), which in turn affect political support toward welfare policies. Based on numerous studies across cultures (e.g., Aare and Petersen 2014; Appelbaum 2002; Meyer and Mulherin 1980; Petersen et al. 2012; Weiner 1995), the deservingness heuristic is likely a cognitive module universally shared across the human population due to the common issues of group cooperation (e.g., free-riding, Delton et al. 2012). Since cognitive heuristics are cost-efficient, they can make suboptimal evaluations due to relying on sparse information, and consistent with numerous studies (Allport 1954; Bodenhausen and Lichtenstein 1987; Macrae et al. 1994), researchers argue that it can operate simply through stereotypes (Aare and Petersen 2014: 687), which are defined as beliefs about the characteristics, attributes, and behaviors of members of certain groups (Hilton and von Hippel 1996: 240; cited in Aare and Petersen 2014: 687). This ties directly into the perceived effort of a person and means that the deservingness of a welfare recipient can be determined simply based on how much they resemble a stereotypical depiction of a lazy or unlucky welfare recipient (cf. Aare and Petersen 2014; Petersen et al. 2012). Taken together, the deservingness heuristic operates by taking in sparse information about individuals (e.g., lazy and unlucky stereotypes) and computes an affective response that exacts a causal effect on political support for social welfare policies. For an illustrative view, the operations of the deservingness heuristic underlying the relationship between deservingness and welfare attitudes are provided as a directed acyclic graph (DAG, Pearl 1988, 1993, 1995) in figure 4.2. Note that much of the aforementioned research is also somewhat consistent with evolution by cultural selection (cf. Dawkins 1976; Sperber 1976), since the deservingness heuristic could in principle be a learned heuristic universally shared across cultures, similar to numerous other cognitive heuristics stipulated to be social constructions (e.g., Kuklinski and Quirk 2000; Lau and Redlawsk 2001).

Figure 4.2: Relationship Between Deservingness & Welfare Support

\(\ \)

NOTE: Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG, Pearl 1988, 1993, 1995). Theorized causal relationship based on (Aare and Petersen 2014).

The relationship between deservingness and welfare attitudes has been directly replicated across numerous studies (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019). Since these are direct replications (cf. Isager et al. 2023: 2; Nosek et al. 2012: 619), they rely on highly similar methods, and for brevity, this review will only present the design of the original (i.e., Aare and Petersen 2014). In the original study, Lene Aare and Michael Bang Petersen (2014: 688) rely on cross-national, representative samples from the United States (US, n = 1,009) and Denmark (n = 1,006). Here, they employ a experimental survey design (cf. Gaines et al. 2006) containing three manipulation conditions, with the manipulations being validated text-based vignettes containing deservingness-cues in relation to a lazy, unlucky, and a control welfare recipient17 (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689; also used in Petersen et al. 2012). Survey participants are assigned to view either one of these vignettes using the aforementioned random assignment mechanism (RAM) characteristic of randomized controlled trials (RCTs, Coover and Angell 1907; Peirce and Jastrow 1885; Woodworth and Thorndike 1901), which together with its reliance on stratified random and representative samples (Aare and Petersen 2014: 688) means that their study is here considered capable of providing reliable causal inference. The theorized welfare support outcome is operationalized as political support for tightening the requirements for welfare eligibility of the shown welfare recipient: To what extent do you disagree or agree that the eligibility requirements for social welfare should be tightened for persons like him? (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689, emphasis in original), with the response being measured using a 7-point Likert (Likert 1932) response scale, ranging from Strongly disagree to Strongly agree. They consider relevant demographics to include gender, age, and education (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689), and they use Frequentist multiple linear models, estimated using ordinary least squares (OLS, Aare and Petersen 2014: 691), with all Dont know-responses being excluded from the analysis (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689). By comparison, the replications do not include the control-vignette and solely rely on US-based samples, with Kane et al. (2023) relying on a sample size of 805, while Mummolo and Peterson (2019) conduct two separate replications, with sample sizes of 1,874 and 5,550. To leverage these direct replications, focus will be on the lazy and unlucky conditions and the results specific to the US. In all three studies (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019), they identify the effect of deservingness on welfare support as positive and statistically discernible18 from zero with 95% confidence (see the respective estimates in table 10.1 in the appendix).

To arrive at the specific causal estimate to replicate, a meta-analysis (Eysenck 1995; Glass 1976; Sharpe and Poets 2020) is conducted using the estimates provided by these studies19 (i.e., Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019), which can be considered the platinum standard of science (Pedersen and Stritch 2018: 606), since it combines the results from each study to produce a more robust uncertainty-weighted average estimate. This exploited the numerous advantages of Bayesian inference (Gelman et al. 2014; Heck 2019; Kruschke 2010; Levy and Mislevy 2020; McElreath 2019; Wagenmakers et al. 2010) by employing a multilevel Bayesian model (cf. Brkner 2017, 2018; e.g., Maier et al. 2022). This used the brms R package (Brkner 2017, 2018) to implement the No-U-turn algorithm (NUTS, Hoffman and Gelman 2014) for the Hamiltonian Markov-Chain Monte Carlo procedure (Duane et al. 1987; Neal 1993, 2011), implemented in the probabilistic software STAN (Stan Development Team 2024), to efficiently draw 40,005 samples from the posterior using 7 independent sampling chains, with 2,000 warmup samples being drawn in advance. This produced an estimated uncertainty-weighted average effect of .44 (SD = .12; \(BF_{1,0}\) = 22.37; 95% HDI[.12; .61]; \(\hat{R}\) = 1.00; ESS = 5,553; MCSE = .00; Prior = \(\mathcal{T}_3\)(.00, .08); for an explanation of these metrics, see the Bayesian inference and Analysis-sections), which indicates a positive effect of deservingness on welfare support that can be considered discernible from zero with 95% credibility (see the appendix for model formalization, diagnostics, and posterior distributions). As generally recommended by King et al. (2000), these results can be more meaningfully interpreted as the following: Ceteris paribus, compared to being exposed to a lazy welfare recipient (i.e., someone low in deservingness), individuals exposed to an unlucky welfare recipient (i.e., someone high in deservingness) are on average 43.92 percentage-points (pp) more supportive of allowing the recipient to receive welfare support at the current requirements for welfare eligibility, plus or minus 11.88 pp, and with 95% credibility between 12.24 pp and 61.41 pp.

An advantage of this Bayesian approach (Kass and Raftery 1995; Raftery 1995) is the ability to compute posterior odds (i.e., \(\dfrac{Pr(H_\alpha \ne 0 \ | \ D)}{Pr(H_\alpha = 0 \ | \ D)}\)) from the likelihood odds (i.e., \(\dfrac{Pr(D \ | \ H_\alpha \ne 0 )}{Pr(D \ | \ H_\alpha = 0)}\)) and the prior odds (i.e., \(\dfrac{Pr(\ H_\alpha \ne 0)}{Pr(H_\alpha = 0)}\)) for the estimated parameters (e.g., \(\alpha\)) using Bayes theorem (cf. Bayes and Price 1763; Laplace 2009[1814]; McElreath 2019: 36-39) as shown in equation 1.8:

\(\dfrac{Pr(\ H_\alpha \ne 0 \ | \ D)}{Pr(H_\alpha = 0 \ | \ D)} = \dfrac{Pr(D \ | \ H_\alpha \ne 0 )}{Pr(D \ | \ H_\alpha = 0)} \times \dfrac{Pr(H_\alpha \ne 0)}{Pr(H_\alpha = 0)}\) 1.8

With the likelihood odds also known as the Bayes factor (BF, Kass and Raftery 1995; Raftery 1995), this statistic can be computed from Bayesian models by exploiting the Savage-Dickey density ratio (see Heck 2019; Makowski et al. 2019a; 2019b; Wagenmakers et al. 2010). Then, by assuming prior odds of 1, implying that a non-zero hypothesized parameter is a priori as likely as a hypothesized zero parameter20 (i.e., \(\dfrac{Pr(\ H_\delta \ne 0)}{Pr(H_\delta = 0)} = 1\)), the BF simplifies to the posterior odds (i.e., \(\dfrac{Pr(\ H_\delta \ne 0 \ | \ D)}{Pr(H_\delta = 0 \ | \ D)} = \dfrac{Pr(D \ | \ H_\delta \ne 0)}{Pr(D \ | \ H_\delta = 0)} \times 1 = BF\), Wagenmakers et al. 2010: 165). This metric is particularly useful, because it addresses the limitations and criticisms of the p-value (e.g., American Statistical Association 2016; Cohen 1994; Johnson 1999; Kruschke 2010; Wagenmakers et al. 2010), which is directly illustrated by taking the exponent of the \(ln(BF)\) provided in the results, and assuming prior odds of 1, one can state that the hypothesized effect of deservingness on welfare support is 22.37 times more probable than the hypothesis of no effect given the data. Following guidelines by Adrian E. Raftery (1995), the relative evidence provided by the BF can then be interpreted to indicate strong evidence in favour of the hypothesized relationship between deservingness and welfare support given the data.

Since a Bayesian model relies on the specification of prior distributions for each parameter which may inadvertently bias results if they are strongly informative relative to the data (Gelman et al. 2021: 123-127; Gelman et al. 2014: 55-56), to assess robustness, a multilevel Frequentist meta-analysis (Viechtbauer 2010) is also conducted by employing a model using restricted maximum likelihood (REML, Patterson and Thompson 1971). For inference, this exploited a Student t-parametric bootstrap (Efron and Tibshirani 1994) with an equivalent 40,005 permutations to increase comparability with Bayesian estimates. To compute summary statistics, contrary to the Bayesian results (cf. McElreath 2019: 197), this relied on Frequentist estimators (cf. Fisher 1970; Stock and Watson 2019; Wooldridge 2019), such as biased-reduced estimators of standard error (SE, Park et al. 2022; Park and Wang 2020, 2022) and bias-corrected and accelerated (BCa) confidence intervals (Efron 1987; Makowski et al. 2019a). This yielded a similar estimated SE-weighted average effect of .50 (SE = .06; 95% BCa[.38; .62]), which for practical purposes can be interpreted similar to the Bayesian estimates (though for the interpretive differences, see, e.g., Clayton 2021). While the overlap (Makowski et al. 2019a) between the Bayesian posterior distribution and the Frequentist parametrically-bootstrapped (maximum) likelihood distribution is relatively moderate (67.92%), the exact difference is -.06 (SD = .13; 95% HDI[-.41; .16]), which indicates that, while the Bayesian approach produces a lower, and thus more conservative, estimated average effect, the difference is indiscernible from zero with 95% credibility. As such, the priors used in the Bayesian model can be considered weakly informative in their influence on the estimated parameters, and the specific causal estimate to replicate will be the Bayesian estimates.

Having outlined both the theory, design, and effect pertaining to the relationship between deservingness and welfare attitudes, the reason for assessing the external validity of the SCF by replicating specifically these results can be made clear. Since the relationship is founded in the concept of the deservingness heuristic (Aare and Petersen 2014; Petersen et al. 2011, 2012; Petersen 2012), which is essentially a computational algorithm for making decisions on support for welfare policies, consistent with functionalist psychology (Farrell 2014: 88, 111, 398-403), it is likely that LLM-based simulated behavior would be capable of mimicking the functionality of this cognitive module because the neural networks underlying these models mimic the neural structure of the human brain (cf. OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; 2022; Ornstein et al. 2024). Since the input for the deservingness heuristic has been demonstrated to be expressible entirely as text-based vignettes (Aare and Petersen 2014; Petersen et al. 2011, 2012), the manipulation conditions meaningfully fit with the input-format of LLMs. Similarly, all LLMs trained on a large enough repertoire of text-based expressions of everyday human behavior (e.g., most of OpenAIs GPT-models, cf. OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; 2022; Ornstein et al. 2024) can be expected to have been trained on data reflecting stereotypes, specifically those relating to welfare recipients, which would likely occur in relation to expressions of support for welfare policies targeting these stereotypes. With the gpt-4o-mini LLM by OpenAI (2024a) being one such model that simultaneously manages to be comparatively cost-efficient (costing on average 0.375 US-dollars per 1 million tokens at the time of writing) and capable in terms of producing high-quality outputs, the validation of the SCF will rely on this model. Another consideration in using this phenomena to validate the SCF is that since the human-based studies rely on random sampling and experimental designs (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019), the causal estimates can be considered reliable, and with multiple direct replications confirming the initial results (i.e., Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019), the ability to combine these in a meta-analysis without having to worry about pooling together too different studies (cf. Ioannidis 2016; Sharpe 1997; see also general criticisms by Data Colada 2022a; 2022b; 2022c; 2022d), this provides a rather robust estimate of the effect to compare the SCF against. The specific choice of assessing the external validity of the SCF against the relationship between deservingness and welfare attitudes can thus be considered meaningful and reliable, though it should be noted that any one single assessment is inadequate to robustly conclude that the SCF is externally valid.

With these considerations in mind, the current direct replication study will draw on the theory and existing results pertaining to the deservingness heuristic (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019) to specify the expectation that support for the social welfare eligibility of recipients is higher when the recipient is perceived as high in deservingness compared to recipients perceived as low in deservingness, which is formalized as the following hypothesis:

\(H_1\): Support for welfare eligibility is higher for deserving welfare recipients compared to undeserving welfare recipients.

Given the previously outlined theoretical foundation of the SCF, and the consideration that an investigation of the deservingness heuristic in relation to synthetic units could be meaningful and reliable, it will be expected that the estimated causal effect of deservingness on welfare eligibility does not differ between human-based and synthetic-based studies, formalized as:

\(H_2\): The effect of deservingness on welfare eligibility is the same whether measured among synthetic respondents or human respondents.

Considering these two hypotheses, the subsequent sections will demonstrate how to simulate representative data of the US-population through the use of joint probability random sampling, followed by the introduction of the Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT), which will emulate the survey conditions of the original survey and rely on vignettes to operationalize a manipulation of deservingness through text-based descriptions of a lazy and unlucky welfare recipients.

4.2 Simulating Data

As previously mentioned, simulating data allows the researcher to decide which characteristics the LLM should base its life-history and responses on. While the selected gpt-4o-mini LLM by OpenAI (2024a) is expectedly capable of inferring characteristics proportional to a population by basing them on their prevalence in its training data, explicitly determining the characteristics gives the researcher more control over the characteristics generated, which could impact the behavior of the synthetic respondents and how generalizable results are to the population of interest. Similarly, while it can be expected that the greater the number of simulated characteristics, the more realistic the behavior of the LLM, specifically which and how many characteristics to simulate will likely vary depending on characteristics found relevant for the particular research topic and the ability of the selected LLM to retain and process information. For this demonstration, the common demographics (e.g., ANES 2021; Ruggles et al. 2024) of US State residence, area residence type, number of children in household, sex, age, marital status, ethnoracial group21, highest level of education, employment status, and annual household gross income ($US) will be simulated, which includes the demographic characteristics deemed relevant by Aare and Petersen (2014), and this will likely provide gpt-4o-mini with plenty of realistic information from which to generate the life-histories. Furthermore, since the results from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023) relate specifically to political attitudes toward welfare requirements, the characteristics of preferred political party and political ideology will also be simulated.

Simulating characteristics can be done so that their prevalence in the data is proportional to a national population of interest. Since this demonstration focuses on replicating the results from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023), the population of interest is determined to be the adult population of the United States of America (US). A population-proportional simulation of characteristics can be achieved by constructing a stratification matrix using large samples such as those that form the basis of census data (cf. Gelman and Little 1997). A stratification matrix consists of every combination of the characteristics of interest and their frequency in the population, and a US-based version can be constructed using US Census Bureau data provided by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024). Here, the 2022-wave is used due to being relatively contemporary, containing measures of most characteristics to simulate (i.e., US State residence, area residence, number of children in household, sex, age, marital status, ethnoracial group, highest level of education, employment status, and annual household gross income in 2022 US dollars) and a large sample size (\(n\)) of 3,373,378 respondents, which after data cleaning (e.g., removing missing values and respondents less than 18 years old) results in 2,403,591 usable observations. However, the data lacks measures of political party affiliation and political ideology, meaning that these measures will have to be imputed (Kalton and Kasprzyk 1982; King et al. 2001; Rubin 1988).

To impute the measures of political party affiliation and political ideology, data from the similarly recent 2020-wave of the American National Election Survey (ANES 2021) can be used. While the ANES relies on samples substantially smaller than the IPUMS (\(n\) = 8,280), it is also contemporary and contains similar measures of all characteristics to simulate. The subset of the ANES of all these characteristics can be used to train statistical models to impute political party and ideology, which necessitates recoding all variables to have the same categories and scale across the IPUMS and ANES. To leverage as much data from the ANES as possible, missing values were imputed (range: 12 - 3,700) with the multiple imputations by chained equations procedure (MICE, van Buuren and Groothuis-Oudshoorn 2011), using the random forest algorithm (Breiman 2001; Ho 1995; Liaw and Wiener 2002) due to its generally high accuracy, non-parametric nature, and ability to handle both categorical and continuous data. This involved 121 imputation iterations, which was estimated as the number of iterations necessary for chain convergence (cf. von Hippel 2020). Having undertaken data cleaning similar to the IPUMS data prior to imputation (e.g., removing respondents less than 18 years old), this results in one imputed ANES sample of 6,568 usable observations.

Following then the methodology of cross-validation (Stone 1974), an unbiased measure of the imputation accuracy of statistical models can be derived by splitting the ANES data into a train and test dataset, using the conventional 80/20 split ratio (e.g., Frana et al. 2024), training the models on the training data and testing their imputation accuracy on the testing data. To assess variability in imputation accuracy, Bootstrapped cross-validation (Xu and Liang 2001) is used, which here involves iteratively splitting, training, and testing models a total of 10 times.
