To impute respondents dichotomously-coded preferred political party, a varying-intercepts Bernoulli model (Gelman and Hill 2007) and a Random Forest model (Breiman 2001; Ho 1995; Liaw and Wiener 2002) are compared. From their predictions, a confusion matrix (Tharwat 2018) is generated, with imputation accuracy being computed as the equally-weighted arithmetic mean of the total accuracy (ACC), sensitivity (i.e., recall) and specificity (Yerushalmy 1947), positive predictive value (PPV; i.e., precision) and negative predictive value (NPV) (Altman and Bland 1994), which are popular, complementary metrics of model accuracy. The average imputation accuracy of the varying-intercepts Bernoulli model is 66%, with a standard deviation (SD) of 1 percentage points (pp), while the Random Forest model has an imputation accuracy of 65% (SD = 1pp), meaning that the varying-intercepts Bernoulli model is chosen to impute political party in the IPUMS data due to its (marginally) superior accuracy. Imputing political ideology, which due to its Likert (1932) scale could be treated either as an ordered or (less appropriately) as a continuous variable (cf. Lantz 2013; Wu and Leung 2017), involves a varying-intercepts Gaussian model (Gelman and Hill 2007), a Generalized Additive Model (GAM, Hastie and Tibshirani 1990; Wood 2004, 2011, 2017), and a Random Forest model (Breiman 2001; Ho 1995; Liaw and Wiener 2002). These are similarly evaluated, though given its non-dichotomous coding, only ACC is used to measure imputation accuracy. These models produce an ACC of 30% (1pp), 30% (1pp), and 43% (1pp), respectively, resulting in the Random Forest model being chosen to impute political ideology for its superior accuracy. While the imputation accuracies of both political party affiliation and political ideology can be considered relatively high, they are far from an accuracy of 100%, meaning that these imperfectly imputed values may make the resulting stratification matrix less reliably representative of the adult US population.

Having imputed preferred political party and political idelogy in the IPUMS data, all chosen characteristics are available, and a stratification matrix is generated by counting the frequency of every combination of the characteristics (n = 2,366,924). Then, analogous to a non-parametric bootstrap (Efron 1979, 2003), simulating data can done by sampling with replacement from the stratification matrix, with the sampling probability being the frequency of each combination of characteristics. This aforementioned joint probability procedure for simulated random sampling ensures that the value of each characteristic is simulated conditionally on the values of all the other characteristics (e.g., P(sex = Male | State = Tennessee, Age = 65, Political Ideology = Conservative)), making the resulting data more closely reflect the proportionality of characteristics in the US population. Asymptotically, data simulated in this manner is representative of the national population of interest, and for smaller datasets that nonetheless are unrepresentative, the multilevel regression and poststratification (MRP, Gelman and Little 1997) method may alternatively be used to adjust for such sample-population imbalances. With this US-based stratification matrix available, a sample can then easily be generated. For the purposes of this demonstrative replication, the sample size of the original study is used (Aare and Petersen 2014: 688), which entails a relatively large sample size of 1,009 simulated respondents being generated. Given that the aforementioned parallel worlds-estimation is here used to produce two counterfactual outcomes for each respondent (see below), this results in an effective sample size of 2,018. With regards to successfully replicating the aforementioned effect size of .44 (SD = .12; 95% HDI[.12; .61]), a false-positive error rate (\(\epsilon_{\alpha}\), i.e., Type I error) of 5% is specified a priori, which together with 4 fixed model parameters (i.e., intercept mean, intercept standard deviation, coefficient, and the model degrees of freedom, see model in the Bayesian inference-section), the false-negative error rate (\(\epsilon_{\beta}\), i.e., Type II error) is estimated to be 4.14%. This means that the study has an estimated statistical power (Gelman and Carlin 2014) of 95.86%, which can be considered more than adequate for replicating the existing results (cf. Cohen 1988, 1991). Similarly, the type M error rate (\(\epsilon_{M}\), Gelman and Carlin 2014) is 1.03, meaning that the effect is unlikely to be substantially under-/overestimated (i.e., the exaggeration rate is only 3%), while the type S error rate (\(\epsilon_{S}\), Gelman and Carlin 2014) is .00%, indicating almost no probability of the estimate having the wrong sign. As such, the probability of a successful replication is high, at least as indicated by these metrics.

Simulating the data in this manner produces a 1009 \(\times\) 13 matrix, with randomly-determined examples of simulated units being provided in table 4.1. The simulated data contains an identification number (id, omitted from table 4.1) and the 12 measures of the selected characteristics of each simulated respondent: Their US state of residence (e.g., Maine, Vermont, Florida), area residence type (e.g., City, Rural Area, Small Town Or Surburb), number of children (range: 0 - 4 Or More), sex (i.e., Female, Male; 52.82% females), age (mean: 51.72; SD = 18.53; range: 18 - 95), marital status (e.g., Not Married, Widowed, Divorced), ethnoracial group (e.g., Chinese, Bangladeshi, Ecuadorian), level of education (range: Less Than High School Credential - Graduate Degree), employment status (e.g., Not In Labor Force, Employed, Unemployed), annual household gross income in 2022 US dollars ($) (median: 82,000; IQR = 99,000; range: -6,910 - 1,360,000), preferred political party (i.e., Democratic Party, Republican Party; 53.72% democrats), and political ideology (range: Extremely Liberal - Extremely Conservative). For more details and greater overview of the simulated data, descriptive statistics are provided both metrically and graphically in the appendix.

On average, the sample is estimated to capture 97.69% (SD = 6.29pp) of the information in the US population in relation to the specified characteristics22, and comparisons of the sample distributions with US population estimates reveals that the sample could generally be considered representative on all measured demographics. Compared to the nationally representative sample used by Aare and Petersen (2014: 688), which employed stratified sampling, the two samples differ by this simulated data including an age range up to 95 compared to their age range up to 70. Possibly as a result of this, the mean age of their sample is 41.1 years, while it is 51.7 here. Also, the ratio of females is in their sample 51%, while it in this simulated sample is 52.8%. As such, while the sample of Aare and Petersen (2014) is relatively younger, based on the characteristics described in their materials, there are no substantial differences between the samples, meaning that this sample can be considered comparatively representative. This representativeness of the sample is likely attributable to the relatively large nominal sample size (n = 1,009) and the joint probability procedure used to generate it. With this simulated data now having been generated, OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini can then be used to generate their life-histories.

4.3 Generating Life-Histories

With simulated data available, a prompt can be engineered, which serves as an input that instructs the LLM to generate life-histories for the respondents. As mentioned, a life-history (Bertaux 1981) can be considered an autobiographical narrative by which individuals frame their life, experiences, identity, relationships, existential purpose and place in society (e.g., Znaniecki and Thomas 2020[1974]), and their purpose here is to provide more character and nuance to the simulated respondents in a way that goes beyond their assigned characteristics. This will expectedly help the LLM respond in a manner that is consistent with a human possessing the assigned characteristics. Writing a prompt that instructs the LLM to generate the life-history based on the assigned characteristics helps ensure that other characteristics generated in the life-history are functions of the explicitly determined characteristics. The prompt engineered for this specific purpose, with examples of characteristics specific to a randomly-sampled simulated unit is provided in table 4.2.

Table 4.2: Life-History Prompt
id Prompt
495

You are to act as a character and must remain in character for the purposes of a roleplay scenario. You and your thus refer to your character from now on. Your character has the following characteristics:

Country: United States of America (USA)

State: North Carolina

Area: Rural Area

Number of Children in Household: 0

Sex: Male

Age: 25

Marital Status: Not Married

Ethonoracial Group: Black/African American

Annual Household Gross Income (In 2022 $US): 13200

Education: Some Post-High School, No Bachelors Degree

Employment Status: Not In Labor Force

Preferred Political Party: Democratic Party

Political Ideology: Moderate; Middle Of The Road

Be creative but realistic and compose a brief life-history for your character based on the provided characteristics:

NOTE: Example of a prompt engineered to generate a life-history. The characteristics in the prompt are based on data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

The prompt specified here for generating life-histories instructs the gpt-4o-mini LLM (OpenAI 2024a) to act as a character and to persistently remain in character. This serves to ensure that all output generated by the LLM reflects behavior consistent with that character. It also contains a list of all the assigned characteristics, followed by a request for it to generate a (brief) life-history based on these characteristics. While an increase in the number of provided characteristics and the request of a longer life-history will expectedly result in behavior that more realistically reflects a human possessing these traits, this likely comes at the cost of greater financial costs and time needed by the LLM to process the input and generate an output. An advantage of relying on the API of GPT-models by OpenAI is that researchers can control numerous parameters of the model. For example, the max length (i.e., max_tokens) parameter can be restricted to reduce costs (OpenAI 2025a), though this will likely reduce its ability to act in a manner consistent with its assigned characteristics. What constitutes an optimal max length will expectedly vary across different research purposes, depending in part on the number of relevant characteristics from which the LLM is to generate life-histories. For this demonstration the max_tokens for generating life-histories is set to 500, which is found to be adequate within this context, since the LLM can generate life-histories within this limit without its output being truncated due to exceeding the limit. Another relevant parameter is the temperature of the LLMs output (i.e., temperature), which determines the randomness of the output (OpenAI 2025a). A higher value makes its output adhere less to language syntax, making its output less cohesive and meaningful. The default value outlined by OpenAI is 1, and while an optimal value will likely vary across contexts, a text analysis of the generated life-histories (see below) found this value to be adequate for the context of generating realistic life-histories.

To generate life-histories from the simulated data, it is recommended to use the gpt-4o-mini LLM through OpenAIs API (OpenAI 2025a). As mentioned, gpt-4o-mini is among the best-performing and cheapest models (OpenAI 2024a; 2025b), with a hallucination rate as low as 1.7% and factual consistency rate of 98.3% (Vectara 2025), indicating that the model is generally reliable. Making requests through OpenAIs API is preferred, since data generated in this way are not used to train their models, and in terms of privacy, such data is generally deleted after 30 days (OpenAI 2024d). This helps reduce concerns that studies such as this could inadvertently train the model, leading to results more consistent with researcher preferences rather than human behavior, which would result in tautological results. Compared to manually generating life-histories, calling the API using software exponentially speeds up the process and is easily done through R in RStudio. To this end, this demonstration relies on the openai R package (Rudnytskyi 2023) because of its ease in making such API requests. Due to the speed of such software, it is furthermore recommended to enforce pauses between calls to the API to reduce traffic, which can stress their systems. OpenAI already enforces rate limits (OpenAI 2025a), and to avoid unintentionally hitting one of their numerous request limitations, the researcher can a priori enforce a pause between requests. This demonstration uses a relatively substantial pause of 3.1 seconds to avoid hitting rate limits, though values could vary depending on the number and length of requests.

This demonstration implements and recommends that LLM-output is generated through separate requests, one for each simulated respondent, to ensure that observations are independent. An alternative to this procedure is batching, which involves grouping multiple requests together into a single request (OpenAI 2025a). For example, by providing the characteristics of several simulated respondents in the same prompt and asking for multiple life-histories. While this can reduce both financial and time costs, a serious methodological concern of batching is that generating life-histories (and most other types of outcome) in batches produces output that may be interdependent, which typically is not desirable. For example, output generated in batches may be more strongly correlated than output generated in other batches or output generated individually. This would violate the common statistical assumption of observations being independent and identically distributed (iid, Gaenssler and Stute 1979; McElreath 2019: 81), which would likely need to be accounted for using statistical modeling (e.g., multilevel models, Gelman and Hill 2007). Furthermore, when generating the outcome across different group conditions using batching, there may be information spill-over, for example, if the LLM in generating a counterfactual output mistakes a unit in one manipulation condition with a unit in another manipulation condition, or if the mere presence of information relating to both group conditions affects the generation of results. This spill-over would violate the aforementioned fundamental assumption of stable unit treatment value assumption (SUTVA, Angrist et al. 1996; Cox 1958; Gelman et al. 2021: 353-354; Imbens and Rubin 2015: 9-12; Rosenbaum and Rubin 1983; Rubin 1974), which the SCF was formalized to depend on for reliable causal inference. While general methods could be implemented to account for this information spill-over (Imbens and Rubin 2015: 12-13; e.g., Aronow and Samii 2017), these can be complex (Rosenbaum 2007), and as similarly argued by Elizabeth Stuart (2010: 3), the most effective solution is simply to prevent interdependency and spill-over by design. As such, to prevent violations of iid and SUTVA in this manner, it is recommended to generate life-histories and most other types of outcome separately, unless the purpose specifically is to study interdependency.

With the specifications and considerations in mind, a life-history for each simulated resondent can be generated. In this demonstration, this involves a for-loop, which iteratively goes through each respondent, makes a call to OpenAIs API for the selected gpt-4o-mini LLM, and saves the output to the data. The loop accounts for possible errors in calling the API by waiting 10 seconds before trying again, up to a total of 3 times. Information about the output generation provided by OpenAI is saved, such as the time of receiving a response from the model, which help provide documentation of the data. The number of tokens used and the time it took to generate the output is also stored, which will be used to ascertain financial and time costs. Note that before it is possible to call OpenAIs API, researchers must create an OpenAI account, deposit adequate finances, and generate a unique API key (OpenAI 2025a). The key will be used to connect your requests with your finances and should thus be kept private. Following these specifications, the below R code provides an overview of some of the code used to generate life-histories with the gpt-4o-mini LLM (OpenAI 2024a): 

# Initialize columns for storing the GPT-output
simulated_data$life_history_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_id_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_object_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_created_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_model_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_prompt_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_completion_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_logprobs <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_finish_reason <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_message.refusal <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_message.role <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_time_cost <- NA


# Construct prompt
messages_life_history <- list()
messages_life_history[[1]] <- list(
  "role" = "system",
  "content" = "You are a human simulator."
)
messages_life_history[[2]] <- list(
  "role" = "user",
  "content" = NA
)


# Progress bar to keep track of the for-loop
pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0, max = nrow(simulated_data), style = 3)


# Indices in the data for which to generate life-histories
indices <- simulated_data$id[is.na(simulated_data$life_history_gpt)] %>% as.numeric()


# Reset attempts
attempt_thresholds <- 0


# For-loop for generating life-histories
for(i in c(indices)){
  
  # Check if threshold has been met
  if(attempt_thresholds >= max_attempt_thresholds){
    print("Threshold for maximum number of errors reached. Stopping...")
    break
  }
  
  
  # Start time recording
  t0 <- Sys.time()

  
  # Enforce a pause if this is the second iteration or higher
  if(i > 1){
    Sys.sleep(pause_duration)
  }
  
  
  # Adjust prompt to reflect respondent i's characteristics
  messages_life_history[[2]][2] <- list(paste0(
    "You are to act as a character and must remain in character for the purposes of a roleplay scenario. 'You' and 'your' thus refer to your character from now on. Your character has the following characteristics:
    Country: United States of America (USA)
    State: ", simulated_data$state[i], "
    Area: ", simulated_data$urban[i], "
    Number of Children in Household: ", simulated_data$children[i], "
    Sex: ", simulated_data$sex[i], "
    Age: ", simulated_data$age[i], "
    Marital Status: ", simulated_data$married[i], "
    Ethonoracial Group: ", simulated_data$race_d[i], "
    Annual Household Gross Income in 2020 $US: ", simulated_data$household_income_d[i], "
    Education: ", simulated_data$education[i], "
    Employment Status: ", simulated_data$employment[i], "
    Preferred Political Party: ", simulated_data$political_party[i], "
    Political Ideology: ", simulated_data$political_ideology[i], "
    Be creative but realistic and compose a brief life-history for your character based on the provided characteristics:"
  ))
  
  
  # Set initial attempt
  attempt <- 1
  
  
  # Call GPT model (and use tryCatch to make the loop continue retrying if encountering an error)
  while(attempt <= max_attempts){
    print(paste0("Attempt: ", attempt, "/", max_attempts))
    attempt <- attempt + 1

    tryCatch(
      expr = {
        gpt_output <- openai::create_chat_completion(
          model = selected_gpt_model,
          messages = messages_life_history,
          max_tokens = max_tokens$life_history,
          temperature = temperature$life_history,
          openai_api_key = OPENAI_API_KEY
        )
        break
      },
      error = function(e){
        print(paste("Error encountered. Error message:", e))
        print(" Going to sleep for 10 seconds ...")
        Sys.sleep(time = 10)
      }
    )
  }
  
  
  # Check is used attempts reach threshold
  if(attempt >= max_attempts){
    attempt_thresholds <- attempt_thresholds + 1
    print(paste0("Maximum number of errors reached threshold. Thresholds met: ", attempt_thresholds, "/", max_attempt_thresholds))
    
    # Update progress bar
    setTxtProgressBar(pb, i)
    
    
    # End and store time recording
    t1 <- Sys.time()
    simulated_data$life_history_time_cost <- t1-t0
    
    next
  }

  
  # Store life history
  simulated_data$life_history_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$choices$message.content


  # Store utility info
  simulated_data$life_history_id_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$id
  simulated_data$life_history_object_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$object
  simulated_data$life_history_created_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$created
  simulated_data$life_history_model_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$model
  simulated_data$life_history_prompt_tokens[i] <- gpt_output$usage$prompt_tokens
  simulated_data$life_history_completion_tokens[i] <- gpt_output$usage$completion_tokens
  simulated_data$life_history_logprobs[i] <- gpt_output$choices$logprobs
  simulated_data$life_history_finish_reason[i] <- gpt_output$choices$finish_reason
  simulated_data$life_history_message.refusal[i] <- gpt_output$choices$message.refusal
  simulated_data$life_history_message.role[i] <- gpt_output$choices$message.role
  

  # Update progress bar
  setTxtProgressBar(pb, i)
  
  
  # End and store time recording
  t1 <- Sys.time()
  simulated_data$life_history_time_cost <- t1-t0
}


# Convert Unix Timestamp to Datatime
simulated_data$life_history_datetime <- lubridate::as_datetime(simulated_data$life_history_created_gpt)

Using the aforementioned specifications, generating 1,009 life-histories using this for-loop takes 192.76 minutes, or 3.21 hours, with the expected time-cost per simulated respondent thus being 11.46 (SD = .00) seconds. Output from the gpt-4o-mini model can be gauged to ascertain whether it ran into any issues during the generation (OpenAI 2025a). This includes its finish_reason, where a stop-response is consistent with no issues, while length-response means that the life-histories were cut short due to the model reaching the specified max_tokens limitation. Another output parameter is message.refusal, which indicates whether the model refused to provide an output, and an NA-response is generally consistent with no issues. A message refusal can happen for several reasons and retries or changing the input may fix the issue. For an example of the contents of a life-history, a randomly-sampled index is provided in table 4.3.

Table 4.3: Example of an LLM-Generated Life-History
id Life-History
495 My name is Marcus Lee, and I grew up in the small, tight-knit community of rural North Carolina. My folks are from herea mix of tradition and a yearning for the future. They instilled in me the values of hard work and community support, but also the importance of pursuing education and finding my own path.

After finishing high school, I dabbled in a few local community college coursesmostly focused on automotive repair and computer technologybecause Ive always had a knack for figuring things out. Unfortunately, life took a few unexpected turns, and I had to step back from my education. Financial struggles hit hard, and Ive found myself working odd jobs and helping out family and neighbors rather than sticking to a career path.

At 25, Im not married and dont have kids, but I keep close ties with my family and friends. I often help my younger cousins with their homework or mentor them through issues they face in school. Being part of this community means everything to me; we rely on each other, especially in tough times.

Politically, I lean towards the Democratic Party and believe in finding balanced solutions that cater to everyones needs. I value social justice but also want to ensure that economic opportunities are accessible to all, including the folks in my rural area who often get left behind.

With an annual income of around $13,200, Ive managed to keep my head above water, but its definitely a struggle. I find small joyslike cooking on the weekends, playing pick-up basketball with friends, or attending local church events. NOTE: Synthetic data generated by OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini model on 2025-02-03 10:50:14 using simulated characteristics based on data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

With life-histories now generated from the simulated characteristics, this synthesis of simulated data and LLM-based data can be considered to have produced what was previously termed synthetic units. When later being tasked to act as a survey respondent (see below), the LLM by merit of basing its behavior on the combined information in the life-history specific to each synthetic unit, rather than merely basing it on the information reflected in the assigned characteristics specific to each simulated unit, its behavior will likely be more realistic and in a more nuanced way reflect actual human behavior.

In terms of quality assurance, it is here recommended to validate that the life-histories reflect and are consistent with the assigned characteristics. This serves to ensure that subsequent output by the model (i.e., the counterfactual outcomes) correctly draws on the assigned characteristics. Analogous to procedures used in qualitative methodology (OConnor and Joffe 2020) or computational text analysis (Theocharis and Jungherr 2021), validations can be performed by raters, who read the generated life-history and compare it to the assigned characteristics to assess consistency. Raters can provide their evaluations of consistency in numerous formats, for example, dichotomously (e.g., Consistent, Inconsistent), continuously (e.g., 7-point Likert (1932) scale), or in open-text format. The number of raters and evaluated life-histories can vary, for example, it can involve two independent raters, who evaluate all life-histories or a random sample, with the scope of the evaluation likely depending on the resources available for the given project. Rater evaluations can then be assessed to ascertain their inter-rater reliability (Saal et al. 1980), which expresses whether raters are generally in agreement on the (in)consistency of the output. If rater evaluations are provided in a quantifiable format, this can be estimated as a reliability coefficient, for example, as percent agreement, Sklars \(\omega\) (Hughes 2022), Krippendorffs \(\alpha\) (2018), Fleiss \(\kappa\) (1971), Cohens \(\kappa\) (1960), Scotts \(\pi\) (1955), Spearmans \(\rho\) (1904), Kendalls (1938), or the product-moment correlation coefficient (r, Bravais 1844; Pearson 1895a; Stigler 1989), depending on the number of raters and the scale used to measure (in)consistency. If the same rater has evaluated the same output multiple times, intra-rater reliability (Saal et al. 1980) can also be similarly estimated. An alternative procedure to human raters is to have LLMs act as raters, which can reduce financial and time costs related to evaluating the consistency of the model output. If doing this, the randomness inherent to the LLM can be maximally reduced (i.e., temperature = 0), which increases the determinism of the LLM-raters (cf. OpenAI 2025a), expectedly producing a perfect inter- and intra-rater reliability. However, this may under-/overestimate consistency, and until the rater reliability of LLMs has proven comparable to human raters in assessing consistency between life-histories and characteristics, caution in choosing to use LLM-raters is advised, as it reduces human supervision and quality control over the output.

For the present purposes of evaluating the consistency between the assigned characteristics and the characteristics mentioned in the generated life-history, a single-rater assessment was conducted by the author using a random sample of 100 synthetic units. Here, following standard practice for response options (e.g., ANES (2021)), the rater could choose between Agree, Disagree, Didnt know, or Prefer not to answer in relation to whether the information contained in the life-history matched each assigned characteristic. To estimate the intra-rater reliability of this human rater, after a 7-day window to reduce recall (Agnihotri et al. 2024; Ernst et al. 2019; Srensen et al. 2024), a random sample of 50 of the previously-coded synthetic units were recoded by the same rater. Consistent with a consensus-based approach (Syed and Nelson 2015: 5), rater-discrepancies were resolved by comparing ratings across the two intervals, with the proportion of responses for each category being provided in table 4.4. Intra-rater reliability was estimated as percent agreement and Sklars \(\omega\) (Hughes 2022) prior to resolving discrepancies and are similarly provided in the table.

Human assessment of consistency in synthetic data generated by OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini model using simulated characteristics based on data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

The results from the content analysis of the generated life-histories reveal a generally high overlap between the assigned characteristics and the LLM-generated life-histories. Few instances were found, where the LLM had generated information in direct contrast with the assigned characteristics, with most identified cases being inconsistencies in the units area of residence (4% of the time). The relatively large number of unclear cases (i.e., Dont know-situations) is the result of the LLM not explicitly stating the assigned characteristic in the life-history. This was most evident for the Ethnoracial group-category (80%), where the only instances of explicit mention were for individuals of black or immigrant background. Similarly, the specific annual household gross income was rarely mentioned, with the LLM often making vague and implicit references to the units income (70%, e.g., a modest income). Age was often implicitly mentioned in the life-histories (23%) by being stated as the synthetic units year of birth, though it was typically entirely missing. While the LLM generally succeeded in explicitly stating the political ideology of the synthetic respondent, their preferred political party was often not stated (10%), perhaps because the LLM communicated it implicitly by stating the political values of the unit. While it would seem that the prompt could be improved by stating that the LLM must explicitly mention each assigned characteristic in the life-history, the results nonetheless indicate a generally high consistency between the assigned characteristics and life-histories in this sample, with few direct contradictions, indicating that the life-histories could be considered to reliably reflect the assigned characteristics. As such, this use of life-histories can be expected to enable a more realistic investigation of the effect of deservingness on welfare support, achieved by conducting a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT).

4.4 Conducting an SCT

With synthetic units having been produced through the synthesis of simulated data and LLM-based data, a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) can then be conducted, which implements the parallel worlds-estimation procedure whilst emulating the survey design of Aare and Petersen (2014), enabling an exogenous manipulation of deservingness by simultaneously and independently exposing each synthetic respondent to both the lazy and unlucky welfare recipient vignettes, measuring their support for restricting the welfare eligibility of each recipient. The following subsections cover (1) the simultaneous and independent generation and measurement of the counterfactual outcomes across a lazy and unlucky manipulation condition; (2) an assessment of (im)balance between the measured characteristics of the synthetic respondents across these two manipulation conditions; (3) a statistical test of the simultaneity assumption to ascertain whether parallel worlds-estimation expectedly eliminates time as a confounder; and (4) a formalization of the statistical model, which in line with Bayesian inference (Gelman et al. 2014, 2021; Heck 2019; Kruschke 2014; McElreath 2019; Wagenmakers et al. 2010), will be used to estimate the causal effect of deservingness on welfare support.

4.4.1 Parallel Worlds

The procedure for generating the counterfactual outcomes is similar to the procedure used for generating life-histories. This will involve prompting the LLM to assume the character of the synthetic respondent by relying on the characteristics described in the previously generated life-histories. As mentioned, the novel concept of a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) can be considered an SCF-based version of the Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT, Coover and Angell 1907; Peirce and Jastrow 1885; Woodworth and Thorndike 1901), since its borrows heavily on its design and ability to provide reliable causal inference (cf. Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49). Just like an RCT, the SCT will involve exogenously assigning the synthetic respondents to group conditions with varying manipulations, followed by then measuring the outcome. However, an SCT does not rely on the randomized assignment mechanism (RAM) of an RCT, since every respondent can be assigned to every manipulation condition and have all their counterfactual outcomes measured. For this, it employs the aforementioned simultaneous and independent exogenous assignment mechanism (SIXAM), where each synthetic respondent is assigned to every manipulation condition, and with the measurement of simultaneous and independent counterfactual outcomes, intra-unit comparisons can be made that eliminate confounders by merit of the exogeneity of the SIXAM, providing reliable causal inference. While doing intra-unit comparisons in this manner will eliminate all unit-invariant confounders when estimating individual treatment effects (ITEs)23 (cf. Westreich et al. 2015), to also eliminate time as a possible confounder of the ITEs, it is important that this process, at least with respect to each synthetic respondent, occurs simultaneously across manipulation conditions, which was previously introduced as the simultaneity assumption. Compliance with this assumption is implemented with the aforementioned concept of parallel worlds-estimation, which exploits parallel computation (cf. Gottlieb and Almasi 1989; Ozdoganlar and Endres 2021[1999]) to simultaneously generate and measure the counterfactual outcomes of each respondent by handling these processes in separate computational cores. If the simultaneity assumption is not violated, the intra-unit comparisons will also remove all time-invariant confounders in relation to the ITEs. A limitation of parallel worlds-estimation is that it requires implementation on a machine that has as many computational cores as there are manipulation conditions. With 2 manipulation conditions considered here and 8 cores available on the system used to implement parallel processing, parallel worlds-estimation is available for this replication.

With the above considerations in mind, the current demonstration involves replicating the survey design and two manipulation conditions invariably employed by Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023). The replication has so far managed to simulate a sample of similar size (n = 1,009) and representativeness to Aare and Petersen (2014) from the (theoretically) same population of adults from the US. Since details on the design of the original study are sparse, which is contrary to best practice (cf. Christensen et al. 2019), replicating the survey conditions is limited to the vignettes and outcome measurement. The vignettes that make out the manipulation conditions involve the description of a lazy welfare recipient: Imagine a man who is currently on social welfare. He has never had a regular job, but he is fit and healthy. He is not motivated to get a job (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689; Petersen et al. 2012) and an unlucky welfare recipient: Imagine a man who is currently on social welfare. He has always had a regular job, but has now been the victim of a work-related injury. He is very motivated to get back to work again (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689; Petersen et al. 2012). While these phrasings are evidently useful (cf. Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019; Petersen et al. 2012), to implement the parallel worlds-estimation procedure, the word length and character length of the manipulations would expectedly matter in relation to the simultaneity assumption. Since the vignettes differ in both word length (i.e., 30 and 36 words, respectively) and character length (i.e., 142 and 184 characters, respectively), it is unlikely that the parallel API-requests to gpt-4o-mini and its resulting responses will occur simultaneously due to differences in the time needed to process these differing inputs, and a violation of the simultaneity assumption is thus expected.24 This is because the GPT-model uses time to process the input (e.g.,, it tokenizes a sentence by breaking it down into individual words), which can vary depending on the length of the input, though the exact impact of word and character length on processing time may differ. To address this issue, without changing the substantive meaning of the vignettes, they are rephrased to have the same word length (i.e., 33 words) and character length (i.e., 171 characters).25 These can then be embedded into prompts that present the vignette to the gpt-4o-mini LLM, provided in table 4.5.

Table 4.5: Manipulation Conditions
Lazy Welfare Recipient Unlucky Welfare Recipient
One day you decide to participate in a survey. You are informed that the responsible researchers are professional and impartial and care about your honest opinions.

On the first few pages, you answer questions regarding your background. You turn a page and are then greeted with the following scenario:
Imagine a man who is currently on social welfare. He has never had a regular job, but he is fit and healthy. He lacks motivation to find employment and does not seek work.

You take a few seconds to properly imagine this man before clicking to the next page. This page greets you with the following question about the man you just read about:
To what extent do you disagree or agree that the eligibility requirements for social welfare should be tightened for persons like him?

Your response options are:
1 Strongly disagree

4 Neither agree or disagree
5 Somewhat agree

99 Dont know

You answer: 		One day you decide to participate in a survey. You are informed that the responsible researchers are professional and impartial and care about your honest opinions.

On the first few pages, you answer questions regarding your background. You turn a page and are then greeted with the following scenario:
Imagine a man who is currently on social welfare. He has always had a regular job, but he has now suffered a work-related injury. He is highly motivated to return to work.

You take a few seconds to properly imagine this man before clicking to the next page. This page greets you with the following question about the man you just read about:
To what extent do you disagree or agree that the eligibility requirements for social welfare should be tightened for persons like him?

Your response options are:
1 Strongly disagree
2 Disagree
3 Somewhat disagree
4 Neither agree or disagree
5 Somewhat agree
6 Agree
7 Strongly agree
99 Dont know

You answer:

NOTE: Example of prompt engineered with the purpose of using vignettes to generate different manipulation conditions for synthetic respondents using LLMs. Rephrased vignettes based on Aare and Petersen (2014) and Petersen et al. (2012).

To further increase the external validity of the results, the prompt are formulated to create a realistic survey environment, for example, by stating that the respondent has chosen to participate in a survey and has already filled out questions regarding their background characteristics. This includes standard survey introductory text informing the synthetic respondent that the researchers are impartial and professional and care for the respondents honest answers. This flavor text serves to reduce the impact of social desirability (Edwards 1953; Krumpal 2013) and other demand characteristics (Masling 1966; Nichols and Maner 2008), such as expectancy effects (McDermott 1895: 34) and experimenter demand bias (Druckman 2015: 57-58), on respondent answers. To inform the LLM of the intended response format, the prompts includes the response scale, which in line with the replication is a 7-point Likert (1932) scale26 (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689), though it should be noted that other types of scales may be of greater use to researchers when studying other phenomena. Lastly, the prompt explicitly states that the respondent takes their time to imagine the welfare recipient, which serves to ensure that the response reflects a contemplated opinion. While this may increase the reliability of the response, it could make results less generalizable, since not all human respondents take their time to read and comply with vignettes (Kane et al. 2023), and given how agreeable the GPT models generally are (cf. OpenAI 2024a; 2024b; 2024c; Ornstein et al. 2024), it is likely that responses generated by these current models will fail to reflect non-compliant and inattentive human respondents.

With one vignette being used in each manipulation condition, the synthetic respondents can then be simultaneously and independently assigned to both conditions to provide their counterfactual responses. Similar to generating the life-histories, this again involves a for-loop iterating over each synthetic respondent, thus abiding by the iid and SUTVA assumptions. Unlike before, however, the loop implements a nested for-loop that implements the parallel worlds-estimation using parallel processing (Microsoft and Weston 2022b). This involves two independent computational cores, with each one making a separate call to gpt-4o-mini API (OpenAI 2024a). As mentioned, this serves to reduce any time difference between observing each outcome across the manipulation conditions. API calls are again made continuously with a 3.1 second pause between each synthetic respondent, and a 10-second pause in case of an error, up to a total of 3 tries. It should be further noted that the code also implements randomization, with a Bernoulli-process (cf. Bernoulli 1713[2006]; Kachitvichyanukul and Schmeiser 1988) determining the initial index-value of the parallel process-loop (i.e., whether the index-sequence is [1,2] or [2,1]), which serves to ensure that any idiosyncratic waits attributable to the initial index-value are unbiased.

The below R-code specifies the for-loop that employs the simultaneous and independent exogenous assignment mechanism (SIXAM) to produce two counterfactual outcomes for each respondent, one for the lazy welfare recipient and one for the unlucky welfare recipient. The implementation of the parallel worlds-estimation procedure uses two independent cores, with one core being used to process each manipulation condition. 

# Initialize columns for storing the 'lazy' outcome
simulated_data$outcome_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_id_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_object_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_created_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_model_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_prompt_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_completion_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_logprobs <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_finish_reason <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_message.refusal <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_message.role <- NA


# Initialize columns for storing the 'unlucky' counterfactual outcome
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_id_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_object_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_created_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_model_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_prompt_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_completion_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_logprobs <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_finish_reason <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_message.refusal <- NA
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_message.role <- NA


# Initialize column for recording time cost
simulated_data$outcome_time_cost <- NA


# Assign one computational core to each manipulation condition
doParallel::registerDoParallel(cores_parallel_worlds)


# Progress bar to keep track of the for-loop
pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0, max = nrow(simulated_data), style = 3)


# Indices in the data for which to generate the counterfactual outcomes
indices <- simulated_data$id[is.na(simulated_data$outcome_gpt) | is.na(simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_gpt)] %>% as.numeric()


# Reset attempts
attempt_thresholds <- 0


# For-loop for generating the counterfactual outcomes
for(i in c(indices)){
  
  
  # Check if threshold has been met
  if(attempt_thresholds >= max_attempt_thresholds){
    print("Threshold for maximum number of errors reached. Stopping...")
    break
  }
  
  
  # Start time recording
  t0 <- Sys.time()

  
  # Enforce a pause if this is the second iteration or higher
  if(i > 1){
    Sys.sleep(pause_duration)
  }
  

  # Adjust prompt to reflect respondent i's life-history
  message_history <- list(
    list(
      "role" = "system",
      "content" = "You are a human survey respondent."
    ),
    list(
      "role" = "assistant",
      "content" = simulated_data$life_history_gpt[i]
    ),
    list(
      "role" = "user",
      "content" = NA
    )
  )
  
  
  # Set initial attempt
  attempt <- 1
  
  
  # Use parallel processing to 'create parallel worlds', where each respondent is assigned to either condition and have their outcome measured. Randomization is used to decide the index sequence for unbiasedness
  if(rbinom(1, 1, .5)){
    gpt_results <- foreach::foreach(j = 1:2, .combine = "rbind") %dopar% {
      
      # Adjust prompt to reflect the manipulation condition
      message_history[[3]]$content <- group_condition[[j]]$content
      
      while(attempt <= max_attempts){
        
        # Record attempts
        attempt <- attempt + 1
    
        # Call GPT model (and retry if encountering an error)
        tryCatch(
          expr = {
            gpt_output <- openai::create_chat_completion(
              model = selected_gpt_model,
              messages = message_history,
              max_tokens = max_tokens$outcome,
              temperature = temperature$outcome,
              openai_api_key = OPENAI_API_KEY
            )
            return(data.frame(
              condition = group_condition[[j]]$condition,
              gpt_output = gpt_output
            ))
            break
          },
          error = function(e){
            Sys.sleep(time = 10)
          }
        )
      }
    }
  }else{
    gpt_results <- foreach::foreach(j = 2:1, .combine = "rbind") %dopar% {
      
      # Adjust prompt to reflect the manipulation condition
      message_history[[3]]$content <- group_condition[[j]]$content
      
      while(attempt <= max_attempts){
        
        # Record attempts
        attempt <- attempt + 1
    
        # Call GPT model (and retry if encountering an error)
        tryCatch(
          expr = {
            gpt_output <- openai::create_chat_completion(
              model = selected_gpt_model,
              messages = message_history,
              max_tokens = max_tokens$outcome,
              temperature = temperature$outcome,
              openai_api_key = OPENAI_API_KEY
            )
            return(data.frame(
              condition =  group_condition[[j]]$condition,
              gpt_output = gpt_output
            ))
            break
          },
          error = function(e){
            Sys.sleep(time = 10)
          }
        )
      }
    }
  }
  
  
  # Check is used attempts reach threshold
  if(attempt >= max_attempts){
    attempt_thresholds <- attempt_thresholds + 1
    print(paste0("Maximum number of errors reached threshold. Thresholds met: ", attempt_thresholds, "/", max_attempt_thresholds))
    
    
    # Update progress bar
    setTxtProgressBar(pb, i)
    
    
    # End and store time recording
    t1 <- Sys.time()
    simulated_data$outcome_time_cost <- t1-t0
    
    next
  }
  
  
  # Store 'lazy' outcome
  simulated_data$outcome_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.message.content[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]


  # Store 'lazy' utility info
  simulated_data$outcome_id_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.id[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_object_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.object[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_created_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.created[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_model_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.model[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_prompt_tokens[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.usage.prompt_tokens[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_completion_tokens[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.usage.completion_tokens[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_logprobs[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.logprobs[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_finish_reason[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.finish_reason[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_message.refusal[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.message.refusal[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  simulated_data$outcome_message.role[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.message.role[gpt_results$condition == "lazy"]
  
  
  # Store 'unlucky' counterfactual outcome
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.message.content[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]


  # Store 'unlucky' utility info
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_id_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.id[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_object_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.object[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_created_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.created[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_model_gpt[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.model[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_prompt_tokens[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.usage.prompt_tokens[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_completion_tokens[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.usage.completion_tokens[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_logprobs[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.logprobs[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_finish_reason[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.finish_reason[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_message.refusal[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.message.refusal[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_message.role[i] <- gpt_results$gpt_output.choices.message.role[gpt_results$condition == "unlucky"]
  
  
  # Update progress bar
  setTxtProgressBar(pb, i)
  
  
  # End and store time recording
  t1 <- Sys.time()
  simulated_data$outcome_time_cost <- t1-t0
}


# Convert Unix Timestamp to Datatime
simulated_data$outcome_datetime <- lubridate::as_datetime(simulated_data$outcome_created_gpt)
simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_datetime <- lubridate::as_datetime(simulated_data$outcome_counterfactual_created_gpt)

Executing the above for-loop, generating a counterfactual outcome for the lazy and unlucky welfare recipient manipulation conditions for each of the 1,009 synthetic respondents, takes a total of 182.00 minutes, or 3.03 hours. This means that for these specified settings, the expected time-cost per simulated respondent is 10.82 (SD = .00) seconds. Following this, the generated outcomes can the be examined to ascertain whether the intended output has been generated and if the model ran into any issues generating it. Similar to the generated life-histories, this could involve using coders to check for consistency between the responses and the life-histories/characteristics, but this is beyond the scope of this paper. To help illustrate these LLM-generated counterfactual outcomes, an example of a synthetic respondent with both counterfactual outcomes observed is provided in table 4.6.

Table 4.6: Example of Counterfactual Outcomes

The provided example gives an overview of the expected output produced by the gpt-4o-mini model, which can consist of responses of varying length and concision that may not be as easily processed as data generated by human respondents in a survey. This may not be an issue if the researcher wants to analyze the output in a qualitative manner, however, data can otherwise be converted to a format more easily processed quantitatively by using regular expressions (regex, Thompson 1968; Wickham 2023) to extract the part of the responses that fit with the intended response scale. Since Aare and Petersen (2014) treat the 7-point Likert scale (somewhat inappropriately, cf. Gb et al. 2007; Lantz 2013; Wu and Leung 2017) as interval-scaled (cf. Stevens 1932), this replication similarly converts the outcome to a numeric format for linear analysis. For an overview of the response distributions across these two manipulation conditions, descriptive statistics are provided metrically and graphically in the appendix. Following this, the group balance in synthetic respondent characteristics can then be assessed.

4.4.2 Group Balance

As outlined in the theoretical basis and identification strategy of the SCF, this paper has so far argued that the intra-unit comparisons achieved with parallel worlds-estimation, entirely equivalent to blocking (cf. Duflo et al. 2007: 3925; Gelman et al. 2021: 347-353; Imai et al. 2008: 489), ensures perfect balance in the respondent characteristics across manipulation conditions. Following recommended procedures (Imai et al. 2008; Mutz and Pemantle 2012: 3), to empirically assess whether the SIXAM of parallel worlds-estimation can be expected to not violate the simultaneity assumption, this subsection examines balance in characteristics across the manipulation conditions and tests whether the SIXAM is biased. This is done across all simulated characteristics, comparing their averages or frequencies across the lazy and unlucky welfare recipient manipulation conditions. Consistent with similar recommendations (Imai et al. 2008: 498), unstandardized estimates of group differences are provided. The results are provided in table 4.7.

The balance table reveals that there are invariably no differences in any of the synthetic respondent characteristics across the manipulation conditions, with even the sum of differences across characteristics being exactly zero. With balance being a property of the sample (Stuart 2010: 11; Imai et al. 2008: 497), this means that the results in this study cannot be confounded by these characteristics. While tests using inferential statistics could help ascertain whether the SIXAM is unbiased outside of this particular sample (Mutz and Pemantle 2012: 3), from merely considering the invariable differences of zero, which would yield extreme (e.g., p = 1), if not undefined, test statistics, it can be credibly inferred that the SIXAM guarantees perfect balance on the assigned characteristics on samples as well.

While the balance table only demonstrates perfect balance on the measured characteristics, given that every synthetic respondent is assigned to both manipulation conditions, thus providing every respondent with a perfect unit for comparison across conditions, it is here argued that there is perfect balance not only on the measured characteristics but also every unmeasured characteristic as well, since comparisons of the same unit across two counterfactual conditions implies that all unit-invariant characteristics are balanced as well. This demonstrates the high internal validity of the SCF and the equivalent efficiency between the SIXAM and blocking, especially when compared to other methods (e.g., the RCT) that only guarantees perfect balance on average, or asymptotically as a function of the sample size.

4.4.3 Testing Simultaneity

With group balance having been demonstrated to be perfect, a more relevant concern for researchers using the SCT is testing the simultaneity assumption. As mentioned, this assumption serves to eliminate the ability of time to confound results, which would be possible if the generation and measurement of outcomes across manipulation conditions for the same individual varied. This was why the parallel worlds-estimation procedure was used when generating the outcome data, since parallel processing expectedly helps ensure that the generation occurs simultaneously by using separate computational cores. However, while the use of parallel processing offers a reasonable argument for abiding by the simultaneity assumption, recall that a reasonable argument is seldom a guarantee for the validity of an assumption, and it can be considered best practice to empirically test assumptions when possible to see whether they hold (cf. Hartman and Hidalgo 2018). The simultaneity assumption can be tested since the time of receiving the response by gpt-4o-mini LLM was saved and stored in the data. This allows assessing whether the time difference between generating the outcomes across the two manipulation conditions is zero and whether the generation is biased towards any manipulation condition. If the difference is zero across all synthetic respondents, this suggests that the individual treatment effects (ITE) are unconfounded by time. However, should this be false, another option is that the difference across all individuals are expectedly 0, which means that the average treatment effect (ATE) can be considered unconfounded by time. Both conditions can be interesting to examine, though if the first condition holds, the second condition would necessarily hold as well.

Testing that the difference in outcome generation across manipulation conditions is zero can be done by specifying a statistical model and doing a Bayesian hypothesis test (cf. Heck 2019; Wagenmakers et al. 2010), with an a priori null hypothesis (\(H_0\)) that the time difference (\(\delta\)) in the measurement time across group conditions is zero (\(H_0: \delta = 0\)), and with an alternative hypothesis (\(H_a\)) being that it is non-zero (\(H_a: \delta \ne 0\)).27 As was already made evident in the Bayesian meta-analysis, this study primarily subscribes to abductivist scientific reasoning (Dellsn 2024), in part, by relying on Bayes theorem (Bayes and Price 1763; Laplace 2009[1814]) for statistical inference (Gelman et al. 2014, 2021; Heck 2019; Kruschke 2010; McElreath 2019; Wagenmakers et al. 2010), though it complements this approach with deductive reasoning (Popper 2002[1959]) and Frequentist inference (Fisher 1970; Stock and Watson 2019; Wooldridge 2019), and the hybrid approach of this paper can be considered part of an emerging Bayesian-Frequentist framework (e.g., Han et al. 2023; Wulff and Taylor 2024; Yuan 2009). With this in mind, for the purposes of testing the simultaneity assumption, using notation based on McElreath (2019), a Bayesian model is specified in table 4.8. Note that a Frequentist version of the model can easily be derived by changing the priors to uniform distributions, or equivalently, omitting them entirely (Hastie et al. 2017: 272).

Table 4.8: Simultaneity Test Model
\(D_{z, i} \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{N}(\delta, \varsigma)\) 1.1
\(\delta \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_3(0, \: 1)\) 1.2
\(\varsigma \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}^{(0; \infty]}_3(1, \: .077)\) 1.3

NOTE: Bayesian Generalized Linear Model. 1.1 is the likelihood-function, which specifies that the observations of the outcome variable \(D_{z, i}\) (i.e., the time difference between measurements across the manipulations conditions in time second standard deviations) are assumed to be independent and identically (i.e., iid) distributed as a normal (Gaussian) distribution, with the mean (\(\delta\)) and standard deviation (\(\varsigma\)) parameter being the desired estimands. 1.2 is the mean (\(\delta\)) prior, which is specified to be a Student t distribution (Gosset 1908; Helmert 1876a; 1876b; 1875; Lroth 1876; Pearson 1895b), with a degrees of freedom (df) parameter of 3, mean of 0, and a standard deviation of 1. 1.3 is the prior for the (residual) dispersion (\(\varsigma\)), specified as a non-negative Student t distribution, with a df of 3, mean of 1, and standard deviation of .077.

In the model, the time difference in time second standard deviations is treated as a continuous outcome that is assumed to be independent and identically distributed (iid), following a normal (Gaussian) distribution (Gauss 2012[1809]).28 Following recent recommendations (Lundberg et al. 2021), the quantities of interest (i.e., the estimands) are explicitly stated as the mean (i.e., \(\delta\)) and dispersion (\(\varsigma\)) of this time difference distribution. The prior distribution of the mean is specified to a priori assume no difference, while its standard deviation is specified as 1, which serves to make the priors be weakly informative relative to the data (Gelman et al. 2014: 55-56; Gelman et al. 2021: 123-127). Consistent with practices recommended by Paul-Christian Brkner (2017, 2018), the priors are specified to follow a Student t distribution (Gosset 1908; Helmert 1876a; 1876b; 1875; Lroth 1876; Pearson 1895b), which, following Aki Vehtari, are specified with 3 degrees of freedom (df) to enable a finite mean and variance of the prior distribution. The dispersion (i.e., residual standard deviation) prior is specified as a non-negative Student t with a df of 3. Only non-negative values are allowed, since the dispersion by definition cannot be negative. Its mean is specified as a 1 standard deviation of the time difference, with a standard deviation of .077, which effectively means that the model is a priori expected to account for little to no variation in time difference, with the standard deviation being wide enough to let data prove it wrong. This can be considered more conservative than other approaches (e.g., McElreath 2019: 120-121), which typically specify the prior for the dispersion so that the model is a priori expected to explain all or most variation in the outcome, which is arguably unreasonable for most models, at least in the social sciences.

The model is then fit to the data in R using the brms R package (Brkner 2017, 2018) to exploit STAN (Stan Development Team 2024) and the NUTS algorithm (Hoffman and Gelman 2014) to efficiently draw samples from the time difference posterior distribution. To assess whether the posterior has been reliably identified, 7 independent sampling chains are used, and to increase the reliability of the drawn samples, each chain will first draw 2,000 samples for warmup. Following this, approximately 40,000 samples are then be drawn in total, which serves to reliably identify the posterior and produce precise Bayes factors (BF, Makowski et al. 2019a) by invoking the law of large numbers (Angrist and Pischke 2015: 13-16; Sen and Singer 1993). With model diagnostics and posteriors being provided in the appendix, inspections of the fitted model using traceplots and the Gelman-Rubin Convergence metric (\(\hat{R}\), Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021), the sampling chains are found to reliably converge to the same posterior distribution (\(\hat{R}\) < 1.01), with an approximately zero sampling error as indicated by the negligible Monte-Carlo Standard Error (MCSE .001, Kruschke 2014). Accounting for the autocorrelation between chains, the effective sample size (ESS) can also be considered sufficiently large (ESS 1,000, Brkner 2017).

As previously mentioned, the specified priors may affect the results in an unwanted manner and to validate the priors as noninformative relative to the data, a Frequentist version of the model is estimated using ordinary least squares (OLS, Legendre 1805). Inferential statistics from this model were derived using the non-parametric bootstrap (Efron 1979, 2003; Efron and Tibshirani 1994) with the number of permutations equivalent to the number of posterior samples (i.e., 40,005 permutations), exploiting the fact that the Frequentist bootstrap approximates a Bayesian model with uniform priors (Hastie et al. 2017: 272). Comparing the posterior distribution with its (maximum) likelihood counterpart, while the overlap is a mere 15.32%, the exact difference is nonetheless zero with 95% credibility. Visual comparisons of the distributions (provided in the appendix) suggest that the low overlap is due to the multimodal distribution of the (maximum) likelihood distribution, possibly a result of too few permutations to invoke the law of large numbers for this irregular data. Given the credible lack of difference between the distributions, the priors were nevertheless concluded to be noninformative relative to the data. The posterior distribution for the estimated mean time difference (\(\hat{\delta}\)) parameter is displayed in figure 4.3, while summary statistics are provided in table 4.9.

Figure 4.3: Time Difference Between Measured Group Conditions

NOTE: Posterior distribution of the time difference (in time second standard deviations) between measurements across manipulation conditions (i.e., \(\delta\)). Posterior samples = 40,005. The dashed black line indicates a time difference of zero. The geometric below the distribution indicates the posterior mode (circle), the 95% HDCI (thick bar), 99% HDCI (thin bar), and 99.9% HDCI (line). Results derived from synthetic data generated by OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini using vignettes and questions based on Aare and Petersen (2014) and Petersen et al. (2012), as well as data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

The results reveal that the a priori expectation of a some time difference in generating and measuring the counterfactual outcomes across the lazy and unlucky welfare recipient manipulation conditions has been updated by the data resulting in a estimated average time difference in time second standard deviations of .033 (SD = .031; 95% HDI[-.027; .097]; \(BF_{1,0}\) = .03). Following King et al. (2000), it can be interpreted as, ceteris paribus, compared to the unlucky welfare recipient manipulation condition, the time it takes OpenAIs gpt-4o-mini model to receive and respond to the prompt containing the life-history and manipulation condition (see table 4.5) is on average .033 standard deviations (SD) slower for the lazy welfare recipient manipulation condition, plus or minus .031SD, and with 95% credibility between -.027SD and .097SD. This difference is positive yet relatively small and converted into into raw seconds for ease of interpretation, the unstandardized time difference is merely .740 seconds. This means that despite the attempts to ensure perfect time equivalence across the manipulation conditions, some difference persists in the sample. Since balance is a property of the sample (Stuart 2010: 11; Imai et al. 2008: 497), this means that estimates of individual treatment effects could be biased by being confounded by time. To assess how detrimental this is for the analysis, a summary of the sample, however, reveals that the time difference is exactly zero for 93.76% of the synthetic respondents. Possibly biased estimates thus do not make out the majority of the sample. While it may be argued that the confounding effect of time will have to be large to substantively bias estimates from the data (cf. Cinelli and Hazlett 2020), a more reliable approach would be to complement the main analysis with a sensitivity analysis that omits the possibly time-confounded synthetic respondents to gauge its impact on the results.

\(\hat{\delta}\) Mean .033 (.031) [-.027; .097] 0.295 -3 1 21,127 0 \(\mathcal{T}^{(0; \infty]}_3(.000, 1.000)\)
