Results derived from synthetic data generated by OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini using vignettes and questions based on Aare and Petersen (2014) and Petersen et al. (2012), as well as data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

Turning to the inferential statistics provided by the model, following (Mutz and Pemantle 2012: 3; Imai et al. 2008), these can be used to test whether the current implementation of the parallel worlds-estimation procedure can be expected to violate the simultaneity assumption. Consulting the 95% highest density (posterior) intervals (HD(P)I, McElreath 2019: 56-58), these reveal that the difference is expectly zero with 95% credibility. This can be similarly expressed by considering the two-tailed p-value (cf. Makowski et al. 2019a; 2019b), indicating that the probability of at least as an extreme difference assuming that there is no difference is 29.47%, which would be considered statistically indiscernible from zero at conventional levels (\(p > .05\)). In line with Bayesian inference (Heck 2019; Makowski et al. 2019b; Wagenmakers et al. 2010), an arguably more relevant conclusion can be derived by considering the computed Bayes factor (Makowski et al. 2019a). Assuming that a hypothesized time difference is as probable as no hypothesized time difference, taking then the inverse exponent (Euler 1862) of the resulting posterior log-odds reveals that the hypothesis that the parallel worlds-estimation procedure is unbiased is 20.20 times more probable than the hypothesis that the parallel worlds-estimation procedure is biased. Following the guidelines by Raftery (1995), this can be interpreted to provide strong evidence against against the hypothesis that the parallel worlds-estimation violates the simultaneity assumption by generating non-zero time differences across manipulation conditions given the data. As such, while some time differences do exist in the sample, they make out a small portion, and with regards to the implementation of the parallel worlds-estimation procedure implemented here, the simultaneity assumption has been proven testable, with results indicating that it is unbiased and can be considered to produce no time differences.

4.5 Bayesian Inference

To replicate the meta-analytic estimate derived from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023) as closely as possible, the model used for statistical inference solely includes an intercept and coefficient for the difference between the lazy and unlucky welfare recipient manipulation conditions. Contrary to these existing study, Bayesian inference is used, which can generally be considered superior in terms of interpretation and inference (Cohen 1994: 998-999; Pawitan 2001: 13; Clayton 2021; Gelman et al. 2014, 2021; Kruschke 2010; Kruschke and Liddell 2018; McElreath 2019), though for increased comparability with their results, Frequentist models are used for robustness. As previously alluded to, a caveat of the SCFs ability to generate multiple counterfactual outcomes for each synthetic respondent is that the data can be transformed into a long format to take advantage of these multiple observations for each unit. While this creates a respondent-clustered structure in the data, which would violate the iid assumption because observations in this format would not be independent, it is easily accounted for with a hierarchical/multilevel model (Gelman and Hill 2007; Yarkoni 2020) that specifies respondent-varying intercepts. To ease comparability with the meta-analytic estimates, as well as the estimates by Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023), the responses to the outcome To what extent do you disagree or agree that the eligibility requirements for social welfare should be tightened for persons like him? (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689) are first recoded so that higher values indicate less agreement with tightening the eligibility requirements for the social welfare recipient, which is followed by then normalizing the outcome (i.e., min-maxing: rescaled 0-1). For similar reasons, the categorical variable indicating the manipulation condition is specified so that the reference category is the lazy welfare recipient manipulation. Using notation similar to McElreath (2019) and Nalborczyk et al. (2019), the specified multilevel model is then formalized and provided in table 4.10.

Table 4.10: Modeled Relationship between Deservingness & Welfare Support
\(Y_i \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_\nu(\mu_i, \sigma)\) 1.1
\(\mu_i = \alpha_{id[i]} \: + \: \beta_G \: \cdot \: G_i\) 1.2
\(\beta_G \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_3(0, \: .077)\) 1.3
\(\alpha_{id} \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_3(\mu_\alpha, \: \sigma_\alpha)\) 1.4
\(\mu_\alpha \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_3(.5, \: .039)\) 1.5
\(\sigma_\alpha \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}^{(0; \infty]}_3(0, \: .039)\) 1.6
\(\sigma \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}^{(0; \infty]}_3(.5, \: .039)\) 1.7
\(\nu \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}^{(1; 2018)}_3(2013, \: 155.757)\) 1.8

NOTE: Bayesian Generalized Linear Model with respondent ID-varying intercepts. 1.1 is the likelihood-function, which specifies that the observations of the outcome variable \(Y\) (i.e., welfare support) are assumed to be independent and identically (i.e., iid) distributed as a Student t distribution (Gosset 1908; Helmert 1876a; 1876b; 1875; Lroth 1876; Pearson 1895b), with a mean, dispersion (i.e., residual standard deviation), and degrees of freedom (df) parameters. 1.2 is the affine function (Boyd and Vandenberghe 2018) of the mean parameter, which consists of random (i.e., respondent-level) varying intercepts and a fixed coefficient indicating the difference across the groups (i.e., manipulation conditions), with the lazy welfare recipient vignette being the reference category. 1.3 is the prior of the fixed coefficient, specified as a Student t distribution, with a 3 degrees of freedom (df) parameter, a mean of 0, and dispersion of .077. 1.4 is the prior for the respondent-level varying intercepts, Student t distributed, with a df of 3, an unknown mean, which is the fixed (i.e., US-level) intercept, and an unknown dispersion parameter. 1.5 is the hyper prior for the fixed/mean parameter of the respondent-varying intercepts, being Student t distributed, df of 3, mean of .5, and a dispersion of .039. 1.6 is the hyper prior for the dispersion parameter of the respondent-varying intercepts, being distributed as a non-negative Student t, with a df of 3, mean of 0, and dispersion of .039. 1.7 is the prior for the dispersion of the outcome (RMSE), specified as a non-negative Student t distribution, with a df of 3, mean of .5, and dispersion of .039. 1.8 is the prior for the df parameter of the model, being distributed as a truncated Student t, with a mean of 2,013, dispersion of 155.757, while the truncation includes values between 1 and 2,018.

The model assumes that the outcome distribution (i.e., welfare support) is independent and identically (iid) Student t distributed (Gosset 1908; Helmert 1876a; 1876b; 1875; Lroth 1876; Pearson 1895b), with its mean, dispersion (i.e., residual standard deviation), and degrees of freedom (df) being the estimands (cf. Lundberg et al. 2021). Using a Student t distribution for the likelihood allows estimating the df of the model and makes the model more robust (Gelman et al. 2021: 264-286; McElreath 2019: 233-234; OHagan 1979). The mean is modeled as an affine function (Boyd and Vandenberghe 2018), consisting of random (respondent-varying) intercepts and a fixed (i.e., US-level) coefficient indicating the difference in outcome of seeing an unlucky compared to a lazy welfare recipient. Since the purpose is to compare the results to the meta-analytic estimates derived from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023), to validate the SCFs generalizability, the priors do not incorporate information from their results, but instead are specified as a priori weakly informative relative to the data (cf. Gelman et al. 2014: 55-56; Gelman et al. 2021: 123-127), accounting for the 0 - 1 scaling of the welfare support outcome variable. For example, this is achieved by the prior for the mean of the intercepts (i.e., \(\mu_\alpha\)) exploiting the fact that a normalized variable (range: 0 - 1) with no information could expectedly be centered at .5, and its dispersion (i.e., .039) is specified to permit most values to be within the 0 - 1 bounds. In line with this, the prior for the coefficient (i.e., \(\beta_G\)) a priori assumes no direction, though with a dispersion of .039 it accounts for the coefficient likely being bounded between 0 and 1 due to the normalized scale. Similarly, the prior for the degrees of freedom (df) of the model (i.e., \(\nu\)) expects it to be the number of observations (i.e., n = 2,018) minus the 5 estimated fixed parameters (i.e., \(\beta_G\), \(\mu_\alpha\), \(\sigma_\alpha\), \(\sigma\), and \(\nu\)), with the bounds permitting the lowest possible df of 1 and the highest possible df of 2,018 (i.e., the total number of observations in the long data-format). The upper bound of 2,018 for the df prior is specified to account for the possibility of parameters being mutually informative, allowing for a df higher than 2,013, but also that the model cannot be more robust than permitted by the total number of observations in the data. All priors are specified using a Student t to similarly exploit its robust properties, with a df of 3 to ensure that they have a finite mean and variance. While these prior specifications may not be optimal and could be criticized if they impact the results in an unwanted manner, a property of Bayesian inference is that the likelihood (i.e., the estimates when omitting the priors) relatively quickly overwhelms the priors as the sample size increases (Wagenmakers et al. 2010: 167). To validate this, in a manner similar to the meta-analysis and simultaneity test, priors will be checked to ascertain whether they are weakly informative relative to the data by comparing Bayesian estimates with Frequentist estimates, which would indicate that their impact on results are inconsequential.

With this model specified, a few a priori considerations for testing the two aforementioned hypothesis can be made. In relation to the expectation that increasing deservingness increases welfare support (\(H_1\)), this is supported by the coefficient being (1) credibly different from zero as ascertained by a 95% highest density (contiguous) interval (HD(C)I, Kay 2024a; 2024b; Makowski et al. 2019a; McElreath 2019: 56-58), or similarly with a 95% bias-corrected and accelerated (BCa, Efron 1987) or a 95% equal-tailed confidence interval (CI, Stock and Watson 2019: 117-118) for Frequentist models, which following recommendations (Brandsttter 1999), are here preferred over p-values; and (2) that the relative evidence in the form of the posterior odds (Makowski et al. 2019a; i.e., BF with prior odds of 1, Wagenmakers et al. 2010) indicates that the hypothesis of a relationship between deservingness and welfare is more probable than the (null) hypothesis of no such relationship (i.e., \(ln(BF) > 0\)) given the data. It should also be noted that the sample size is listed as 2,018 in the analysis, due to the long-format of the data that accounts for each synthetic respondent in the nominal sample (n = 1,009) having had an outcome measured two times, one for each counterfactual outcome. With these considerations in mind, an analysis of the results can be conducted.

5 Analyses

With the overall aim of replicating the meta-analytic estimate of the effect of deservingness on welfare support, this section first covers (1) a confirmatory analysis that tests the hypothesized causal relationship between deservingness and welfare support (i.e., \(H_1\)). The robustness of the results are then assessed in (2) a sensitivity analysis, which includes numerous alternative model specifications, including a test of heterogenous effects across the specified characteristics, and a test of whether the partial violation of the simultaneity assumption results in time confounding the results. To test the hypothesis that results are the same whether derived from synthetic or human respondents (i.e., \(H_2\)), the section then (3) compares the results from the main analysis to the meta-analytic estimate derived from the human-based studies (i.e., Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019). Lastly, to provide researchers with an overview of the costs induced by using the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF), (4) a cost analysis assesses the financial and time costs of its implementation as a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT).

5.1 Confirmatory Analysis

To test the theorized relationship between deservingness and welfare support (\(H_1\)), the specified multilevel Bayesian statistical model (see table 4.10) is fitted to the synthetic data. Similar to estimating the Bayesian models for the meta-analysis and the test of the simultaneity assumption, this procedures uses the NUTS Hamiltonian MCMC (Hoffman and Gelman 2014) of STAN (Stan Development Team 2024), implemented by the brms R package (Brkner 2017, 2018), using 7 independent sampling chains, with 2,000 warmup samples per chain, followed by a total of approximately 40,000 post-warmup samples. For ease of overview, results are provided graphically and metrically. To give a sense of the difference in welfare support induced by the manipulations, predicted welfare support across manipulation conditions are illustrated in figure 5.1. For the exact difference, the posterior of the estimated difference across manipulation conditions is provided in figure 5.2. For summary estimates and model diagnostics, summary statistics in a metric format are provided in table 5.1. Model diagnostics and results not covered here are provided in the appendix.

Figure 5.1: Differences in Welfare Support across Manipulation Conditions

NOTE: Posterior distributions of the normalized (0 - 1) welfare support across group conditions. Posterior samples = 40,005. The geometric below the distributions indicate the posterior mode (circle) and the 95% HDCI. Results derived from synthetic data generated by OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini using vignettes and questions based on Aare and Petersen (2014) and Petersen et al. (2012), as well as data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

To first assess, whether the results by the model are reliable, model diagnostics are inspected. These reveal that the posterior has been reliably identified, with chain convergence being excellent (\(\hat{R}\) < 1.01, Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021), the effective sample size being sufficient (ESS > 1,000, Brkner 2017), and there is almost no sampling uncertainty (MCSE < .000, Kruschke 2014). By comparing the results to a Frequentist bootstrapped version of the same model (see the Sentivity Analysis-section), which found an overlap of 97.17% and no difference with 95% credibility, priors were validated as noninformative relative to the data.29 In terms of the models goodness-of-fit, the posterior predictive p-value (\(PP_P\), Gelman et al. 1996) of 0.942 indicates that the model tends to make exaggerated estimates of welfare support, but the Bayesian \(R^2\) (Gelman et al. 2019) of .721 (SD = .011; 95% HDI[.701; .742]), by contrast, indicates that the models explanatory power can with 99.99% credibility be interpreted as substantial (Cohen 1988), suggesting a relatively high fit. Since the results of the model are thus relatively reliable, with the priors being noninformative relative to the data, focus can be directed to the model parameters, which can be used to assess whether deservingness increases welfare support (i.e., \(H_1\)).

Figure 5.2: Difference in Welfare Support for an Unlucky Welfare Recipient compared to a Lazy Welfare Recipient

NOTE: Posterior distribution of the normalized (0 - 1) coefficient of deservingness on welfare support. Posterior samples = 40,005. The geometric below the distribution indicates the posterior mode (circle), the 95% HDCI (thick bar), 99% HDCI (thin bar), and 99.9% HDCI (line). Results derived from synthetic data generated by OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini using vignettes and questions based on Aare and Petersen (2014) and Petersen et al. (2012), as well as data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

Does deservingness increase welfare support? Since the difference across the manipulation conditions are positive with 95% credibility, and the relative evidence (i.e., \(BF_{1,0}\)) overwhelmingly supports \(H_1\), deservingness would seem to increase welfare support among synthetic respondents. This is indicated by the normalized (0 - 1) deservingness-coefficient of .607 (SD = .009; 95% HDI[.590; .625]; \(ln(BF_{1,0})\) = 228.24), where the 95% highest density interval (HDI, cf. McElreath 2019: 56-58; Makowski et al. 2019a) indicates that the coefficient is positive and discernible from zero with 95% credibility. The estimated effect of deservingness on welfare support can, following King et al. (2000), specifically be interpreted as the following: Ceteris paribus, compared to seeing a lazy welfare recipient (i.e., someone low in deservingness), an individuals support for less strict requirements for welfare eligibility is on average 60.68 percentage points (pp) higher, plus or minus .91pp, and with 95% credibility between 58.96pp and 62.51pp, when seeing an unlucky welfare recipient (i.e., someone high in deservingness).

These results are consistent with the theorized relationship and is further corroborated by the computed Bayes factor (i.e., \(BF_{1,0}\), cf. Makowski et al. 2019a; Wagenmakers et al. 2010), which is reported on the natural-logarithmic scale due to its size. Assuming a priori that the hypothesized effect is as probable as the hypothesis of no effect, the \(BF_{1,0}\) indicates that the hypothesized effect (i.e., \(H_1\)) is much more probable than the hypothesis of no effect given the data. Following the guidelines by Raftery (1995), the relative evidence provided by the \(BF_{1,0}\) can specifically be interpreted to provide very strong evidence in favour of the hypothesized relationship between deservingness and welfare support given the data. Having thus found substantial support for the hypothesized causal relationship between deservingness and welfare support among synthetic respondents (\(H_1\)), an assessment can be made regarding the robustness of these results.

5.2 Sensitivity Analysis

Are the results robust? With the estimates seeing no substantial difference as a result of changing the Bayesian model (table 4.10) to (1) a Frequentist bootstrapped version, (2) changing from random effects to fixed effects, (3) including interactions with the assigned characteristics, nor (4) omitting synthetic respondents for whom the measurement time difference was non-zero, this insensitivity to varying model specifications suggest that the results from the main analysis are generally robust. This is based on a sensitivity analysis (cf. Athey and Imbens 2017: 19-21), which involved 4 separate assessments, each focused on different aspects by which the results could vary as a function of the model specification. The first assessment addressed the reliance on Bayesian inference and the possible impact that the specification of priors could have on the results. The second assessment examined whether a change from the models random effects (i.e., ID-varying intercepts) to fixed effects impacted inference. The third assessment investigated the possibility of heterogenous treatment effects, which involved re-specifying the main model to include interactions with the assigned characteristics. The fourth assessment sought to address the possibility that the violation of the simultaneity assumption for some of the synthetic respondents (see the Testing Simultaneity-section) could confound the results.

Considering first the possibility that Bayesian inference involves specifying priors which may inadvertantly impact results due to being strongly informative relatively to the data (Gelman et al. 2014: 55-56; Gelman et al. 2021: 123-127), the main model was changed to its Frequentist counterpart by omitting the priors. The Frequentist model was then estimated using restricted maximum likelihood (REML, Bates et al. 2015; Patterson and Thompson 1971), and for comparability with the Bayesian results, inferential statistics was estimated using the relatively computationally intensive non-parametric bootstrap (Efron 1979, 2003), with the number of permutations being equivalent to the Bayesian posterior samples (i.e., 40,005 permutations). Similar to the Frequentist counterpart-model estimated for the meta-analysis and simultaneity test, inferential statistics apply Frequentist estimators to produce bias-reduced standard errors (SE, Park et al. 2022; Park and Wang 2020, 2022) and bias-corrected and accelerated (BCa) confidence intervals (Efron 1987; Makowski et al. 2019a). The resulting estimated average effect of deservingness in this Frequentist model is .607 (SE = .009; 95% BCa[.590; .625]), indicating a 95% confident difference in welfare support of 60.74pp on average when exposed to a unlucky welfare recipient compared to a lazy welfare recipient, all else equal. This closely resembles the Bayesian estimate, and the exact difference is -.001 (SD = .013; 95% HDI[-.025; .025]), which indicates a negligible difference that is zero with 95% credibility. Accordingly, the impact of the priors is negligible, and they can be considered noninformative relative to the data, showing that results are robust across the Bayesian and Frequentist approaches.

The second assessment involved changing the random effects of the Bayesian model to fixed effects (Wooldridge 2019: 463-472; Stock and Watson 2019: 367-376), with both random and fixed effects having their own advantages in different circumstances (Wooldridge 2019: 473-474; Rabe-Hesketh and Skrondal 2012: 95-97; McElreath 2019: 399-431). While fixed effects can remove all unit-invariant confounding (Wooldridge 2019: 463-472; Stock and Watson 2019: 367-376), since intra-unit comparisons are part of the identification strategy of the SCF, this property is already incorporated into the design of the SCF, and random effects were thus preferred for the main analysis due to its properties of partial-pooling making results more generalizable (Rabe-Hesketh and Skrondal 2012: 96; Yarkoni 2020) and less prone to overfitting (McElreath 2019: 399-431). Since a non-parametric bootstrap becomes more computationally demanding with fixed effects, inference for the Frequentist fixed-effects model solely relied on asymptotics (Stock and Watson 2019: 690-695; Wooldridge 2019: 117-180), employing 95% equal-tailed confidence intervals (Stock and Watson 2019: 117-118) and cluster-robust standard errors (Stock and Watson 2019: 376) to account for the multiple observations. Accordingly, the estimates are reported as provided by the statistical software used for this model (i.e., Berg 2018) without applying extra bias-corrections. The results of this model are .607 (SE = .009; 95% CI[.590; .625]), and the fact that these estimates do not differ in any substantial way to the results from the main analysis indicates that the results are insensitive to the specification of random or fixed effects.

Having argued that assigning and generating life-histories based on nationally representative characteristics could make the behavior of the synthetic respondents more nuanced and realistic, a third assessment served to analyse whether the estimates varied across the assigned characteristics, which could imply that the assignment of nationally representative characteristics mattered for the results. This involved modifying the main model to include linear interactions between the manipulation condition and each characteristic. Similar to the Frequentist fixed-effects model, for computational ease, inference for the model relied on asymptotics. Due to the relatively large number of estimated parameters in this model, consistent with the Frequentist approach, the p-values are adjusted to account for the inflated false-discovery rate (FDR, Benjamini and Yekutieli 2001) associated with the multiple comparisons (Shaffer 1995; Wright 1992) made by the model. While a run-down of every parameter is beyond the scope of this paper, it should be briefly mentioned that, statistically discernible heterogenous deservingness-effects on welfare support were identified for political ideology and preferred political party (\(p_{adj} \le .05\)), and prior to the adjustments, interactions with sex, 2 levels of education, and 3 US states (i.e., Arkansas, Alabama, and Florida) were also confidently non-zero. Given the substantial statistical power necessary to identify interactions (Gelman et al. 2021), and the models assumption that the interactions for the continuous variables are linear, these results regarding the presence or absence of interactions should be taken with caution. The main takeaway of this assessment is that the interactions for some of the assigned characteristics are consistent with heterogenous effects, suggesting that the assignment of relevant characteristics from which to generate life-histories could indeed impact results and possibly make results more generalizable to the human population of interest.

The last assessment of robustness sought to address the finding that the simultaneity assumption appeared to have been violated for a relatively small subset of synthetic respondents. This was an issue, since it allowed time to possibly confound the results, because time-invariant confounders were no longer eliminated by design. An analysis of this possibility involved omitting all synthetic respondents for whom the time difference in measuring the counterfactual outcomes was non-zero, resulting in a nominal sample size of 946. Fitting a Frequentist non-parametric bootstrapped version of the main model to the long-form of this data, with inference again relying on the aforementioned bias-reduced estimators, this resulted in an estimated effect of deservingness of .607 (SE = .009; 95% BCa[.588; .625]). This estimate is with 95% confidence non-zero and of similar direction and magnitude as the main results. In fact, the exact difference is .000 (SD = .013; 95% HDI[-.025; .026]), which again is neglible and zero with 95% credibility. As such, when completely eliminating the possibility of time confounding results, there is no substantial impact on the main results, and the main results can be considered relatively robust to time confounding. With this sensitivity analysis in mind, the results can thus be considered robust. This leaves the question of whether this SCF-based approach has managed to adequately replicate the meta-analytic results derived from the human-based studies (i.e., \(H_2\)), which is addressed in the subsequent section.

5.3 Replication Analysis

Do the results replicate the meta-analysis? Comparing the SCF-based estimate derived from a synthetic sample to the meta-analytic estimate derived from human samples, while revealing varying magnitudes, they are both positive and discernible from zero with 95% credibility. Assessing the exact difference reveals support for \(H_2\) with there being no difference with 95% credibility, and the results can be considered to replicate the meta-analysis. This is made evident by first comparing the results from the SCF-based main analysis to the human-based results from the Bayesian analysis. For robustness, this is followed by comparing the main results with the results from the aforementioned Frequentist meta-analysis.

To compare the Bayesian estimates from the main analysis with the meta-analytic estimate, recall that the results of the Bayesian meta-analysis of the human-based studies (i.e., Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019) revealed an uncertainty-weighted average estimated effect of deservingness on welfare support of .44 (SD = .12; 95% HDI[.12; .61]). Visually comparing the estimates reveals both to be positive and different from zero with 95% credibility, which can be taken as evidence that the SCF can produce estimates of similar direction and certainty as human-based studies. However, the SCF-based estimates do appear to be of a larger magnitude than the meta-analytic estimate, though it remains of a similar magnitude to the individual human-based studies by Mummelo and Peterson (2019, their MTurk study) and Kane et al. (2023) of approximately .550 (SE = .023; 95% CI[.505; .595]) and .583 (SE = .026; 95% CI[.532; .634], respectively. The fact that the human-based estimates are also of similarly larger magnitudes than the meta-analytic estimate is consistent with the SCF-based estimates similarly deviating from the meta-analytic mean due to the known properties of sampling variability and heterogeneous effects across studies. This can be further examined by computing the exact difference between the SCF-based and human-based results, revealing a difference (in pp) of 16.77 (SD = 11.92; 95% HDI[-1.14; 48.30]), which provides support for \(H_2\) by indicating no systematic difference between the SCF-based and human-based estimates with 95% credibility.

To further ensure the robustness of this finding, the SCF-based results are also compared to the Frequentist-version of the meta-analysis, which yielded the aforementioned SE-weighted estimated average of .50 (SE = .06; 95% BCa[.38; .62]). Visually comparing these estimates to the SCF-based estimates leads to the same conclusions of similar direction and credibility of the results, with the exact difference (in pp) between the Frequentist meta-analytic estimate and the SCF-based estimate being 10.40 (SD = 6.43; 95% HDI[-1.37; 22.43]). While the SCF-based estimates again are somewhat exaggerated compared to the meta-analytic estimate, though now to a lesser extent and still of similar magnitude to results by Mummolo and Peterson (2019) and Kane et al. (2023), it can again be stated that there is no systematic difference between the estimates with 95% credibility, thus further supporting \(H_2\).

Considering that the SCF manages to replicate the direction and credibility of human-based studies, with some exaggeration subject to sampling variability and study-based heterogeneity, this replication analysis do find relatively robust evidence that this SCF-based replication of the relationship between deservingness and welfare support among synthetic respondents succeeds in replicating the human-based results. With support for \(H_2\) by merit of the similarity in the results, this demonstrates not just the high internal validity (cf. Stock and Watson 2019: 478-481) of the SCF, corroborating the theoretical justifications outlined in its conceptualization, but also its relatively high external validity (cf. Stock and Watson 2019: 481; Gelman et al. 2021: 354-355), as indicated by its ability to replicate the robust human-based causal relationship between deservingness and welfare support. As such, based on the analysis of this replication study, it is concluded that the LLM-driven SCF, at least as implemented in the form of an SCT, is capable of generating causal estimates using an adequately-powered and representative sample of synthetic respondents, that if investigated in human populations, can be expected to replicate. At the same time, despite the relatively large sample used here (n = 1,009), no single replication can ultimately validate a theoretical framework, and it thus remains a possibility that SCF-results can fail to generalize beyond the topic of deservingness and welfare support investigated in this study. Before discussing the implications of the formalization of the SCF, the novel concepts of synthetic units, parallel worlds-estimation, the SCT, its external validity, and this replication, a cost analysis will ascertain the financial and time costs of implementing the SCF as an SCT.

5.4 Cost Analysis

As the final part of the analysis of this demonstrative replication study and proof-of-concept of the SCF, this section ascertains the costs associated with the SCF. This serves to help researchers estimate the expected costs of relying on the SCF compared to using human samples. For this, it should be emphasized that all costs reported in this analysis are based on the application of the SCF specific to the replication study, such as the choice of the gpt-4o-mini LLM by Openai (2024a), the sample size, number of characteristics from which to generate life-histories, the length and wording of the life-history prompts, the token limitations on the output by the LLM, the length and wording of the prompt containing the manipulation conditions, and the number of manipulation conditions from which to generate counterfactual outcomes. Note also that the only costs considered for this analysis involves financial and time costs incurred from making requests to the LLM API, specifically the gpt-4o-mini LLM API by Openai (2024a), with usage costs being specific to the chosen LLM. Such costs incur due to the LLM using resources to process the prompt and generate a response output, with financial costs being tied to the length of the prompt in terms of tokens, with each token in a text-based prompt corresponding to approximately one word. At the same time, costs vary for input and output tokens. Researchers should keep in mind that while newer models may show better performance, that the selected gpt-4o-mini are among the cheapest and most cost-efficient at the time of writing (cf. OpenAI 2025b), charging on average 0.375 $US per 1,000,000 input/output tokens used. Besides considering financial costs, time costs are also considered, which involve the time that the LLM takes to process requests and the pauses enforced between making calls to the LLM to respect the time limits by OpenAI. With these considerations in mind, the financial and time costs incurred by relying on the SCF to generate the life-histories and the counterfactual outcomes can be estimated.

Financial Costs. In terms of financial costs, generating 1,009 life-histories and two counterfactual outcomes with the provided prompts and specified settings, the total cost is estimated to be .56 $US. This means that the expected financial cost per respondent is merely .001 (SD = .000) US dollars. Compared to studies that rely on human participants, this can be considered significantly cheap, especially considering that human-based studies may costs thousands of dollars to achieve a sample size compared to the 1,009 used in this replication study. At the same time, with an implementation of SCF as demonstrated here, saving the resources that it could otherwise cost to ensure that a human-based sample is representative could allow the researcher to re-allocate the resources where they are needed more. Similarly, while laboratory experiments and field experiments arguably do provide a high internal validity (Gerber and Green 2012), the SCF, as demonstrated here, provides a comparably high internal validity, and researchers may consider how many resources could be saved to working within the framework of the SCF.

Time Costs. Another relevant cost for researchers to consider is time costs. Generating the life-histories and the counterfactual outcomes for the lazy and unlucky welfare recipient manipulation conditions took a total of 374.76 minutes (i.e., 6.25 hours.). With 1,009 synthetic respondents, the expected time cost per respondent is 22.29 (SD = .00) seconds. Compared to human studies that may take months to obtain such a sample size, this can generally be considered a substantial reduction in the time taking to obtain this many survey responses. This means that researchers can save a substantial amount of time by applying the SCF to conduct an SCT compared to having to rely on human respondents, which can be considered advantageous, since their work effort can be dedicated more to doing research rather than waiting for data collection to finish.

Taken together, this cost analysis thus reveals that the SCF, through is implementation as an SCT, can be considered substantively less costly, both in terms of the financial and time resources needed to conduct a study. The demonstration has revealed that the SCF is capable is generating large and representative samples of data, where synthetic respondents can be subjected to numerous manipulation conditions to have their counterfactual outcomes generated in simultaneous and independent parallel processes, producing results that can generalize to human-based studies. The SCT can thus be expected to save surmountable resources for researchers, and the financial bar needed to conduct a study with a high internal validity and external validity is substantially lowered, thus increasing the ability of researchers to make reliable causal inferences across disciplines, particularly when the theorized cause is non-manipulable and where both the theorized cause and outcome are meaningfully expressible through natural language.

6 Discussion

With this paper having introduced the conceptualization of a novel causal framework, the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF), theoretically outlined to enable reliable causal inference when the theorized cause is non-manipulable in human populations, it solves the existing issue of researchers being unable to manipulate relevant phenomena of interest (e.g., Buunk and van Vugt 2013: 17). Solving this issue was found to be especially pertinent given that practically any result derived from non-manipulated (i.e., endogenous) phenomena could, in principle, be subject to confounding (Fisher 1935; Greenland et al. 1999; VanderWeele and Shpitser 2013). As mentioned, while the existing concept of the longitudinal design (Wooldridge 2019: 7-10, 334-335) does help address the issue of reverse causality (cf. Hume 2011), for any endogenous phenomenon, neither positive results nor negative results imply causality (cf. Kennaway 2015; Manninen 2019c; Pearson 2015[1900]) due to the respective possibilities of spuriousness and masking (Gumbel 1933; McElreath 2019: 123-153; Stock and Watson 2019: 584-586). By recognizing that the burden of proof rests upon the researcher making a causal claim (cf. Cargile 1988; Hume 2010[1748]; Russo 2019; Sagan 1979), existing methods for making causal inference proved generally unreliable (e.g., Baker et al. 2022; Bertrand et al. 2004; Ferman 2023; Kahn-Lang and Lang 2020; Ryan et al. 2015; Samii 2016; Wan et al. 2024) due to their reliance on untestable and dubious assumptions that, contrary to best practice (cf. Rohrer 2018: 34; Stuart 2010: 3; Samii 2016), were not guaranteed by design. By contrast, the SCF does not suffer these limitations due to eliminating confounding by design. To gather the insights derived from its development, a summary and discussion of its theoretical formalization and empirical validation are provided in this section.

With a definition of causality based on the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (POF, Holland 1986; Imbens 2015: 374-377; Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005) as the difference in potential outcomes between two physically and temporally distinct phenomena, with solely the temporally-precedent cause varying across the potential outcomes, the SCF is formalized using the POF. As such, it can be considered as an extension of it, with the causal identification strategy of the SCF being directly derived from POF-based equations, which involve intra-unit comparisons of simultaneous and independent counterfactual outcomes. To enable this counterfactual comparison, the SCF is based on the theoretical foundation that language and behavior are closely related and mutually informative: The behavior of individuals shape their language, and their language shape their behavior (cf. Bandura 1999; Chung et al. 2007; Galton 1884; Holtgraves 2013; Lucy 1992; Pennebaker et al. 2003; Thibodeau and Boroditsky 2011; Whorf 2011[1956]). With Large Language Models (LLMs, Shanahan 2024) having proved increasingly capable of emulating human natural language and showing human-comparable performance in numerous disciplines (cf. Colette et al. 2024; Holderried et al. 2024; Jansen et al. 2023; Ornstein et al. 2024; Pang et al. 2024), the use of LLMs to emulate human behavior is paramount to the SCF. This also means that the SCF is formalized to enable reliable causal inference with non-manipulable phenomena in human populations, limiting its intended scope of application to topics belonging to the social and behavioral sciences (cf. Wright 2015). Accordingly, through its reliance on LLMs to achieve this goal, a key assumption of the SCF is that the theorized cause and outcome must be meaningfully expressed through natural language, and for the ability of the LLM to emulate behavior associated with the theorized cause and outcome, it must have been trained on data containing expressions of these phenomena. While these restrictions can limit the usefulness of the SCF, they nonetheless reflect relevant considerations about the areas of application for which the SCF can be considered meaningful. Similarly, explicitly specifying the intended scope and expected limitations serve to make researchers aware that the SCF may not be equally valid nor as reliable across all topics of interest and that applications outside of its intended area of application warrants further considerations, justification, and validation.

The reliance of the SCF on LLMs in emulating human behavior to enable the manipulation of a non-manipulable phenomena specifically involves the generation of simulated units. These units are defined here to possess human characteristics, whose inclusion serve as a basis to guide the behavior of the LLM when controlling each unit in a more nuanced and human-like direction. It is here important that an adequate number of relevant characteristics are simulated so that the resulting behavior becomes as realistic as possible. At the same time, since applications of the SCF will likely involve simulated samples of human units drawn from a particular population of interest, to enable better inference, it is important that the characteristics assigned to these units are simulated in proportion to their prevalence in that particular population. To further make the behavior of the LLM-controlled simulated units more realistic and generalizable, life-histories (cf. Schtze 2008) are generated by the LLM based on the assigned characteristics, enabling a more fleshed-out and realistic characterization of each unit. This step is taken to infuse the simulated units with human-nuance not captured by the assigned characteristics, resulting in these units being conceptually distinguished as synthetic units. With the intended use of the SCF being the inference of causality to human populations, the use of simulated data may be seen as invalid or meaningless because human units are not directly used in an SCF-based analysis. However, this criticism would fail to account for indirect way that human text-based behavioral data are used to train the LLMs, not to mention the existing use of simulated and synthetic data for research into real-world phenomena (e.g., Abowd et al. 2004; Emam et al. 2020; Kinney et al. 2011; Macy and Willer 2002; Nikolenko 2021; van Lange et al. 2013: 31; Zivenko et al. 2025). Similarly, from the recognized disciplines of functionalist and behaviorist psychology (Farrell 2014: 88, 111, 362-403), the study of human behavior does not necessitate the studied unit necessarily being human, with the key requirement instead being the respective functional or behavioral equivalence between humans and the studied unit. As long as researchers can plausibly justify why the function or behavior is expectedly similar, if not equivalent, between synthetic units and human units, SCF-based research can be considered valid and meaningfully inferrable to human populations.

Once synthetic units have been generated, each of these can be manipulated with respect to the theorized cause enabling reliable causal inference through the elimination of all unit- and time-invariant confounders. Similar to a random assignment mechanism (RAM) employed in Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs, cf. Angrist and Pischke 2015: 1-46; Angrist and Pischke 2009: 15-22; Stock and Watson 2019: 48-49), the SCF employs a simultaneous and independent exogenous assignment mechanism (SIXAM), which simultaneously and independently assigns each synthetic unit to every manipulation condition through a parallel process, jointly referred to as parallel worlds-estimation. The simultaneous and independent nature of this assignment helps eliminate most concerns for pre-treatment and post-treatment biases (cf. Linos and Twist 2018; Montgomery et al. 2018). Once a counterfactual outcome for each manipulation condition has been generated, intra-unit comparisons thus provide an unbiased and efficient strategy for causal identification (cf. Westreich et al. 2015). While this procedure essentially enables the researcher to multiply the initial sample of synthetic units by a factor equivalent to the number of manipulation conditions, this does result in a sample with autocorrelated observations (cf. Gelman et al. 2021: 459; Stock and Watson 2019: 375), since the multiple counterfactual observations are clustered around each synthetic unit. This, however, is not a critical concern, since the multiple observations of each unit easily addressed through the use of multilevel statistical models (cf. Gelman and Hill 2007) or alternatively through the use of cluster-robust standard errors (cf. Stock and Watson 2019: 376). One might criticize that the ability to eliminate unit-invariant and time-invariant confounders with these intra-unit comparisons of counterfactual outcomes may be invalid and/or unreliable by relying on dubious assumptions. For example, the ability to measure counterfactual outcomes for the same synthetic respondent assumes (1) that the LLM treats the synthetic unit as the exact same unit across the multiple manipulation conditions (e.g., prior to each manipulation conditions, unit i in manipulation condition k is exactly the same as unit i in manipulation condition k), and (2) that the responses are generated simultaneously (i.e., the simultaneity assumption). As a response to these criticisms, it can be argued that the former assumption can be justified by stating that the units across the manipulation conditions are the same conditional on their life-histories, and should the LLM possibly infer different characteristics not specified in the life-histories conditional on the manipulation condition that this is not innately different from how varying manipulation conditions, such as framing or priming vignettes (cf. Bargh and Chartrand 2000; Tversky and Kahneman 1981), could affect the self-perceptions of human participants, with certain memories, characteristics, thoughts, and behaviors varying in saliency (see, e.g., Fausey and Boroditsky 2010; Thibodeau and Boroditsky 2011). Regarding the latter assumption, simultaneity can be promoted by implementing the outlined parallel worlds-estimation procedure and ensuring that the manipulation conditions, if implemented as text-based prompts, are of the same character length and word length. Similarly, as demonstrated in the proof-of-concept, the simultaneity assumption can be tested, with the analysis being capable of accounting for possible violations. Accordingly, the assumptions made by the SCF can be justified and they do not invoke premises innately contradicting existing research.

While the formalization of the SCF as reiterated above arguably provides a strong justification for the high internal validity of this framework (cf. Stock and Watson 2019: 478-481), there are justified concerns, especially regarding its external validity (cf. Stock and Watson 2019: 481; Gelman et al. 2021: 354-355). To address such concerns and provide a demonstrative proof-of-concept, the SCF was implemented with the purpose of comparing its results to human-based studies. Specifically, this sought to replicate the robustly established causal relationship between deservingness and welfare support (cf. Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019). This relationship was theoretically grounded in evolutionary psychology (cf. Buss 2019), with the causal mechanism involving a distinct cognitive module (cf. Kurzban and Aktipis 2007) dubbed the deservingness heuristic (cf. Petersen 2012), an automatic and compulsory mechanism that evaluates the deservingness of individuals with respect to (welfare) support through use of information shortcuts, such as stereotypes (Aare and Petersen 2014; Petersen et al. 2011, 2012). A meta-analysis was used to aggregate results from existing studies (cf. Sharpe and Poets 2020), leading to the formalization of the hypotheses that deservingness increases welfare support and, based on the theoretical basis of the SCF, that this relationship did not differ between human and SCF-based studies. Conceptually replicating the original study on deservingness and welfare support (i.e., Aare and Petersen 2014), a random sample of 1,009 simulated humans from the adult population of the United States (US) was drawn. Each simulated unit were assigned the relevant characteristics of US state of residence, area of residence, sex, age, number of children, ethnoracial group, marital status, level of education, employment status, annual household gross income in 2022 US dollars, preferred political party, and political ideology, with each characteristics being jointly simulated using population-based estimates derived from the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021), resulting in a sample representative on all the relevant characteristics. Based on these characteristics, life-histories were then generated using the cost-efficient and highly capable gpt-4o-mini LLM (OpenAI 2024a), with requests being made through its API for efficiency and privacy concerns. These life-histories were validated to consistently reflect the assigned characteristics, though each characteristic was not necessarily explicitly mentioned. To serve as the manipulation conditions in a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT), the SCFs version of an RCT, vignettes detailing a lazy and unlucky welfare recipient were adapted to have the same word and character length without changing their substantive meaning, which served to ensure that the counterfactual outcomes could be generated simultaneously. Using an implementation of the parallel worlds-estimation procedure, the life-histories and vignettes were supplied as prompts to the gpt-4o-mini LLM, and a counterfactual outcome of welfare support was generated for each synthetic respondent in response to each manipulation condition. Assessments then unsurprisingly revealed perfect balance on the assigned characteristics across manipulation conditions, though a test of the simultaneity of the parallel worlds-estimation procedure revealed a non-zero time difference for a small subset of synthetic respondents, which could enable time to confound results. A multilevel Bayesian model was specified for the analysis (cf. Brkner 2017, 2018), which confirmed the hypothesis that deservingness increases welfare support among synthetic respondents. This was reinforced by a sensitivity analysis (cf. Athey and Imbens 2017: 19-21), and the partial non-zero time differences was also found not to substantively impact the results. A replication analysis then found that the results did not credibly differ from the human-based meta-analytic results, indicating that results were externally valid and generalizable to a human population. A cost analysis was also conducted to reveal that compared to human studies that the SCF was substantially cheaper and more time-efficient.

While this conceptual replication study does provide evidence for both the internal and external validity of the SCF, corroborating its central aim of enabling causal effects to be identified from synthetic samples and generalized to human populations, no single study can sufficiently validate a framework. Despite the strong theoretical foundation for its internal validity, in part due to the SCT mimicking the strengths of the RCT, it is impossible to properly validate the ability of the SCF to derive the correct causal estimate from a non-manipulable phenomenon and infer it to humans because it is by definition not manipulable in human populations. This means that justifying a reliance on the SCF will, in part, have to rely on a continued validation against results from theorized cause that are manipulable in human populations. Another concern of the SCF is that for it to fulfill its intended goal of enabling researchers to draw reliable causal inference for non-manipulable phenomena, it needs to be relatively easily implementable. With this study having done its best not only to describe the theoretical foundation and rationale of the SCF in an attempt to explain the scope, area of application, assumptions, and limitations behind the SCF, it has also provided a proof-of-concept and validation of the SCF, including making the data and code to replicate its entire implementation freely available. By doing this, the hope is that researchers can relatively easily implement the SCF for their particular research topic. However, since the SCF does require modifying the provided code to suit their particular research context, researchers may nonetheless find the SCF difficult to implement. It is the hope of the researcher that future work will serve to address these practical limitations by making the SCF more easily implementable. At the same time, future studies could be conducted to expand the implementation of the SCF to designs besides the SCT. For example, an SCF-based version of a field experiment (cf. Gerber and Green 2012), which by merit of simulating a more realistic study environment may provide more ecologically valid results than the SCT (cf. Schmuckler 2001). At the same time, following the mantra of garbage-in-garbage-out (GIGO, Yoder-Wise 2023), researchers implementing the SCF needs to be aware that a central premise for its reliability is the quality of the results are contingent on the quality of the input and that not all LLMs may be equally capable of emulating human behavior (cf. Edyko et al. 2023; Koga and Du 2024; Lecler et al. 2023; Obaid et al. 2023; Saka et al. 2024; Shea and Ma 2023). For these reasons, it is important that future research also targets the continued development of LLMs, including validations of their use within the SCF, though given the recent advances, it is likely that the ability of LLMs to emulate human behavior will only increase with time.

7 Conclusion

This paper sought to answer the research question of whether an LLM-based causal framework could be developed to provide reliable causal inference for instances where the theorized cause were otherwise non-manipulable. This endeavor was motivated by the substantial issues that researchers face when the theorized case is non-manipulable (e.g., Buunk and van Vugt 2013: 17), which prevent them from using the golden standard of Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs, Meldrum 2000) and effectively makes causal inference unreliable due to the possibility of confounding (Fisher 1970; McElreath 2019). While alternative methods have been developed to help mitigate these issues, a review found them to be generally unreliable due to relying on dubious and untestable assumptions that failed to be as reliable as RCTs (Baker et al. 2022; Bertrand et al. 2004; cf. Rohrer 2024; Ryan et al. 2015; Samii 2016; Wan et al. 2024). To mitigate these shortcomings within the social and behavioral sciences, using theory based in linguistics, psychology, and natural language processing, this paper developed the novel Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF). The SCF specifically exploits Large Language Models (LLMs, Shanahan 2024) to emulate human behavior in the form of synthetic units, produced through a synthesis of simulated characteristics randomly sampled in proportion to a population of interest. These synthetic units can be manipulated where humans cannot, thus making an otherwise non-manipulable phenomenon manipulable. Recognizing the limitations of LLMs, an application of the SCF within its intended area of application requires the theorized cause and outcome to be meaningfully expressible through natural language. The concept of parallel worlds-estimation was further introduced to exploit the fact that synthetic units can be independently, simultaneously, and exogenously assigned to an arbitrary number of manipulation conditions, enabling researchers to measure a counterfactual outcome for each type of manipulation. With every synthetic unit being in all manipulation conditions, the SCF ensures perfect balance between the manipulation groups. Being formalized using the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (Imbens and Rubin 2015; Neyman 1923; Rubin 2005), the causal identification strategy enabled by the SCF specifically involves intra-unit comparisons of independently and simultaneously generated couterfactual outcomes, eliminating all unit- and time-invariant confounding by design.

A proof-of-concept and validation of the generalizability of SCF-based results to human populations followed in the form of a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) that sought to replicate the established relationship between deservingness and welfare support (cf. Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019). This demonstration showed how to simulate respondent characteristics jointly proportional to the population of the United States using estimates derived from the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (ANES 2021), making results more representative of that population. It was then shown how to create prompts to generate life-histories (cf. Bertaux 1981) for the simulated respondents, adding extra nuance to the simulated characteristics. This served to make the selected LLM-model, OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini, more capable of realistically imitating the behavior of a person with those traits. An implementation of parallel worlds-estimation was provided, which utilized parallel processing to generate and measure two counterfactual levels of welfare support from exposure to a lazy and unlucky welfare recipient vignette. The replication then proved perfect group balance in terms of the simulated characteristics and tested the simultaneity assumption, finding a partial violation among a small subset of the synthetic respondents, though a subsequent sensitivity analysis (cf. Athey and Imbens 2017: 19-21) revealed that time nonetheless did not confound the results. A multilevel Bayesian statistical model was specified (cf. Brkner 2017, 2018), with a multilevel Frequentist model for robustness (cf. Bates et al. 2015), producing results that closely replicated the human-based results of an effect of deservingness on welfare support. A cost analysis found that the implementation of the SCF was substantively cheaper compared to studies on human samples. As such, this paper managed to successfully develop the SCF, which constitutes a novel causal framework that enables researchers to manipulate an otherwise non-manipulable phenomenon, thus making causal inference derived from this procedure reliable. While the SCF currently shows a promising generalizability to human populations, further validations are needed. Lastly, it should be noted that the SCF does not constitute a substitute for employing RCTs when the theorized cause is manipulable in human populations, and caution is advised if applying the SCF outside of its intended area of application. Development of the SCF is planned in future studies, which are expected to further increase and demonstrate its scientific utility.

10.2 Software Specifications

This document was created on a Windows 10 x64 (build 19045) operating system (OS) on the 2025-03-18 18:51 CET (Timezone: Europe/Copenhagen). The machine has 8 cores available, and the range of doubles is \(2.23e^{-308}\) - \(1.8e^{+308}\).

All code is written in R version 4.4.1 (2024-06-14 ucrt), while the document is written with markdown (Gruber 2014) and LaTeX (Lamport 1986) in the RStudio version 2024.4.2.764, using the R packages knitr (Xie 2024b; v1.47, Xie 2014, 2015), markdown (v1.13, Xie et al. 2024), rmarkdown (Allaire et al. 2024; v2.27, Xie et al. 2018, 2020), and bookdown (Xie 2024a; v0.40, Xie 2016). The code makes extensive use of R packages that are part of the tidyverse (v2.0.0, Wickham et al. 2019), including dplyr (v1.1.4, Wickham et al. 2023a), tidyr (v1.3.1, Wickham et al. 2024a), readr (v2.1.5, Wickham et al. 2024b), stringr (v1.5.1, Wickham 2023), lubridate (v1.9.3, Grolemund and Wickham 2011), and tidytext (v0.4.2, Silge and Robinson 2016). Graphs were produced with ggplot2 (v3.5.1, Wickham 2016), bayesplot (v1.11.1, Gabry et al. 2019), tidybayes (v3.0.6, Kay 2023), dagitty (v0.3.4, Textor et al. 2016), ggdag (v0.2.13, Barrett 2024), latex2exp (v0.9.6, Meschiari 2022), magick (v2.8.3, Ooms 2024a), rsvg (v2.6.1, Ooms 2024b), ggdist (v3.3.2, Kay 2024a; 2024b), and ggpubr (v0.6.0, Kassambara 2023). Calls to OpenAIs API was done with the openai R package (v0.4.1, Rudnytskyi 2023), while the implementation of parallel processing necessary for the parallel worlds-estimation procedure was achieved using the parallel (v4.4.1, R Core Team 2024), doParallel (v1.0.17, Microsoft and Weston 2022a), and foreach (v1.5.2, Microsoft and Weston 2022b) R packages. The seed of SEED for random number generation (RNG) was exogenously determined using the random (v0.2.6, Eddelbuettel 2017) R package, which relies on randomness by random.org. Rater reliability was assessed using caret (v6.0.94, Kuhn 2008) and sklarsomega (v3.0.2, Hughes 2023). Statistical estimation and inference was conducted using the R packages lme4 (v1.1.35.4, Bates et al. 2015), broom.mixed (v0.2.9.6, Bolker and Robinson 2024), fixest (v0.12.1, Berg 2018), mice (v3.16.0, van Buuren and Groothuis-Oudshoorn 2011), howManyImputations (v0.2.5, von Hippel 2020), randomForest (v4.7.1.1, Liaw and Wiener 2002), mgcv (v1.9.1, Wood 2004, 2011, 2017), metafor (v4.6.0, Viechtbauer 2010), brms (v2.21.0, Brkner 2017, 2018), bayestestR (v0.13.2, Makowski et al. 2019a), effectsize (v0.8.9, Ben-Shachar et al. 2020), e1071 (v1.7.14, Meyer et al. 2023), rQCC (Park et al. 2022; v2.22.12, Park and Wang 2020, 2022), HuraultMisc (v1.1.1, Hurault 2021), lsa (v0.73.3, Wild 2022), and summarytools (v1.0.1, Comtois 2022). Data was formatted using the scrutiny (v0.4.0, Jung 2024), weights (v1.0.4, Pasek et al. 2021), scales (v1.3.0, Wickham et al. 2023b), and kableExtra (v1.4.0, Zhu 2024) R packages. Data from the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021) were read and processed using the haven (v2.5.4, Wickham et al. 2023c), labelled (v2.13.0, Larmarange 2024), and sjlabelled (v1.2.0, Ldecke 2022) R packages.

10.3 Meta-Analysis

This section details the meta-analysis conducted on the studies of the effects of deservingness on welfare attitudes by Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023). The specific estimates used for the meta-analysis are provided in table 10.1. Based on McElreath (2019) and Nalborczyk et al. (2019), a formalization of the Bayesian Generalized Linear Model with varying-intercepts used for the meta-analysis is provided in table 10.2. Traceplots for assessing model convergence are provided in figure 10.1. The posterior predictive distribution of the model is provided visually in figure 10.2. The explanatory power of the Bayesian Meta-Analysis model (i.e., Bayesian \(R^2\), Gelman et al. 2019) is provided metrically in table 10.3 and visually in figure 10.3. For the estimated parameters, following Bowley (1910) and Tukey (1910), posterior descriptions are provided as a 13-point summaries. For the estimated fixed/mean intercept (\(\hat{\mu_\alpha}\)), it is provided metrically in table 10.4 and visually in figure 10.4. Similarly, a metric format of the intercept dispersion (\(\hat{\sigma_\alpha}\)) is provided in table 10.5 and visually in figure 10.5. The models estimated degrees of freedom (\(\hat{\nu}\)) is provided metrically in table 10.6 and visually in figure 10.6. When possible and meaningful, the mode, median, mean, interquartile range (IQR), skewness, kurtosis, posterior predictive p-value (\(PP_P\), Gelman et al. 1996), chain convergence (\(\hat{R}\), Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021), effective sample size (ESS, Brkner 2017), and Monte-Carlo Standard Error (MCSE, Kruschke 2014) are listed in the table notes.

10.3.1 Studies

Table 10.1: Studies used in the Meta-Analysis
Study Estimate Sample Size Collection Method
Aare & Petersen (2014) .422 (.030) [.363; .481] 1,009 YouGov
Mummolo & Peterson (2019) .550 (.023) [.505; .595] 1,874 MTurk
Mummolo & Peterson (2019) .457 (.016) [.426; .488] 5,550 Qualtrics
Kane et al.(2023) .583 (.026) [.532; .634] 804 MTurk

NOTE: Normalized coefficients (0 - 1) with robust standard errors in parentheses and 95% confidence intervals in brackets. The estimates listed under Aare and Petersen (2014) were derived from recomputed values by Mummolo and Peterson (2019), provided visually in their Online Appendix (p.21, Figure B6, under Welfare Support Study). Estimates from Mummolo and Peterson (2019) and some by Kane et al. (2023) were only provided visually and were imputed using visual tools by Gross et al. (2014).

10.3.2 Bayesian Meta-Analysis Model

Table 10.2: Bayesian Meta-Analysis Model
\(Y_i \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_\nu(\mu_i, \sigma)\) 1.1
\(\mu_i = \alpha_{study[i]}\) 1.2
\(\alpha_{study} \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_3(\mu_\alpha, \: \sigma_\alpha)\) 1.3
\(\mu_\alpha \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}_3(0, \: .077)\) 1.4
\(\sigma_\alpha \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}^{(0; \infty]}_3(0, \: .077)\) 1.5
\(\nu \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{T}^{(1; 4)}_3(1, \: .077)\) 1.6

NOTE: Bayesian Generalized Linear Model with study-varying intercepts. 1.1 is the likelihood-function, which specifies that the observations of the outcome variable \(Y\) (i.e., welfare support) are assumed to be independent and identically (i.e., iid) distributed as a Student t distribution (Gosset 1908; Helmert 1876a; 1876b; 1875; Lroth 1876; Pearson 1895b), with a mean, dispersion (i.e., residual standard deviation), and degrees of freedom (df) parameters. 1.2 is the affine function (Boyd and Vandenberghe 2018) of the mean parameter, which consists of random (i.e., study-varying) intercepts. 1.3 is the prior for the study-varying intercepts, Student t distributed, with a df of 3, an unknown fixed (i.e., US-level) mean intercept, and an unknown dispersion parameter. 1.4 is the hyper prior for the fixed/mean of the study-varying intercepts, being Student t distributed, with a df of 3, mean of 0, and a dispersion of .077. 1.5 is the hyper prior for the mean dispersion parameter of the study-varying intercepts, being distributed as a non-negative Student t, with a df of 3, mean of 0, and standard deviation of .077. 1.6 is the prior for the df parameter of the model, being distributed as a truncated Student t, with a mean of 1, standard deviation of .077, while the truncation includes values between 1 and 4. Note that no prior for the dispersion of the outcome (i.e., \(\sigma\)) is specified, because the model weighs the estimates from each study based on their estimated standard errors.

10.3.3 Model Diagnostics

Figure 10.1: Chain Convergence of the Bayesian Meta-Analysis Model

NOTE: Traceplot. Total chains = 7, total samples per chain = 7,715, warmup samples per chain = 2,000. Total posterior samples = 40,005. The gray-shaded area indicates the warmup samples. Effective Sample Size (ESS, Brkner 2017) = 5,553, 4,949, and 17,731, respectively. Chain convergence (\(\hat{R}\), Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021) = 1.001, 1.000, and 1.000, respectively. Monte Carlo Standard Error (MCSE, Kruschke 2014) = .002, .001 and .001, respectively. Data for meta-analysis derived from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023).

10.5.2 Simultaneity Test

This section gives an overview of the diagnostics and estimates from the Bayesian Generalized Linear Model (BGLM) used to test the simultaneity assumption (see table 4.8). A traceplot of chain convergence of this model is provided graphically in 10.20. The models goodness-of-fit is provided as a posterior predictive plot in figure 10.21, with explained variance (\(R^2\), cf. Gelman et al. 2019) not being reported due to being entirely invariant. Building on Bowley (1910) and Tukey (1910), a 13-number summary of the estimated mean time difference (\(\hat{\delta}\)) is provided in table 10.20 and visually in figure 10.22, while the estimated dispersion (\(\hat{\varsigma}\)) is provided in table 10.21 and figure 10.23. When possible and meaningful, the mode, median, mean, interquartile range (IQR), skewness, kurtosis, posterior predictive p-value (\(PP_P\), Gelman et al. 1996), chain convergence (\(\hat{R}\), Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021), effective sample size (ESS, Brkner 2017), and Monte-Carlo Standard Error (MCSE, Kruschke 2014) are listed in the table notes.

10.5.3 Deservingness & Welfare Support

This section gives an overview of the diagnostics and estimates of the the Multilevel Bayesian Generalized Linear Model (ML-BGLM) for testing the relationship between deservingness and welfare support (see table 4.10). Building on Bowley (1910) and Tukey (1910), this includes 13-number summaries. A traceplot of chain convergence of this model is provided graphically in 10.24, while the models goodness-of-fit is provided as a posterior predictive distribution in figure 10.25 and as explained variance (\(R^2\), cf. Gelman et al. 2019), metrically in table 10.22 and visually in figure 10.26. The estimated coefficient (\(\hat{\beta_G}\)) is provided metrically in table 10.23 and visually in figure 10.27, while the estimated intercept mean (\(\hat{\mu_\alpha}\)) and dispersion (\(\hat{\sigma_\alpha}\)) are provided in tables 10.24 and 10.25, and in figures 10.28 and 10.29, respectively. The models estimated dispersion parameter (\(\hat{\sigma}\)) is provided in table 10.26 and figure 10.30. The models estimated degrees of freedom (df) parameter (\(\hat{\nu}\)) is provided in table 10.27 and figure 10.31. When possible and meaningful, the mode, median, mean, interquartile range (IQR), skewness, kurtosis, posterior predictive p-value (\(PP_P\), Gelman et al. 1996), chain convergence (\(\hat{R}\), Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021), effective sample size (ESS, Brkner 2017), and Monte-Carlo Standard Error (MCSE, Kruschke 2014) are listed in the table notes.

10.6 Citation

The Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) and its related concepts of parallel worlds-estimation and the Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) are original concepts by Emil Niclas Meyer-Hansen, conceived as part of the authors PhD project proposal for Aarhus University (submitted 2024-9-5). This work serves as the founding paper of these concepts. In their current states, Emil Niclas Meyer-Hansen is the sole author and contributor to their ongoing development, conceptualization, formalization, and implementation. For correspondence, contact the author via email: emil098meyerhansen@gmail.com.

Please, if you use, refer to, and/or continue the development of the SCF and/or SCT, provide proper reference and citation to their founding author. An example of proper citation is provided below:

  • Meyer-Hansen, E. N. (2025): The Synthetic Causal Framework: An LLM-based Solution to the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference. Preview version (Large-N Release): 2025-03-18-18-53, on Open Science Framework. DOI: 10.17605/OSF.IO/5P3M2

For LaTeX users, a BibTeX entry is provided below:
