  1. Independent researcher. Holds a Master of Science (MSc.) and Bachelor of Science (BSc.) in Political Science from Aarhus University, Denmark. Email: emil098meyerhansen@gmail.com

  2. Regarding the notion that no theory can ever be proven correct (Lakatos 1970; Miller 1974; Popper 2002[1959]; see also Dellsn 2024), consistent with Thomas Kuhn (1970; as cited by Farrell 2014: 43), while also emulating Richard McElreath (2019: xiii), it may be boldly argued that all theories are false, but some are useful.

  3. Note that within the Frequentist NHST, a null hypothesis (\(H_0\)) can never be disproven nor proven (i.e., accepted, Gigerenzer 2004; Wagenmakers et al. 2010: 159; Wilkinson and The Task Force on Statistical Inference 1999: 599).

  4. As demonstrated by Google Scholar currently listing 505,000 results for the search query: causal inference.

  5. The 10,278 projects created in 2024 were projects currently registered on the Open Science Framework (OSF) mentioning causal inference, with many more projects likely existing that are not registered on the OSF.

  6. The criterion that causal relationships necessitates physical phenomena serves to exclude metaphysical phenomena, which are generally considered inherently beyond the scope of science (Farrell 2014: 8-10; Hume 1975[1777]: 165; Van Fraassen 2002). Note that the term physical phenomena here includes psychological, sociological, and related socially constructed phenomena (Hacking 1999), at least as long as they in principle are reducible to physical phenomena.

  7. The criterion that causal relationships involves physically distinct phenomena (e.g., \(X \ne Y\)) serves to a priori exclude considerations for the nonetheless interesting concept of self-causing phenomena (i.e., causa sui, Masi 2023).

  8. The notion that causal relationships involve temporally distinct phenomena (e.g., \(X \prec Y\)) serves to a priori exclude concerns for retrocausality (Leifer and Pusey 2017) and mutual causation (Yang et al. 2018), which under some circumstances may have some validity to them (for discussion, see, e.g., Drummond and Reid 2021). Note that this does not exclude feedback causation (Baumeister et al. 2007). For example, suppose two temporally-variable vector phenomena (e.g., \(X_t\) and \(Y_t\), with all \(X_t \ne Y_t\) and all \(X_t \prec Y_t\)), where \(t\) indexes increases in time. At some initial point in time, suppose that \(X_1\) causes \(Y_1\), for example, through a stochastic process (e.g., \(Y_1 = X_1 + \epsilon_1\)). Then, a later time point, \(Y_1\) causes \(X_2\) in a similar process (e.g., \(X_2 = Y_1 + X_1 + \epsilon_2\)). Such feedback causation are not excluded from consideration here.

  9. Note that this definition of a cause is intentionally simplified to mostly include sufficient, probabilistic, and contrary-to-fact causes (Seawright 2002). As such, it deliberately ignores valid considerations of more complex causes, such as INUS causes (Mackie 1980).

  10. As an extended consideration to causal effects possibly being heterogenous conditional on \(X\), it should be noted that heterogeneity can extend to the specific level of \(C\) held constant. For example, if subsets of \(C\) interact with the \(D\) conditional on \(X\). However, with a sample representative of the population of interest as achieved with random sampling (see below), this does not bias causal inference, and notation to account for this scenario is thus not considered here.

  11. For example, suppose that researchers posit a causal relationship between height and age. They conduct a study where they first measure the height of subjects followed by then asking them their age. The researchers run a model and find that an increase in height is associated with an increase in age. Instead of considering the possibility of reverse causality, i.e., that increases in age causes increases in height, they argue that this is impossible, because they measured height prior to age. Such an argument would be nonsensical, precisely because both height and age exist prior to their measurement.

  12. Note that a masking effect may alternatively be denoted a suppression effect (cf. Lenz and Sahn 2021).

  13. This is an emphasized criticism specifically targeting flawed definitions of causality, such as one currently made by Merriam-Webster, who include a definition of causality as the relation [] between regularly correlated events or phenomena. Since correlated events or phenomena, in principle, can be just as regularly confounded, this is an example of a cum hoc ergo propter hoc logical fallacy (Manninen 2019c), and the definition is erroneous and promotes an unreliable conceptualization of causality.

  14. As an extension of the statement correlation does not imply causation, Professor of Statistics at Columbia University, Andrew Gelman, has stated that correlation does not even imply correlation. For an interesting and alternative view specific to quantum mechanics, see, e.g., Fitzsimons et al. (2015).

  15. As a response to criticisms of this statement by Kenneth A. Bollen and Judea Pearl (2013: 312-313; see also Bollen 1989: 41; Goldthorpe 2001: 15; Bhrolchin and Dyson 2007: 3), it should be clarified that the statement no causation without manipulation by Paul W. Holland and Donald Rubin (Holland 1986: 959) does not make the ontological claim (cf. Jacquette 1976) that causal effects cannot occur without manipulation, since causal effects undoubtedly occur all the time without human intervention, of which both Paul W. Holland and Donald Rubin are likely aware. Instead, it makes the epistemological claim (cf. Rosenberg 2016: 2) that we cannot reliably identify a causal effect without a manipulation. Furthermore, this manipulation does not necessarily require human intervention, for example, a natural experiment (Dunning 2008) could qualify, and if the assumptions for alternative strategies do hold, reliable causal inference can indeed be drawn in quasi-experiments (Angrist and Pischke 2009: 113). But for non-manipulated settings this merely begs the question (Rivera 2019) of how researchers can credibly assess whether assumptions outside of their control have been violated. As such, the statement no causation without manipulation (Holland 1986: 959) serves to outline the premise for the scientific method on how to draw epistemologically reliable causal inference.

  16. Multilevel models can be implemented in standard statistical software. For R (R Core Team 2024), Bayesian multilevel models can be implemented using, for example, brms (Brkner 2017, 2018) and rstanarm (Goodrich et al. 2024), while Frequentist versions are provided in, e.g., the lme4 package (Bates et al. 2015). For Stata (StataCorp 2023), Bayesian and Frequentist multilevel models are provided as standard features.

  17. In Aare and Petersen (2014), the wording of the lazy welfare recipient vignette is: Imagine a man who is currently on social welfare. He has always had a regular job, but has now been the victim of a work-related injury. He is very motivated to get back to work again (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689). Wording of the unlucky welfare recipient is Imagine a man who is currently on social welfare. He has never had a regular job, but he is fit and healthy. He is not motivated to get a job (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689). Wording of the control welfare recipient is Imagine a man who is currently on social welfare (Aare and Petersen 2014: 689).

  18. The term statistically discernible is explicitly used as a more appropriate term compared to the conventional term of statistical significance (cf. McShane et al. 2019).

  19. In relation to the results of the effect of deservingness of welfare support derived from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023), it should be noted that the reported statistical models from which the estimates were derived were not identically specified. For example, Kane et al. (2023) only report results from models including attentiveness-interaction terms, where the results derived from the most attentive respondents were used due to being arguably most reliable. Note also that some estimates (e.g., means, standard errors, and confidence intervals) are less reliable because they had to be derived using informed approximations (e.g., estimating the standard error by knowing that the mean and 95% confidence intervals) or tool-assisted eyeballing (Gross et al. 2014) because the study (e.g., Mummolo and Peterson 2019) only reported the relevant results visually. Note that the meta-analysis of a previous version of this paper used results derived from the incorrect graphs, leading to underestimated estimates.

  20. While the assumption of prior odds of 1 fits with the Frequentist notion of unbiasedness by being entirely noninformative, it arguably assigns too much relative weight to the hypothesis of no effect, since researchers often find a null hypothesis of exactly no effect to be highly unlikely a priori (e.g., Gelman et al. 2021: 59-60). This is similarly expressed by Meehls (1978) conjecture that in some settings the null hypothesis is always false (Gigerenzer 2004: 600-602). Assuming prior odds of 1 is thus arguably too conservative, because it results in an underestimation of the actual posterior odds, but this merely produces a bias against the researchers (alternative) hypothesis by reducing the statistical power of their study.

  21. Ethnoracial group is a term used to denote the overlapping racial/ethnic/national terminology employed in the US (e.g., White, African-American, Chinese, etc.).

  22. The level of shared information between the simulated sample and the population was estimated by a novel application of cosine similarity (Kozlowski et al. 2019: 910-911; Mikolov et al. 2013: 5). Analogous to computational text analysis (Theocharis and Jungherr 2021), this exploits the fact that cosine similarity is derivable from Token Frequency Documents (TDF, e.g., Rheault and Cochrane 2020; Rodriguez et al. 2023a: 6; Rodriguez et al. 2023b: 5), which can be reconceptualized as an Information Frequency Matrix (IFM) that reflects the frequency of values (i.e., information) occurring in the sample and population. With cosine similarity being scaled 0 - 1 in such instances, cosine similarity here reflects the shared information between the sample and population.

  23. With respect to the statement that intra-unit comparisons eliminates all unit-invariant confounders, it should be added that this does not guarantee the elimination of numerous types of errors (e.g., systematic measurement error, Bandalos 2018) and biases (e.g., social desirability bias, Edwards 1953; Krumpal 2013) that may also make results invalid and unreliable.

  24. The expectation that differences in character length or word length of the manipulations could violate the simultaneity assumption is in part based on simultaneity tests suggesting this, as ascertained in a pilot study used in a previous versions of this study.

  25. The rephrasing of the welfare recipient vignettes used by Aare and Petersen (2014) and Petersen et al. (2012) so that they were of equal word length and character length relied on ChatGPT (OpenAI 2022). To ensure that phrasings were meaningful and did not change the substantive meaning of the original vignettes, the phrasings were compared and validated by the author.

  26. Note that the prompts for generating counterfactual outcomes in a previous version of this paper incorrectly specified a 5-point Likert (1932) scale instead of the correct 7-point Likert scale.

  27. A previous version of this paper followed a procedure Hartman and Hidalgo (2018), that, while arguably an improvement on the Null-Hypothesis Significance Testing (NHST) framework, unfortunately were difficult to implement in a Bayesian framework given current software limitations, with the author having to rely on transformations of data that made it improper for a linear model specification, resulting in convergence issues. Once Bayesian software packages has been updated to allow bimodal priors, the suggestions by Hartman and Hidalgo (2018) will be more reliably implementable.

  28. While modeling the likelihood as a Student t distribution (Gosset 1908; Helmert 1876a; 1876b; 1875; Lroth 1876; Pearson 1895b) would have been preferable compared to a Gaussian (Gauss 2012[1809]) for robustness (Gelman et al. 2021: 264-286; McElreath 2019: 233-234; OHagan 1979), inspections of model convergence using convergence metrics and traceplots found that this choice resulted in failed convergence (\(\hat{R} \ge 1.1\), Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021).

  29. Inconsequential exceptions to this are the dispersion parameter (\(\sigma\)) and intercept dispersion parameter (\(\sigma_\alpha\)), where Bayesian estimates compared to likelihood-estimates were found to be different with 95% credibility, indicating that priors are informative relative to the data. For the dispersion parameter (\(\sigma\)), the posterior was specifically credibly higher than the likelihood, though higher estimates are a desirable property for the dispersion parameter, because it makes the Bayesian estimates more conservative. For the intercept dispersion parameter (\(\sigma_\alpha\)), the posterior was credibly lower than the likelihood, and the Frequentist estimates are here more conservative than the Bayesian estimates.

  30. The fundamental concept underlying the SCF, SCT, and Parallel Worlds-estimation were conceptualized by Emil Meyer-Hansen no later than March 3rd, 2024, prior to knowing about similar concepts involving the use of LLMs for experimental research purposes, for example, Hewitt et al. (2024), which the author was first made aware of on January 6th, 2025.
